/** Etymology data for lemma IDs in chunk 8 */
export const etymologyChunk8: Record<number, string> = {
  "3833": "مُمِدٌّ and related words stem from the root م-د-د, with the root verb مَدَّ meaning \"he extended,\" \"he supplied,\" or \"he prolonged.\" مُمِدٌّ means \"one who supplies,\" \"provider,\" or \"one who extends.\" It reflects the root’s essence of increasing, expanding, or augmenting, with مُمِدٌّ focusing on the active role of the supplier or provider. This term highlights the act of extending resources, support, or reinforcements, emphasizing the source of provision and its active nature in sustaining or enhancing what is already present, whether physically or metaphorically.",
  "3834": "مُمْتَرِينَ and related words stem from the root م-ر-ي, with the root verb مَارَىٰ meaning \"he disputed,\" and امْتَرَىٰ meaning \"he doubted\" or \"he was skeptical.\" مُمْتَرِينَ means \"doubters\" or \"those who are in doubt.\" The root reflects questioning, hesitation, and uncertainty, often linked to a lack of clarity or conviction. مُمْتَرِينَ embodies persistent skepticism, extending beyond occasional doubt to an ongoing state of intellectual or emotional turmoil. It also implies disputation, as doubt often drives individuals to challenge or argue against perceived uncertainties or truths.",
  "3835": "مُمْسِكٌ and related words stem from the root م-س-ك, with the root verb مَسَكَ meaning \"he held,\" \"he grasped,\" or \"he seized.\" مُمْسِكٌ means \"withholder\" or \"one who restrains.\" The connection lies in embodying the act of holding back, reflecting the root's core concept of grasping. This term conveys themes of control and limitation, highlighting the power to prevent or withhold, whether in a physical, emotional, or metaphorical sense.",
  "3836": "مُمْسِكَاتُ and related words stem from the root م-س-ك, with the root verb مَسَكَ meaning \"he held\" or \"he withheld.\" مُمْسِكَاتُ means \"withholders.\" The connection lies in the act of holding back or retaining, reflecting the root's core idea of grasping. This term often refers to those who withhold or restrain, embodying the concept of control and limitation. In various contexts, it can denote individuals or forces that prevent or restrict, highlighting the dynamics of power and submission.",
  "3837": "مُمْطِرٌ and related words stem from the root م-ط-ر, with the root verb مَطَرَ meaning \"it rained.\" مُمْطِرٌ means \"one who causes rain\" or \"bringing rain.\" The connection highlights the agent or cause of rain, directly relating to the root's focus on the act of raining. It reflects the role of rain-bringers, symbolizing forces that bring nourishment or, metaphorically, significant change.",
  "3838": "مُنَادِ and related words stem from the root ن-د-ي, with the root verb نَدَا meaning \"he called,\" \"he proclaimed,\" or \"he invited.\" مُنَادِ means \"the caller\" or \"the one who calls,\" referring to someone regularly engaged in calling or summoning others. It emphasizes the role of a person who actively initiates communication to gather or inform others. The root conveys calling, summoning, and gathering through vocal means, and مُنَادِ embodies this by representing someone who consistently unites or addresses others through vocal outreach.",
  "3839": "مُنَادِيًا and related words stem from the root ن-د-ي, with the root verb نَدَا meaning \"he called,\" \"he proclaimed,\" or \"he invited.\" مُنَادِيًا means \"caller\" or \"one who calls\" and refers to someone actively engaged in the act of calling in a specific moment or context. It emphasizes the action of summoning or announcing to others. The root highlights vocal communication and assembling people, with مُنَادِيًا focusing on the immediate act of calling to connect individuals or convey messages dynamically.",
  "3840": "مُنَافِقِينَ and related words stem from the root ن-ف-ق, with the root verb نَفَقَ meaning \"he tunneled\" or \"he made an underground passage,\" and the derived verb نَافَقَ meaning \"he acted hypocritically.\" مُنَافِقِينَ means \"hypocrites\" and refers to those who outwardly display faith but inwardly conceal disbelief or deceit. The connection lies in the root's concept of concealment and duality, akin to how a tunnel provides hidden pathways, symbolizing duplicity. This term emphasizes the deceitful nature of hypocrisy, where actions and intentions are misaligned, reflecting the root’s focus on hidden realities.",
  "3841": "مُنَافِقَاتِ and related words stem from the root ن-ف-ق, with the root verb نَفَقَ meaning \"he tunneled\" or \"he made an underground passage,\" and the derived verb نَافَقَ meaning \"he acted hypocritically.\" مُنَافِقَاتِ means \"female hypocrites\" and refers to women who conceal their true beliefs or intentions behind a façade of outward righteousness. The connection lies in the tunnel's nature as a hidden passage, symbolizing the concealment and deception inherent in hypocrisy. Just as a tunnel obscures what lies within, hypocrisy involves presenting a false appearance while hiding the reality, reflecting the root’s focus on secrecy and duality.",
  "3842": "مُنبَثٌّ and related words stem from the root ب-ث-ث, with the root verb بَثَّ meaning \"he scattered\" or \"he dispersed.\" اِنۢبَثَّ translates as \"it spread,\" \"it became dispersed,\" or \"it was scattered.\" مُنبَثٌّ means \"spread out,\" describing something widely scattered or dispersed across an area, often with a sense of reaching or filling space. The distinction between بَثَّ (an active scattering) and اِنۢبَثَّ (a passive, natural spreading) adds nuance to مُنبَثٌّ, which implies something that has been naturally or widely dispersed, often filling a given space or area.",
  "3843": "مُنتَشِرٌ and related words stem from the root ن-ش-ر, with the root verb نَشَرَ meaning \"he spread out,\" \"he unfolded,\" or \"he expanded.\" مُنتَشِرٌ means \"one who is dispersed,\" \"spreading,\" or \"actively dispersing.\" The root conveys themes of expansion, movement, and distribution. مُنتَشِرٌ emphasizes the active state of dispersing from a central point or being spread across a space, often associated with living beings, objects, or forces that move dynamically. This term highlights the natural flow and proliferation of entities, embodying the root’s focus on the transition from confinement to openness and widespread activity, reflecting dynamic and purposeful dispersal.",
  "3844": "مُنتَصِرٌ and related words stem from the root ن-ص-ر, with the root verb نَصَرَ meaning \"he helped.\" مُنتَصِرٌ means \"one who defends himself\" or \"one who is victorious,\" focusing on actively securing triumph through effort or self-defense. The connection lies in achieving victory through one’s initiative, reflecting the root’s emphasis on support, whether external or self-driven. مُنتَصِرٌ highlights personal strength and determination in securing success, aligning with the broader themes of triumph and resilience inherent in the root.",
  "3845": "مُنْتَظِرُونَ and related words stem from the root ن-ظ-ر, with the root verb نَظَرَ meaning \"he looked,\" \"he observed,\" or \"he considered.\" انْتَظَرَ means \"he waited\" or \"he anticipated,\" carrying the sense of attentive observation while awaiting an event or outcome. مُنْتَظِرُونَ means \"ones who wait\" or \"ones who are waiting,\" emphasizing the state of expectation with awareness. The connection lies in looking forward to something with anticipation and readiness, reflecting patience and foresight. The root's concept of observation extends to waiting attentively, highlighting the importance of mindfulness, preparation, and perseverance in anticipating outcomes or decisions.",
  "3846": "مُنْتَقِمُونَ and related words stem from the root ن-ق-م, with the root verb نَقَمَ meaning \"he resented\" or \"he avenged,\" and انْتَقَمَ meaning \"he took retribution.\" مُنْتَقِمُونَ means \"Ones who takes retribution\" reflecting the act of enacting justice against wrongdoing. ٱلْمُنْتَقِمُ, one of Allah's (ﷻ) perfect names, means \"The Avenger,\" highlighting His role in holding wrongdoers accountable and exacting justice. This name signifies Allah’s (ﷻ) perfect justice, ensuring that all oppression and transgression are met with appropriate retribution, emphasizing His authority and the balance of divine justice.",
  "3847": "مُنْتَهُونَ and related words stem from the root ن-ه-ى, with the root verb نَهَى meaning \"he forbade\" or \"he prohibited.\" مُنْتَهُونَ means \"those who desist\" or \"those who refrain,\" referring to individuals who cease from prohibited or wrongful actions. The term reflects the root's emphasis on restraint and self-control, highlighting the moral quality of abandoning what is forbidden. مُنْتَهُونَ highlights the value of self-discipline and responsiveness to guidance, emphasizing the importance of aligning actions with ethical and spiritual principles.",
  "3848": "مُنذَرٌ and related words stem from the root ن-ذ-ر, with the root verb نَذَرَ meaning \"he warned\" or \"he vowed.\" مُنذَرٌ is a passive form meaning \"one who is warned,\" referring to a person who has been cautioned about potential dangers. The root conveys themes of warnings and solemn commitments, with مُنذَرٌ emphasizing the state of being alerted to possible consequences. It highlights the responsibility to heed warnings, reflecting the root's focus on awareness and accountability.",
  "3849": "مُنذِرٌ and related words stem from the root ن-ذ-ر, with the root verb نَذَرَ meaning \"he warned\" or \"he vowed.\" This root conveys the act of warning others and making solemn commitments. مُنذِرٌ means \"warner\" or \"one who warns.\" It represents someone who cautions others about impending dangers or consequences. The connection lies in the root's focus on the serious act of warning. مُنذِرٌ embodies the role of an individual who takes on the responsibility to alert others, reflecting the root's essence by emphasizing the moral duty to guide and protect through warnings.",
  "3850": "مُنْزَلٌ and related words stem from the root ن-ز-ل, with the root verb نَزَلَ meaning \"he descended\" or \"he settled.\" مُنْزَلٌ means \"place of descent\" or \"place of settlement,\" referring to a location where something descends or settles by design. In the form مُنْزَلِينَ, it refers to \"those caused to descend,\" highlighting beings or entities intentionally brought down. The connection to the root emphasizes the notion of controlled descent or purposeful arrival, whether referring to physical places or divinely guided events. This word encapsulates themes of order, intentionality, and divine will, reflecting the deliberate nature of descent and settlement in various contexts.",
  "3851": "مُنْزِلِينَ and related words stem from the root ن-ز-ل, with the root verb نَزَلَ meaning \"he descended\" or \"he came down.\" مُنْزِلِينَ means \"ones who bring down\" or \"ones who reveal,\" emphasizing deliberate and purposeful descent, often associated with divine or authoritative actions. The term also extends to mean \"facilitator of settlement,\" ensuring safe descent or placement, or \"host,\" one who provides for and accommodates others. These meanings reflect the root’s versatility in expressing intentional and precise acts of bringing down, settling, or welcoming.",
  "3852": "مُنْشَآتٌ and related words stem from the root ن-ش-أ, with the root verb نَشَأَ meaning \"he grew up\" or \"he arose.\" مُنْشَآتٌ (plural of مُنْشَأَةٌ) means \"constructed structures,\" \"built entities,\" or \"elevated sails.\" The root emphasizes elevation, creation, and formation, directly relating to things raised or established. مُنْشَآتٌ embodies both physical elevation, as in ships with raised sails, and metaphorical establishment, as in structures created with purpose and order. This term connects the root’s themes of rising and construction, highlighting the deliberate act of forming something significant.",
  "3853": "مُنشَرِينَ and related words stem from the root ن-ش-ر, with the root verb نَشَرَ meaning \"he revived,\" \"he resurrected,\" or \"he restored.\" مُنشَرِينَ means \"resurrected\" or \"those who are brought back to life.\" The root conveys the act of bringing something that was lifeless back to vitality or existence. In Qur'anic contexts, مُنشَرِينَ emphasizes the transformative power of resurrection, linking to the idea of being raised after death for accountability. This term reflects themes of divine authority, renewal, and the ultimate reality of life after death.",
  "3854": "مُنْشِئُونَ and related words stem from the root ن-ش-أ, with the root verb نَشَأَ meaning \"he originated,\" \"he grew,\" or \"he began.\" مُنْشِئُونَ means \"producers,\" \"originators,\" or \"creators.\" The root conveys the essence of initiation, where something is brought into existence through purposeful action. This term emphasizes the role of those who actively initiate processes, highlighting the connection between origination and the development of complex systems or creations. The act of \"bringing forth\" aligns with the root’s focus on generating new beginnings and fostering growth.",
  "3855": "مُنْظَرِينَ and related words stem from the root ن-ظ-ر, with the root verb نَظَرَ meaning \"he looked,\" \"he observed,\" or \"he considered.\" أَنْظَرَ means \"he gave respite\" or \"he delayed,\" signifying the act of granting time or postponing an event. مُنْظَرِينَ is a passive participle meaning \"ones who are given respite\" or \"ones who are delayed,\" denoting those granted additional time or deferred from immediate consequences. The connection lies in the root's themes of consideration and time, reflecting mercy and the opportunity for reflection or rectification during the granted delay. This highlights the balance between the privilege of additional time and the responsibility to use it wisely.",
  "3856": "مُنْفَطِرٌ and related words stem from the root ف-ط-ر, with the root verb فَطَرَ meaning \"he cleft\" or \"he split.\" مُنْفَطِرٌ is a passive form meaning \"split asunder\" or \"cleft.\" The connection lies in the state of being broken apart, reflecting the root's emphasis on cleaving. This term is used to describe the sky or heavens being split apart on the Day of Judgment, emphasizing the dramatic changes that will occur.",
  "3857": "مُنْفَكِّينَ and related words stem from the root ف-ك-ك, with the root verb فَكَّ meaning \"he separated,\" \"he untied,\" or \"he loosened.\" مُنْفَكِّينَ means \"those who separate\" or \"those who are removed,\" referring to individuals who are no longer attached or who have broken away from something. The root conveys themes of disconnection, release, or liberation, and مُنْفَكِّينَ highlights a state of detachment or cessation. This term can emphasize the breaking of bonds or the ending of a prior state of connection, reflecting the broader idea of separation, whether physical, metaphorical, or ideological.",
  "3858": "مُنْفِقِينَ and related words stem from the root ن-ف-ق, with the root verb نَفَقَ meaning \"it expired\" or \"it was depleted,\" and the derived verb أَنْفَقَ meaning \"he spent.\" مُنْفِقِينَ means \"those who spend\" and refers to individuals who actively use their wealth for charitable purposes or in the service of others. The connection lies in the act of willingly diminishing one's resources through spending, reflecting the root’s notion of depletion. This term highlights the virtue of generosity, emphasizing the noble act of expending wealth to support others and uphold social welfare.",
  "3859": "مُنْقَعِرٌ and related words stem from the root ق-ع-ر, with the root verb قَعَرَ meaning \"he hollowed out,\" \"he uprooted,\" or \"he dug deeply.\" مُنْقَعِرٌ means \"uprooted\" or \"plucked out from the roots,\" emphasizing the act of complete removal from a deep foundation. The connection lies in the thorough and forceful extraction of something, often leaving behind emptiness or a hollow. Uprooting, whether literal or metaphorical, exposes and disconnects, symbolizing both vulnerability and eradication. The root highlights themes of destruction, excavation, and severance from origins, reflecting its depth and intensity.",
  "3860": "مُنْقَلَبٌ and related words stem from the root ق-ل-ب, with the root verb قَلَبَ meaning \"he turned over,\" \"he inverted,\" or \"he changed.\" مُنْقَلَبٌ refers to \"a return,\" \"a place of return,\" or \"a point of reversal,\" emphasizing the destination or outcome of a process of turning or transformation. This reflects the root’s focus on movement and transition, often pointing to the result or consequence of prior actions. It highlights the inevitability of returning or arriving at a specific state, highlighting the cyclical nature of outcomes and transformations.",
  "3861": "مُنْقَلِبُونَ and related words stem from the root ق-ل-ب, with the root verb قَلَبَ meaning \"he turned over,\" \"he inverted,\" or \"he changed.\" مُنْقَلِبُونَ means \"those who return\" or \"returning ones.\" In the context of returning to Allah (ﷻ), it highlights the inevitability of the transition or journey back to Him. This aligns with the root’s emphasis on movement and reversal, highlighting the idea of a destined and unalterable return to the origin or ultimate accountability.",
  "3862": "مُنْكَرٌ and related words stem from the root ن-ك-ر, with the root verb نَكِرَ meaning \"he did not know,\" \"he found strange,\" or \"he disowned.\" The root conveys ideas of unfamiliarity, rejection, and disapproval. مُنْكَرٌ means \"that which is denied,\" \"reprehensible,\" or \"unrecognizable,\" referring to actions or things deemed objectionable because they deviate from what is morally or socially accepted. The connection lies in the rejection or disapproval of what is perceived as strange, improper, or contrary to established norms, reflecting the root’s emphasis on unfamiliarity and denial.",
  "3863": "مُنْكِرَةٌ and related words stem from the root ن-ك-ر, with the root verb نَكِرَ meaning \"he did not know,\" \"he found strange,\" or \"he disowned.\" The root conveys themes of unfamiliarity, rejection, and denial. مُنْكِرَةٌ means \"one who denies\" or \"a female denier\" and can also describe something \"strange\" or \"unfamiliar\" when referring to feminine nouns. The connection lies in representing a feminine entity or concept that rejects or objects to something perceived as strange, reflecting the root’s focus on unfamiliarity leading to denial or disapproval.",
  "3864": "مُنَجٌّ and related words stem from the root ن-ج-و, with the root verb نَجَا meaning \"he became safe\" or \"he escaped.\" مُنَجٌّ means \"savior\" or \"one who saves,\" referring to someone or an entity actively delivering others from harm or danger. The connection lies in the act of providing rescue and protection, emphasizing themes of mercy, support, and aid. This term reflects the idea of intervention to remove someone from peril or difficulty, symbolizing the compassion and responsibility inherent in acts of saving.",
  "3865": "مُنَزَّلٌ and related words stem from the root ن-ز-ل, with the root verb نَزَلَ meaning \"he descended.\" نَزَّلَ is an intensified form meaning \"he sent down gradually\" or \"he revealed,\" highlighting a progressive and deliberate process. مُنَزَّلٌ is a passive form meaning \"that which is sent down gradually\" or \"revealed,\" emphasizing a methodical descent, such as divine revelation or guidance delivered in stages. This reflects the root’s concept of measured and purposeful transmission, often tied to the idea of wisdom and timing in what is revealed.",
  "3866": "مُنَزِّلٌ and related words stem from the root ن-ز-ل, with the root verb نَزَلَ meaning \"he descended.\" نَزَّلَ is an intensified form meaning \"he sent down gradually\" or \"he revealed.\" مُنَزِّلٌ means \"one who sends down\" or \"revealer,\" describing the entity responsible for controlled and deliberate descent. This aligns with the root’s emphasis on intentional action, often reflecting the divine act of revealing guidance or sending blessings in an orderly and measured way.",
  "3867": "مُنَشَّرَةٌ and related words stem from the root ن-ش-ر, with the root verb نَشَرَ meaning \"he spread out,\" \"he unfolded,\" or \"he opened.\" مُنَشَّرَةٌ means \"spread out,\" \"laid open,\" or \"dispersed.\" The root conveys themes of making something accessible, manifest, or widely distributed, emphasizing the act of bringing something into a visible or open state. This reflects the concept of taking what is enclosed, hidden, or compact and rendering it expansive.",
  "3868": "مُنِيبٌ and related words stem from the root ن-و-ب, with the root verb نَابَ meaning \"he returned\" or \"he turned back,\" particularly to Allah (ﷻ) in repentance. مُنِيبٌ means \"one who turns in repentance\" or \"one who returns to God,\" emphasizing a consistent and sincere effort to seek Allah’s (ﷻ) guidance. The root reflects themes of renewal, humility, and transformation, with مُنِيبٌ representing someone who turns away from error and persistently seeks closeness to Allah (ﷻ) through repentance, submission, and devotion.",
  "3869": "مُنِيرٌ and related words stem from the root ن-و-ر, with the root verb نَوَّرَ meaning \"he or it illuminated\" or \"he or it enlightened.\" مُنِيرٌ means \"illuminating\" or \"luminous,\" referring to something that provides light or clarity. The root conveys themes of brightness, guidance, and the removal of darkness, whether physical or metaphorical. The connection lies in the act of dispelling obscurity and bringing understanding or clarity. This term emphasizes the transformative power of light as a source of guidance, symbolizing the enlightenment achieved through knowledge, truth, and Allah’s (ﷻ) guidance, which illuminate the path to righteousness and understanding.",
  "3870": "مُنْخَنِقَةٌ and related words stem from the root خ-ن-ق, with the root verb خَنَقَ meaning \"he strangled\" or \"he choked.\" The root revolves around choking, constriction, and restriction, conveying the idea of cutting off breath, tightening, or limiting movement. مُنْخَنِقَةٌ means \"that which is strangled,\" referring to animals that have died through strangulation and are therefore unlawful to consume. The connection to the root highlights the unnatural cutting off of life, aligning with the prohibition against consuming such animals as a reminder to uphold purity, compassion, and lawful sustenance.",
  "3871": "مُنْهَمِرٌ and related words stem from the root ه-م-ر, with the root verb هَمَرَ meaning \"it poured forth.\" مُنْهَمِرٌ means \"pouring\" or \"gushing forth.\" The connection lies in depicting something that flows continuously and copiously, like heavy rain or tears, directly relating to the root's emphasis on abundant outpouring. This term highlights the overwhelming and unstoppable nature of such a flow.",
  "3872": "مُهَاجِرٌ and related words stem from the root ه-ج-ر, with the root verb هَجَرَ meaning \"he forsook,\" \"he abandoned,\" or \"he shunned.\" Derived from هَاجَرَ meaning \"he emigrated\" or \"he migrated,\" مُهَاجِرٌ means \"one who emigrates\" or \"an emigrant.\" The connection lies in the act of leaving one's homeland, embodying the root's essence of forsaking familiar surroundings for a greater purpose. It highlights themes of sacrifice, transition, and the pursuit of a noble cause, resonating deeply with the concept of purposeful departure.",
  "3873": "مُهَاجِرَاتٍ and related words stem from the root ه-ج-ر, with the root verb هَجَرَ meaning \"he forsook,\" \"he abandoned,\" or \"he shunned.\" مُهَاجِرَاتٍ means \"female emigrants.\" This term reflects the root's concept by representing a woman who leaves her home or homeland, emphasizing the courage and resolve required to forsake the familiar. It highlights themes of sacrifice and determination inherent in the root, highlighting the personal journey toward a significant goal.",
  "3874": "مُهَانٌ and related words stem from the root ه-و-ن, with the root verb هَانَ meaning \"he was despised\" or \"he became insignificant.\" مُهَانٌ is a passive form meaning \"humiliated\" or \"dishonored.\" The connection lies in the state of being subjected to degradation or contempt, directly relating to the root’s focus on lowness and shame. This term highlights the condition of one who has been stripped of dignity and treated with disrespect.",
  "3875": "مُهَيْمِنٌ and related words stem from the root ه-ي-م-ن, with the root verb هَيْمَنَ meaning \"he oversaw\" or \"he protected.\" مُهَيْمِنٌ means \"guardian,\" \"protector,\" or \"watcher,\" emphasizing active oversight and care. The root conveys themes of authority, guardianship, and vigilant observation, including safeguarding and bearing witness. الْمُهَيْمِنُ, one of Allah’s (ﷻ) perfect names, means \"The Overseer,\" reflecting His complete awareness, protection, and preservation of all creation with unmatched authority and care.",
  "3876": "مُهِينٌ and related words stem from the root ه-و-ن, with the root verb هَانَ meaning \"he was despised\" or \"he became insignificant.\" مُهِينٌ means \"humiliating\" or \"degrading.\" The connection lies in actions or qualities that cause the person exhibiting them to be dishonored, directly aligning with the root’s emphasis on bringing about lowness. This term characterizes behaviors or attributes that result in one’s own belittlement.",
  "3877": "مُهْتَدٍ and related words stem from the root ه-د-ي, with the root verb هَدَىٰ meaning \"he guided\" or \"he led aright.\" Derived from اهْتَدَىٰ meaning \"he was guided,\" مُهْتَدٍ means \"one who is guided.\" This term reflects a person who has actively embraced guidance and is now on the correct path. It emphasizes the transformative state of receiving direction and aligning oneself with truth and righteousness. The use of مُهْتَدٍ suggests a focus on the individual’s reception and adherence to guidance, highlighting the personal impact of being directed toward moral clarity and spiritual growth.",
  "3878": "مُهْتَدِينَ and related words stem from the root ه-د-ي, with the root verb هَدَىٰ meaning \"he guided\" or \"he led aright.\" Derived from اهْتَدَىٰ meaning \"he was guided,\" مُهْتَدِينَ means \"ones who are guided,\" referring to a group or collective. This term conveys the shared experience of being on the correct path, emphasizing communal guidance and collective adherence to righteousness.",
  "3879": "مُهْتَدِي and related words stem from the root ه-د-ي, with the root verb هَدَىٰ meaning \"he guided\" or \"he led aright.\" Derived from اهْتَدَىٰ meaning \"he was guided,\" مُهْتَدِي means \"the guided one\" and emphasizes the idea of ongoing and active guidance. Unlike مُهْتَدٍ, which focuses on the state of having received guidance, مُهْتَدِي suggests a continuous process of adhering to and seeking guidance. This term reflects perseverance and dedication in following the right path, highlighting the sustained and active role of guidance in shaping one’s journey toward truth and moral uprightness.",
  "3880": "مُهْطِعِينَ and related words stem from the root ه-ط-ع, with the root verb هَطَعَ meaning \"he hastened\" or \"he hurried,\" and أَهْطَعَ meaning \"he hastened\" or \"he gazed intently,\" with an added nuance of deliberate focus, submission, or attentiveness. مُهْطِعِينَ means \"those who rush\" or \"those who hasten,\" emphasizing urgency and rapid movement, driven by fear, submission, or intense focus. The root reflects themes of swift action and attentiveness, portraying individuals compelled by an overpowering need or urgency. This term encapsulates the interplay of movement, intent, and submission inherent in the root’s meanings.",
  "3881": "مُهْلٌ and related words stem from the root م-ه-ل, with the root verb مَهَلَ meaning \"he delayed\" or \"he was gentle.\" مُهْلٌ means \"molten metal\" or \"thick liquid.\" The connection may lie in the slow-moving nature of molten substances, reflecting the root's concept of slowness or deliberation.",
  "3882": "مُهْلَكِينَ and related words stem from the root ه-ل-ك, with the root verb هَلَكَ meaning \"he perished,\" \"he died,\" or \"he was destroyed.\" مُهْلَكِينَ means \"those who are destroyed\" or \"those doomed to destruction.\" The nuance lies in the external nature of the destruction, where the individuals are subjected to ruin by an external force or decree. It reflects themes of inevitable and often sudden ruin, emphasizing a state of helplessness and the inevitability of demise as determined by circumstances beyond one's control. The term highlights the fragility of existence and the consequences of actions that lead to destruction.",
  "3883": "مُهْلِكٌ and related words stem from the root ه-ل-ك, with the root verb هَلَكَ meaning \"he perished,\" \"he died,\" or \"he was destroyed.\" مُهْلِكٌ means \"destroyer\" or \"one who causes destruction.\" The term emphasizes an external agent actively responsible for bringing about ruin or demise, aligning with the root's focus on destruction and loss. It reflects themes of annihilation and intentional harm, highlighting the role of deliberate action in causing irreversible damage or the end of existence. This term serves as a reminder of the grave consequences of actions that lead to ruin, whether physical, moral, or societal.",
  "3884": "مُهْلِكِي and related words stem from the root ه-ل-ك, with the root verb هَلَكَ meaning \"he perished,\" \"he died,\" or \"he was destroyed.\" مُهْلِكِي translates to \"one to destroy\" or \"the destroyer.\" The nuance of this term lies in its more direct focus on the capacity or intent to cause destruction. Unlike مُهْلِكٌ, which may emphasize the act itself, مُهْلِكِي highlights the characteristic or identity of being a bringer of ruin. The root's themes of loss and devastation are embodied in this term, emphasizing the destructive power that leads to the cessation of existence or the downfall of others.",
  "3885": "مُوَاقِعُونَ and related words stem from the root و-ق-ع, with the root verb وَقَعَ meaning \"he fell\" or \"it occurred.\" وَاقَعَ means \"he fell into\" or \"he engaged with,\" often implying encountering or engaging in a significant act. مُوَاقِعُونَ means \"those who fall into\" or \"those who engage with.\" The connection lies in actively initiating or participating in an event or action, emphasizing deliberate engagement as something that \"falls upon\" or happens between parties. This term reflects the intentional involvement inherent in the root's meanings.",
  "3886": "الْمُورِيَاتِ and related words stem from the root و-ر-ي, with the root verb أَوْرَى meaning \"he kindled,\" \"he ignited,\" or \"he caused to burn.\" الْمُورِيَاتِ means \"the ones who produce sparks,\" referring to war horses whose hooves strike against rocks, producing visible sparks during their gallop. This imagery reflects strength, intensity, and urgency, connecting to the root’s broader concept of uncovering latent energy or igniting potential. The root highlights transformation, as it involves bringing forth light or heat from concealed sources, symbolizing action and power in motion.",
  "3887": "مُوسَىٰ is the name of Prophet Moses (ﷺ), of Hebrew origin, linked to the root מ-ש-ה (masha), meaning \"to draw out.\" This reflects his rescue from the Nile as an infant and his later role in drawing out the Children of Israel from oppression in Egypt. His life embodies themes of liberation, faith, and perseverance. In the Qur'an, Prophet Moses (ﷺ) exemplifies the struggle against tyranny, steadfastness in adversity, and the power of Allah’s (ﷻ) guidance, highlighting Allah’s (ﷻ) promises to the patient and righteous.",
  "3888": "مُوسِعٌ and related words stem from the root و-س-ع, with the root verb وَسِعَ meaning \"he was or became ample, spacious, or extensive.\" مُوسِعٌ means \"one who is affluent\" or \"one who provides abundantly.\" The connection is through the idea of possessing vast resources or wealth and the capacity to extend generosity. It reflects the ability to provide ample provision or support to others, emphasizing the root's concept of expansiveness and abundance.",
  "3889": "مُوصٍ and related words stem from the root و-ص-ي, with the root verb وَصَّى meaning \"he enjoined\" or \"he advised earnestly.\" مُوصٍ means \"one who makes a will,\" \"one who enjoins,\" or \"testator.\" The connection to the root emphasizes the person performing the action of giving significant instructions or making a bequest, highlighting their role in conveying important responsibilities or wishes.",
  "3890": "مُوفُونَ and related words stem from the root و-ف-ى, with the root verb وَفَىٰ meaning \"he fulfilled\" or \"he completed.\" مُوفُونَ means \"ones who fulfill.\" The connection lies in the person who faithfully carries out promises or obligations, reflecting the root's emphasis on faithfulness and integrity. This highlights the virtue of reliability, emphasizing the moral responsibility to honor one's commitments.",
  "3891": "مُوقَدَةٌ and related words stem from the root و-ق-د, with the root verb وَقَدَ meaning \"it kindled,\" \"it ignited,\" or \"it flamed.\" مُوقَدَةٌ is a passive form meaning \"kindled,\" \"ignited,\" or \"set ablaze.\" The root conveys themes of ignition, combustion, and sustained burning. The term reflects the state of being actively set alight, emphasizing intensity and continuity. In the Qur'an, الْمُوقَدَةُ describes the Hellfire, highlighting its fierce, unrelenting flames.",
  "3892": "مُوقِنِينَ and related words stem from the root ي-ق-ن, with the root verb يَقِنَ meaning \"he was certain.\" مُوقِنِينَ means \"ones who are certain\" or \"sure of the truth.\" This term reflects a settled and unwavering state of certainty already attained, emphasizing inner conviction and the absence of doubt. The connection lies in the root’s emphasis on firm, established certainty that remains steadfast, without requiring further exploration or validation.",
  "3893": "مُوهِنٌ and related words stem from the root و-ه-ن, with the root verb وَهَنَ meaning \"he weakened\" or \"he became feeble.\" مُوهِنٌ means \"one who weakens\" or \"one who causes weakness,\" emphasizing the act of actively diminishing strength or vitality. The connection reflects the root's focus on feebleness, highlighting an agent that brings about weakness or a decline in power.",
  "3894": "مُوَفُّونَ and related words stem from the root و-ف-ى, with the root verb وَفَىٰ meaning \"he fulfilled\" or \"he completed.\" مُوَفُّونَ means \"ones who fulfill completely\" or \"ones who pay in full completely.\" The connection lies in the root’s emphasis on completeness and precision in fulfilling obligations or delivering dues.",
  "3895": "مُوَلِّي and related words stem from the root و-ل-ي, with the root verb وَلِيَ meaning \"he was near,\" \"he befriended,\" or \"he protected.\" The root conveys themes of nearness, guardianship, and direction. مُوَلِّي means \"one who turns\" or \"one who directs,\" emphasizing the act of intentionally guiding or assigning a direction. The connection lies in the root’s focus on proximity and purposeful action, highlighting movement or leadership that and related words stem from closeness and responsibility.",
  "3896": "مِائَةٌ and related words stem from the root م-أ-ي, and refers to the number one hundred in Arabic. In various contexts, it can symbolize completeness, abundance, or a significant quantity.",
  "3897": "مِثْقَالٌ and related words stem from the root ث-ق-ل, with the root verb ثَقُلَ meaning \"it was heavy, weighty, or burdensome.\" مِثْقَالٌ means \"weight\" or \"measure.\" It represents a unit of weight, such as a balance scale measurement, directly linked to the root's meaning. This term is often used metaphorically to signify even the smallest weight of deeds, emphasizing that every action holds significance.",
  "3898": "مِحَالٌ and related words stem from the root م-ح-ل, with the root verb مَحَلَ meaning \"he plotted,\" \"he schemed,\" or \"he devised a plan,\" often with deliberate and calculated intent. مِحَالٌ refers to \"strategy\" and conveys the concept of intricate planning, emphasizing precision and the ability to outmaneuver adversaries. The connection lies in the root's focus on deliberate plotting, reflecting the strength and calculated nature of actions designed to achieve significant outcomes. While it can imply power or retribution as results of strategic action, the primary focus remains on the deliberate and masterful nature of the plan itself.",
  "3899": "مِحْرَابٌ and related words stem from the root ح-ر-ب, with the root verb حَرَبَ meaning \"he plundered\" and حَرْبٌ meaning \"war\" or \"battle.\" مِحْرَابٌ means \"prayer niche\" or \"sanctuary.\" The connection lies in struggle, separation, and devotion. Just as plundering removes something from its original place, a prayer chamber symbolizes withdrawal from worldly distractions for focused worship. It represents a space of spiritual struggle, where one strives against inner desires to attain closeness to Allah (ﷻ). The root’s link to war also reflects the discipline and effort required in worship, making a prayer chamber a place of both refuge and dedication.",
  "3900": "مِدَادٌ and related words stem from the root م-د-د, with the root verb مَدَّ meaning \"he extended\" or \"he spread.\" مِدَادٌ means \"ink,\" connecting to the root through the idea of extension. Ink serves as the medium through which thoughts and words are extended onto surfaces, allowing ideas to be preserved, communicated, and shared. This term emphasizes the root’s core concept of spreading or elongating, illustrating how ink facilitates the transmission of knowledge and the endurance of expression over time and space.",
  "3901": "مِدْرَارٌ and related words stem from the root د-ر-ر, with the root verb دَرَّ meaning \"he was generous, bountiful, or abundant in giving,\" \"it became plentiful, abundant, or full,\" or \"it poured down plentifully.\" This root conveys themes of abundance, flowing, generosity, and preciousness. مِدْرَارٌ refers to \"abundant\" or \"copious,\" particularly describing plentiful rain. The connection lies in continuous, overflowing provision, much like rain that pours down in abundance. Just as something that flows steadily brings nourishment and benefit, this word reflects an outpouring of blessings, sustenance, or provision that is both plentiful and uninterrupted.",
  "3902": "مِرَاءٌ and related words stem from the root م-ر-ي, with the root verb مَارَىٰ meaning \"he disputed\" or \"he doubted.\" مِرَاءٌ means \"disputation,\" \"controversy,\" or \"argument.\" The root reflects the manifestation of doubt through active debate or contention, emphasizing challenges to ideas or beliefs. مِرَاءٌ captures the intensity of intellectual or theological disputes, showing how uncertainty often fuels contention and debate.",
  "3903": "مِرَّةٌ and related words stem from the root م-ر-ر, with the root verb مَرَّ meaning \"he passed by\" or \"he became bitter.\" مِرَّةٌ means \"strength,\" \"vigor,\" or \"force.\" The connection lies in the intensity and potency associated with bitterness, symbolizing resilience and robustness. This reflects the root's core idea of intensity and endurance, emphasizing a strong and steadfast state capable of withstanding challenges, much like the sharpness of a bitter taste.",
  "3904": "مِرْصَادٌ and related words stem from the root ر-ص-د, with the root verb رَصَدَ meaning \"he watched,\" \"he observed,\" or \"he lay in wait.\" مِرْصَادٌ means \"a place of ambush,\" \"an ever-watchful presence,\" or \"a constant lookout.\" The connection lies in the continuous and vigilant observation, embodying the root's emphasis on constant readiness and surveillance. In the Qur'anic context, when it's said that Allah (ﷻ) is \"بالمرصاد,\" it signifies His ever-watchful awareness of all actions, highlighting the profound moral lesson of divine vigilance and accountability.",
  "3905": "مِرْفَقٌ and related words stem from the root ر-ف-ق, with the root verb رَفَقَ meaning \"he was kind\" or \"he was gentle.\" مِرْفَقٌ means \"elbow\" or \"facility.\" The connection lies in the idea of support and assistance, as the elbow supports the arm, embodying the root's emphasis on helpfulness. This term reflects both anatomical and metaphorical support, highlighting the multifaceted nature of assistance and ease.",
  "3906": "مِرْيَةٌ and related words stem from the root م-ر-ي, with the root verb مَارَىٰ meaning \"he disputed\" or \"he doubted.\" مِرْيَةٌ means \"doubt,\" \"uncertainty,\" or \"suspicion.\" The word reflects the internalized state of skepticism or hesitation, rooted in the core idea of doubt. مِرْيَةٌ highlights the emotional and intellectual dimensions of uncertainty, illustrating how it affects one’s beliefs, decisions, and actions.",
  "3907": "مِزَاجٌ and related words stem from the root م-ز-ج, with the root verb مَزَجَ meaning \"he mixed\" or \"he mingled.\" مِزَاجٌ means \"mixture,\" \"blend,\" or \"temperament.\" The connection lies in combining different elements to create a unified whole. This reflects the root's fundamental idea of mixing, emphasizing how diverse components come together to form something new, whether physically—as in a drink—or metaphorically—as in one's disposition.",
  "3908": "مِسَاسٌ and related words stem from the root م-س-س, with the root verb مَسَّ meaning \"he touched\" or \"he felt.\" مِسَاسٌ means \"touch\" or \"contact\" but emphasizes the ongoing or reciprocal nature of interaction. Unlike مَسٌّ, which focuses on the act itself, مِسَاسٌ highlights mutual influence or continuous interaction between entities. This nuance reflects the dynamic and communicative aspects of contact, illustrating how touch facilitates connection, communication, and influence through sustained or mutual engagement.",
  "3909": "مِسْكٌ and related words stem from the root م-س-ك, with the root verb مَسَكَ meaning \"he held,\" \"he grasped.\" مِسْكٌ specifically refers to \"musk,\" a fragrant substance. The connection may be seen in musk's ability to retain its strong fragrance. This reflects the root's concept of holding, emphasizing the enduring and captivating nature of the scent, symbolizing allure and the power to leave a lasting impression. In Islamic tradition, musk is highly valued and often mentioned in descriptions of paradise, symbolizing purity, beauty, and the eternal pleasure of the afterlife. Its enduring fragrance serves as a metaphor for the lasting rewards of righteousness and the sweet scent of faith.",
  "3910": "مِسْكِينٌ and related words stem from the root س-ك-ن, with the root verb سَكَنَ meaning \"he dwelt,\" \"he resided,\" or \"he became still.\" مِسْكِينٌ means \"poor,\" \"needy,\" or \"destitute.\" The connection lies in the state of being subdued or rendered still by poverty, where one's ability to move or act is limited due to lack of resources. It reflects vulnerability and dependence, aligning with the root's concept of stillness, and underscores the importance of compassion and assistance towards those in need.",
  "3911": "مِشْكَاةٌ and related words stem from the root ش-ك-و, which conveys the concept of \"combination\" or \"gathering.\" مِشْكَاةٌ specifically refers to a \"niche,\" \"recess,\" or \"lamp alcove,\" a space in a wall designed to hold a lamp. The connection lies in the idea of gathering light within a confined space, concentrating its glow to enhance its illumination. This concept reflects the root’s meaning of assembling or unifying elements, with the مِشْكَاةٌ symbolizing a vessel that intensifies the light's radiance. Metaphorically, it represents a focused source of clarity or guidance, with the light shining brighter when protected and contained, much like divine wisdom or truth in the heart of a believer.",
  "3912": "مِصْبَاحٌ and related words stem from the root ص-ب-ح, with the root verb صَبَحَ meaning \"he entered the morning.\" مِصْبَاحٌ means \"lamp\" or \"light.\" The connection lies in the root's association with illumination. مِصْبَاحٌ is a source of light that dispels darkness, akin to how morning light brightens the world. In the Qur'an's \"Light Verse,\" it symbolizes Allah's (ﷻ) guidance illuminating the hearts of believers, reflecting the root's emphasis on enlightenment and clarity.",
  "3913": "مِصْرَ and related words stem from the root م-ص-ر, with the root verb مَصَرَ meaning \"he defined a boundary,\" \"he established,\" or \"he built a city.\" مِصْرٌ refers to \"a city\" or \"a country,\" and in the form مِصْرَ, it specifically denotes \"Egypt.\" The root reflects organizing and defining spaces, emphasizing boundaries and structured settlements, whether as urban centers or territorial divisions. This concept extends to the establishment of civilizations and governance, with Egypt exemplifying these ideas as a major cultural center. The term also highlights human efforts to create order and structure in societies, connecting the root’s meanings to themes of development, urbanization, and organization.",
  "3914": "مِعْشَارٌ and related words stem from the root ع-ش-ر, with the root verb عَشَرَ meaning \"he became the tenth.\" مِعْشَارٌ means \"one-tenth\" or \"a tenth part.\" The connection lies in dividing a whole into ten equal parts, reflecting the root's emphasis on the number ten. This term highlights concepts of proportion and equitable division in numerical contexts.",
  "3915": "مِقْدَارٌ and related words stem from the root ق-د-ر, with the root verb قَدَرَ meaning \"he measured,\" \"he determined,\" or \"he decreed.\" مِقْدَارٌ means \"measure,\" \"amount,\" \"quantity,\" or \"degree.\" The connection lies in the tool or means by which measurement is accomplished, directly relating to the root's emphasis on measurement and determination. This term signifies the specific extent or value of something, highlighting the importance of quantifying and assessing.",
  "3916": "مِكْيَالٌ and related words also stem from the root ك-ي-ل, with the root verb كَالَ meaning \"he measured\" or \"he weighed.\" مِكْيَالٌ refers specifically to \"a measuring vessel\" or \"a measure,\" focusing on the tool or standard used to perform the act of measuring. The connection lies in the instrument's role in standardizing quantities, ensuring fairness and reliability in trade. This term emphasizes the necessity of precise tools for maintaining integrity in commerce.",
  "3917": "مِلَّةٌ and related words stem from the root م-ل-ل, with the root verb مَلَّ meaning \"he became weary,\" \"he repeated,\" or \"he adhered to something persistently.\" مِلَّةٌ means \"religion,\" \"creed,\" or \"community of faith,\" signifying a prescribed path or system of belief shared by a group. The root also conveys the idea of regularity and repetition, reflecting the disciplined adherence to established practices and rituals within a religious framework. The root's concept of persistence suggests that faith requires continual engagement, reinforcing the enduring nature of religious devotion as a guiding principle in life.",
  "3918": "مِلْءٌ and related words stem from the root م-ل-أ, with the root verb مَلَأَ meaning \"he filled.\" مِلْءٌ signifies \"fullness,\" \"capacity,\" or \"the amount that fills,\" emphasizing the measure or extent of being full. It reflects the root's concept of filling, whether in terms of physical volume or metaphorical capacity. The word also conveys a sense of sufficiency or completeness, highlighting the result of achieving fullness, whether in a container, space, or an abstract sense of contentment or fulfillment.",
  "3919": "مِلْحٌ and related words stem from the root م-ل-ح, with the root verb مَلَحَ meaning \"it was or became salty.\" مِلْحٌ refers to \"salt\" and is associated with the characteristic of saltiness. It is also defined as \"salty\" when describing water that contains salt. The root emphasizes the essence of saltiness and its effects, such as preservation and enhancement. These dimensions highlight the significance of مِلْحٌ in its various applications, both as a substance essential for life and as a descriptor of a fundamental quality found in nature.",
  "3920": "The particle مِنْ is a versatile word that typically translates to \"from\" or \"of.\" It indicates origin, source, separation, or part of something, and can also signify cause or reason. Its use is essential for clarifying relationships in sentences, as it helps define the starting point or source of an action, condition, or state. مِنْ can also indicate partiality, as in something being \"from among\" a larger group. In the Qur'an, مِنْ is often used to highlight the source of blessings or trials, showing that everything ultimately originates from Allah (ﷻ), reinforcing the concept of Allah's (ﷻ) will and wisdom.",
  "3921": "مِنْسَأَةٌ and related words stem from the root ن-س-أ, with the root verb نَسَأَ meaning \"he postponed,\" \"he delayed,\" or \"he drove forward.\" مِنْسَأَةٌ means \"staff,\" particularly one used to drive or urge animals ahead. The connection lies in the root’s concept of driving forward or delaying, as the staff serves to propel or guide movement, symbolizing authority and control. This reflects the broader theme of urging or postponing actions, emphasizing the utility of tools in directing or regulating motion and behavior. In the Qur'an, Prophet Solomon's (ﷺ) staff played a pivotal role in delaying the jinn from realizing his death, as they continued their labor, unaware that he had passed away while leaning on it.",
  "3922": "مِنْهاجٌ and related words stem from the root ن-ه-ج, with the root verb نَهَجَ meaning \"he followed a path\" or \"he pursued a course.\" مِنْهاجٌ means \"a method\" or \"a way.\" The connection lies in the structured approach or system one follows, directly relating to the root's concept of following a specific path. This term emphasizes the importance of a defined methodology or approach in achieving goals, highlighting the moral lesson of intentionality and direction in one's actions.",
  "3923": "مِهَادٌ and related words stem from the root م-ه-د, with the root verb مَهَدَ meaning \"he spread out\" or \"he prepared.\" مِهَادٌ refers to a \"bed,\" \"resting place,\" or \"foundation,\" embodying the root’s essence of smoothing and laying out for stability and ease. In the Qur'an, this term is often used to describe the earth as a stable and nurturing dwelling, emphasizing Allah’s (ﷻ) meticulous preparation and provision for humanity. It symbolizes the interconnectedness of creation and the deliberate effort to establish harmony and balance in the world.",
  "3924": "مِيثَاقٌ and related words stem from the root و-ث-ق, with the root verb وَثَقَ meaning \"he trusted\" or \"he was firm.\" مِيثَاقٌ means \"a covenant,\" \"a solemn agreement,\" or \"a treaty.\" The connection lies in the emphasis on trust and firmness inherent in making binding agreements, directly relating to the root's meaning. This term signifies the seriousness and sacredness of covenants, highlighting the ethical duty to honor one's commitments.",
  "3925": "مِيرَاثٌ and related words stem from the root و-ر-ث, with the root verb وَرِثَ meaning \"he inherited.\" مِيرَاثٌ means \"inheritance\" or \"legacy.\" The term focuses on the specific portions or shares received by heirs, directly connecting to the root's concept of receiving what is passed down. In Islamic jurisprudence, مِيرَاثٌ details the fair and just distribution of an estate, reflecting the importance of familial rights and societal harmony as ordained by Allah (ﷻ).",
  "3926": "مِيزَانٌ and related words stem from the root و-ز-ن, with the root verb وَزَنَ meaning \"he weighed.\" مِيزَانٌ means \"scale\" or \"balance.\" The connection is direct, as a scale embodies the root's concept of measuring weight and ensuring balance. In Islamic theology, the مِيزَانٌ symbolizes the weighing of deeds on the Day of Judgment, highlighting the principles of justice, accountability, and the precise assessment of one's actions by Allah (ﷻ).",
  "3927": "مِيعَادٌ and related words stem from the root و-ع-د, with the root verb وَعَدَ meaning \"he promised.\" مِيعَادٌ means \"appointed time\" or \"promise.\" The term emphasizes a formal promise with a set time or place, reflecting the root's concept of commitment and certainty. This highlights the significance of precise timing in fulfilling promises, reinforcing the importance of punctuality and reliability in personal and communal obligations.",
  "3928": "مِيقَاتٌ and related words stem from the root و-ق-ت, with the root verb وَقَتَ meaning \"he fixed a time.\" مِيقَاتٌ translates as \"appointed time\" or \"place of meeting.\" The connection lies in the act of determining or specifying a time or location for an event, reflecting the root's emphasis on precision, scheduling, and appointment.",
  "3929": "مِيكَالُ (also known as مِيكَائِيلُ) refers to Angel Michael (ﷺ). The name مِيكَالُ is derived from Hebrew מִיכָאֵל, meaning \"Who is like God?\"—a rhetorical question signifying that none can compare to Allah's (ﷻ) power. Angel Michael (ﷺ) is tasked with overseeing mercy and provision, managing natural phenomena and ensuring sustenance for all beings. His role reflects his name's meaning, as his responsibilities manifest Allah's (ﷻ) unmatched care and provision, emphasizing Allah's (ﷻ) power that sustains all creation.",
  "3930": "The particle ن is essential for adding emphasis and strengthening verbs to convey certainty or intensity. It appears in two forms: the heavy نَّ (with a shaddah) and the light نْ (without a shaddah). These forms intensify the forcefulness of a verb, emphasizing that the action will certainly occur or is strongly assured. In the Qur'an, نون التوكيد is often used to highlight the certainty of divine actions and decrees, powerfully conveying the intensity of events, promises, and warnings.",
  "3931": "نَائِمُونَ and related words stem from the root ن-و-م, with the root verb نَامَ meaning \"he slept.\" نَائِمُونَ means \"those who are sleeping\" or \"sleepers.\" This term directly relates to individuals in the state of sleep, embodying the root's emphasis on rest and inactivity. Metaphorically, نَائِمُونَ can also imply heedlessness or unawareness, as sleep symbolizes a lack of consciousness or attention in certain contexts.",
  "3932": "نَاجٍ and related words stem from the root ن-ج-و, with the root verb نَجَا meaning \"he became safe\" or \"he escaped.\" نَاجٍ means \"one who is saved\" or \"survivor.\" The connection lies in the state of being rescued or delivered from harm, highlighting themes of survival, mercy, and gratitude. This term highlights the blessings of protection and divine deliverance, encouraging individuals to seek refuge in Allah (ﷻ) in times of difficulty.",
  "3933": "نَاجَىٰ and related words stem from the root ن-ج-و, with the root verb نَجَا meaning \"he became safe,\" \"he escaped,\" and \"he conversed secretly.\" نَاجَىٰ means \"he conversed privately\" or \"he held a secret conversation,\" emphasizing intimate and confidential communication. The connection lies in the act of engaging in private exchanges, reflecting trust, closeness, and the protection found in revealing personal thoughts or matters. This term highlights the sincerity and vulnerability involved in such interactions, where secrecy serves as a metaphorical escape from public exposure, fostering a sense of safety and trust.",
  "3934": "نَادَىٰ and related words stem from the root ن-د-ي, with the root verb نَدَا meaning \"he called,\" \"he proclaimed,\" or \"he invited.\" نَادَىٰ means \"he called out,\" \"he cried,\" or \"he proclaimed loudly.\" This root encompasses the ideas of calling out and summoning others. This form intensifies the action of the root verb, emphasizing a strong or urgent call. The connection lies in the amplification of the root's core concept. In the Qur'an, نَادَىٰ is used to signify the act of calling or summoning in significant contexts, such as prayer, divine guidance, and urgent messages.",
  "3935": "نَادِمِينَ and related words stem from the root ن-د-م, with the root verb نَدِمَ meaning \"he regretted\" or \"he repented.\" The root conveys a profound emotional state of sorrow and regret over past actions or decisions. نَادِمِينَ means \"ones who regret\" or \"regretful\" reflecting the recognition of one’s errors and the emotional response to those mistakes.",
  "3936": "نَادِيَ and related words stem from the root ن-د-ي, with the root verb نَدَا meaning \"he called,\" \"he proclaimed,\" or \"he invited.\" نَادِيَ means \"assembly,\" \"council,\" or \"gathering place,\" referring specifically to the space where people come together, often summoned by a call. The root conveys calling and assembling, with نَادِيَ emphasizing the physical location that facilitates interaction and decision-making as the outcome of the call. Contextually, it can also extend to the group assembled there.",
  "3937": "نارٌ and related words stem from the root ن-و-ر, with the root verb نَوَّرَ meaning \"he or it illuminated\" or \"he or it enlightened.\" نارٌ means \"fire,\" symbolizing both illumination and heat. The root conveys themes of light and transformation, and fire reflects this by offering illumination and serving as a means of purification or warning. If one rejects the light of guidance, fire transitions from a tool of transformation to a form of punishment, emphasizing the root’s duality and the consequences of refusing enlightenment.",
  "3938": "النَّازِعَاتُ and related words stem from the root ن-ز-ع, with the root verb نَزَعَ meaning \"he pulled out,\" \"he extracted,\" or \"he removed.\" This root encompasses the concept of forcefully removing or drawing out. النَّازِعَاتُ means \"those who pull out\" or \"extractors.\" In the Qur'an, it refers to angels who extract souls with force. The connection lies in the vivid depiction of extraction inherent in the root. النَّازِعَاتُ embodies the intense and decisive action of pulling out, reflecting the root's essence by highlighting the power and inevitability of the process.",
  "3939": "أُنَاسٌ and related words stem from the root أ-ن-س, with the root verb أَنَسَ meaning \"he was sociable,\" \"he found comfort,\" or \"he became familiar.\" أُنَاسٌ translates to \"people,\" \"folk,\" or \"humankind.\" The connection lies in the collective nature of humanity, where individuals find comfort and familiarity in social companionship, embodying the root’s focus on sociability. أُنَاسٌ represents society as a whole, highlighting the communal aspect of human life and the importance of social connections among people.",
  "3940": "نَاسِكُونَ and related words stem from the root ن-س-ك, with the root verb نَسَكَ meaning \"he devoted himself to worship\" or \"he performed acts of devotion.\" نَاسِكُونَ (plural of نَاسِكٌ) means \"devotees\" or \"worshippers,\" or \"ones devoted to,\" specifically those who actively engage in religious rites and acts of worship. The root emphasizes devotion, purity, and dedication to spiritual practices. نَاسِكُونَ embodies the idea of individuals striving for closeness to Allah (ﷻ) through consistent acts of piety and fulfillment of prescribed rituals, reflecting the root’s focus on sincerity and spiritual commitment.",
  "3941": "ناشِئَةٌ and related words stem from the root ن-ش-أ, with the root verb نَشَأَ meaning \"he grew,\" \"he arose,\" or \"he originated.\" ناشِئَةٌ means \"one who rises,\" \"emerges,\" or \"grows.\" The root highlights themes of growth and development, describing something that gradually comes into being and moves from its early stages toward completion or maturity. ناشِئَةٌ reflects purposeful growth and emergence, whether referring to individuals, ideas, or natural phenomena, aligning with the root's focus on creation, progression, and becoming.",
  "3942": "النَّاشِرَاتِ and related words stem from the root ن-ش-ر, with the root verb نَشَرَ meaning \"he revived,\" \"he resurrected,\" or \"he spread out.\" النَّاشِرَاتِ means \"those that disperse,\" \"those that spread,\" or \"those that revive.\" In the Qur'an, it describes winds dispersing clouds to bring rain, emphasizing their role in renewal and providing life to barren lands. The root conveys the act of distributing or bringing back to life, highlighting active and transformative movement. This term reflects both the physical dispersal of winds and the broader concept of rejuvenation and spreading vitality, embodying the root's dual themes of dissemination and renewal.",
  "3943": "النَّاشِطَاتُ and related words stem from the root ن-ش-ط, with the root verb نَشَطَ meaning \"he was active,\" \"he untied,\" or \"he loosened.\" النَّاشِطَاتُ refers to \"those who untie\" or \"those who loosen,\" describing angels in the Qur'an, gently and effortlessly drawing out the souls of the righteous, akin to untying a knot. The root conveys themes of activity, ease, and purposeful release, emphasizing the smoothness and grace in freeing something from constraint. This term highlights the precise and gentle nature of the angels’ actions, reflecting the root's focus on both energy and liberation.",
  "3944": "ناصِبَةٌ and related words stem from the root ن-ص-ب, with the root verb نَصَبَ meaning \"he toiled,\" \"he labored,\" or \"he exerted effort.\" ناصِبَةٌ means \"fatigued\" or \"weary from labor,\" describing a state of intense effort that results in physical and mental fatigue. The root conveys themes of exertion, struggle, and persistence, emphasizing the burdens and weariness associated with prolonged toil. In its Qur'anic context, ناصِبَةٌ highlights the futility of relentless labor that yields no ultimate benefit, serving as a reminder of the importance of aligning effort with purpose and divine guidance.",
  "3945": "ناصِحٌ and related words stem from the root ن-ص-ح, with the root verb نَصَحَ meaning \"he was sincere\" or \"he advised sincerely.\" ناصِحٌ means \"sincere advisor\" or \"one who counsels with integrity,\" emphasizing honesty and purity in offering guidance. The connection lies in providing genuine, well-intentioned advice, directly relating to the root's focus on sincerity and clarity. This term highlights the moral responsibility of honesty and integrity when advising others, ensuring that guidance is free of deceit or ulterior motives.",
  "3946": "ناصِرٌ and related words stem from the root ن-ص-ر, with the root verb نَصَرَ meaning \"he helped.\" ناصِرٌ means \"helper\" or \"supporter,\" referring to one who provides substantial aid or assistance. The connection lies in the active role of offering support, reflecting the root’s emphasis on help and collaboration. ناصِرٌ highlights the importance of those who stand as allies, offering strength and assistance to ensure success or relief, emphasizing the communal and moral responsibility of providing help.",
  "3947": "نَاصِيَةٌ and related words stem from the root ن-ص-ي, with the root verb نَصَا meaning \"he led,\" \"he directed,\" or \"he advanced forward.\" نَاصِيَةٌ means \"forelock\" or \"forehead,\" referring to the frontmost part of the head, often associated with control and guidance. The connection to the root lies in the act of leading or directing, as the forelock symbolizes how individuals can be metaphorically and physically guided or controlled. This reflects its role in governing actions, representing submission, accountability, and responsibility. The forelock, linked to decision-making and moral choices, highlights the balance between physical guidance and spiritual accountability.",
  "3948": "ناضِرَةٌ and related words stem from the root ن-ض-ر, with the root verb نَضَرَ meaning \"he became fresh,\" \"bloomed,\" or \"flourished.\" ناضِرَةٌ means \"radiant,\" \"glowing,\" or \"fresh,\" describing an outward brightness that reflects vitality and joy. The root emphasizes renewal, flourishing, and the vibrancy of life, likening radiant faces to blooming flowers in their freshness and beauty. ناضِرَةٌ encapsulates the harmony of physical and emotional well-being, symbolizing a state of contentment and vitality that resonates with the perfection of divine creation.",
  "3949": "نَاظِرِينَ and related words stem from the root ن-ظ-ر, with the root verb نَظَرَ meaning \"he looked,\" \"he observed,\" or \"he considered.\" نَاظِرِينَ means \"ones who look,\" \"observers,\" or \"ones awaiting,\" reflecting active engagement in observing or awaiting something with attention. The connection lies in the act of careful observation or contemplation, emphasizing attentiveness and reflection. The root's focus on sight and perception highlight the importance of thoughtful engagement and understanding, particularly in moments requiring insight or discernment, emphasizing the significance of awareness in one’s spiritual and practical journey.",
  "3950": "ناظِرَةٌ and related words stem from the root ن-ظ-ر, with the root verb نَظَرَ meaning \"he looked,\" \"he observed,\" or \"he considered.\" ناظِرَةٌ means \"one who looks,\" \"female observer,\" or \"looking,\" and refers to the act of actively perceiving or awaiting with attention. The connection lies in the root's emphasis on sight and contemplation, reflecting both literal and metaphorical observation. In classical Arabic, ناظِرَةٌ can signify a state of hopeful anticipation or attentive waiting, highlighting the relationship between perception and expectation.",
  "3951": "نَاعِمَةٌ and related words stem from the root ن-ع-م, with the root verb نَعِمَ meaning \"he was at ease\" or \"he enjoyed comfort.\" نَاعِمَةٌ means \"soft,\" \"delicate,\" or \"luxurious,\" conveying a sense of ease, refinement, and bliss. In the Qur'anic context, it describes faces radiant with contentment and delight, reflecting the serene and blissful state of the people of Paradise. This connects to the root's emphasis on ease and pleasantness, highlighting the reward and ultimate comfort granted to the righteous as a manifestation of divine favor.",
  "3952": "نَافَقُوا and related words stem from the root ن-ف-ق, with the root verb نَفَقَ meaning \"he tunneled,\" \"he created a hidden passage,\" \"it expired,\" or \"it was depleted.\" The meaning of \"spending\" also emerges, reflecting the use of resources. نَافَقُوا means \"they acted hypocritically,\" connecting to tunnels as hidden paths, symbolizing hypocrisy’s deceit—presenting a false outward appearance while concealing true intentions. The root’s idea of \"expiration\" or \"depletion\" mirrors how hypocrisy drains sincerity and integrity, leaving emptiness. This contrasts with أَنْفَقَ, where spending reflects generosity and purposeful use, showing how the root embodies both selfless giving and the moral erosion of deceit.",
  "3953": "نَافِلَةٌ and related words stem from the root ن-ف-ل, with the root verb نَفَلَ meaning \"he gave extra\" or \"he granted as a gift.\" نَافِلَةٌ means \"addition,\" \"extra benefit,\" or \"voluntary act,\" referring to something performed or given beyond what is obligatory. The connection lies in the concept of going beyond the minimum requirement, symbolizing generosity or additional devotion. In religious contexts, نَافِلَةٌ often refers to voluntary prayers or acts of worship that are performed to seek additional reward and draw closer to Allah (ﷻ). This term reflects the spiritual aspiration to exceed basic duties and embrace extra acts of goodness, embodying the root's emphasis on surplus and voluntary offerings.",
  "3954": "ناقَةٌ and related words stem from the root ن-و-ق, with the root verb نَقَىٰ meaning \"he cleansed\" or \"he made pure.\" ناقَةٌ means \"a she-camel,\" reflecting its noble and valued role in Arabic culture. The root's broader meanings of purification and refinement connect to the she-camel's association with purity and grace. This term highlights the she-camel's significance as both a vital resource and a symbol of nobility, emphasizing themes of care, value, and the importance of purity in physical and symbolic contexts.",
  "3955": "نَاقُورٌ and related words stem from the root ن-ق-ر, with the root verb نَقَرَ meaning \"he pierced,\" \"he hollowed out,\" or \"he struck, producing a sound.\" نَاقُورٌ refers to a \"trumpet\" or \"horn,\" an instrument that produces a loud, piercing sound. The root conveys themes of penetration, minute examination, and sound production, all connected by the idea of creating impact or clarity. نَاقُورٌ embodies the piercing nature of sound that commands attention, emphasizing its role in signaling or announcing something of great importance.",
  "3956": "نَاكِبُونَ and related words stem from the root ن-ك-ب, with the root verb نَكَبَ meaning \"he turned aside\" or \"he deviated.\" نَاكِبُونَ means \"ones who turn away\" or \"deviators.\" The connection lies in the act of deviating from a path or direction, directly relating to the root's meaning. It represents someone who strays from the correct course or guidance.",
  "3957": "ناكِسُوا and related words stem from the root ن-ك-س, with the root verb نَكَسَ meaning \"he inverted,\" \"turned upside down,\" or \"reversed.\" ناكِسُوا means \"those who lower\" or \"those who bow down,\" specifically referring to lowering one's head. The connection lies in the physical act of lowering the head, symbolizing shame, humility, or defeat, aligning with the root’s concept of inversion or a complete reversal of position. This term reflects a transformation from arrogance or pride to abasement, highlighting the moral and emotional consequences of one's actions, particularly in the face of accountability.",
  "3958": "ناهُونَ and related words stem from the root ن-ه-ى, with the root verb نَهَى meaning \"he forbade\" or \"he prohibited.\" ناهُونَ means \"those who forbid\" or \"those who discourage wrongdoing.\" The word describes individuals who take an active role in preventing immoral or harmful behavior, embodying the root's emphasis on restraint and guidance. This term highlights the responsibility of promoting righteousness and preventing evil within a community, reflecting the importance of moral accountability and collective action to uphold ethical principles.",
  "3959": "نَبَاتٌ and related words stem from the root ن-ب-ت, with the root verb نَبَتَ meaning \"it grew\" or \"it sprouted.\" نَبَاتٌ means \"plants,\" \"vegetation,\" or \"growth.\" The connection lies in representing the result of the growth process—the plants that have sprouted from the earth. This aligns with the root's focus on natural development, emphasizing the abundance and diversity of life arising from the soil, reflecting on the blessings of sustenance provided by Allah (ﷻ).",
  "3960": "نَبَأٌ and related words stem from the root ن-ب-أ, with the root verb نَبَأَ meaning \"he informed,\" \"he announced,\" or \"he brought news.\" نَبَأٌ refers to \"news,\" \"tidings,\" or \"a significant piece of information,\" often highlighting content that is momentous or consequential. The root emphasizes the importance of information that influences understanding, beliefs, or actions. نَبَأٌ captures the weight of truths that demand attention and reflection, highlighting the value of meaningful and impactful communication.",
  "3961": "نَبَذَ and related words stem from the root ن-ب-ذ, and as the root verb, it means \"he discarded,\" \"he threw away,\" or \"he rejected.\" The term also conveys meanings of \"casting aside,\" \"abandoning,\" or \"separating something from oneself.\" The root emphasizes deliberate rejection, often of something deemed insignificant, unwanted, or unworthy. Broader meanings include themes of abandonment, detachment, and exclusion, whether in physical or metaphorical contexts. This connection reflects purposeful actions of dismissal or separation, symbolizing themes of rejection, insignificance, or neglect in both tangible and intangible matters.",
  "3962": "نَبِيٌّ and related words stem from the root ن-ب-أ, with the root verb نَبَأَ meaning \"he informed,\" \"he announced,\" or \"he brought news,\" as well as as well as \"he was exalted or elevated,\" indicating a rise in prominence. نَبِيٌّ means \"prophet,\" referring to one who conveys divine messages and guidance. The root reflects themes of significant communication and the responsibility of transmitting truths that guide and shape lives. نَبِيٌّ highlights the elevated role of a prophet as a messenger entrusted with delivering divine wisdom and commands to humanity.",
  "3963": "نَبَّأَ and related words stem from the root ن-ب-أ, with the root verb نَبَأَ meaning \"he informed,\" \"he announced,\" or \"he brought news.\" نَبَّأَ means \"he informed thoroughly\" or \"he gave detailed news,\" emphasizing a deliberate and emphatic act of delivering information. This intensified form of the root highlights the importance of the content being conveyed, often involving significant or prophetic matters. The root conveys themes of precision, clarity, and depth in communication, highlighting the role of informing with detail and purpose.",
  "3964": "نَبْتَهِلْ and related words stem from the root ب-ه-ل, with the root verb بَهَلَ meaning \"he cursed\" or \"he left someone to their own will or judgment.\" تَبَاهَلَ signifies mutual cursing or supplication. نَبْتَهِلْ means \"we mutually invoke a curse,\" specifically when opposing parties call upon Allah (ﷻ) to expose falsehood or wrongdoing through His divine judgment. The root conveys two interconnected ideas: leaving the person to their own judgment, abandoning further efforts to convince them, and instead turning to Allah (ﷻ) with a solemn invocation to uncover the truth. This transition highlights reliance on Allah's (ﷻ) intervention to resolve disputes and expose falsehoods beyond human means.",
  "3965": "نَبْرَأَ and related words stem from the root ب-ر-أ, with the root verb بَرَأَ meaning \"he brought into being.\" نَبْرَأَ means \"We bring into existence,\" referring to the act of creating life or existence. The use of \"We\" here refers to Allah (ﷻ), expressed in the plural of majesty to denote His supreme authority, grandeur, and power. The root conveys themes of creation, origination, and bringing forth something entirely new with precision and purpose. نَبْرَأُ reflects the divine act of creation, emphasizing Allah’s (ﷻ) unparalleled wisdom and ability to bring all things into existence perfectly and harmoniously.",
  "3966": "نَتَجَاوَزُ and related words stem from the root ج-و-ز, with the root verb جَازَ meaning \"he passed over\" or \"he crossed.\" The root encompasses themes of crossing, transitioning, surpassing, and moving beyond boundaries. جَاوَزَ means \"he exceeded\" or \"he transgressed,\" and نَتَجَاوَزُ means \"we overlook\" or \"we pardon,\" reflecting the act of passing over faults or errors. This connection highlights the root's dual association with exceeding limits and extending forgiveness, emphasizing the values of compassion and mercy.",
  "3967": "نَتَقَ and related words stem from the root ن-ت-ق, with the root verb نَتَقَ meaning \"he shook\" or \"he shook violently.\" This term conveys the act of forcefully shaking, lifting, or uprooting something, often to remove or dislodge it. The root also encompasses themes of separation and extraction, highlighting the dynamic process of detachment from a fixed position. This connection highlights the transformative nature of such actions, reflecting on the disruption of stability and the initiation of change.",
  "3968": "نَجَا and related words stem from the root ن-ج-و, with the root verb نَجَا meaning \"he became safe\" or \"he escaped.\" The root conveys themes of deliverance, separation, and the act of being removed from harm or danger. نَجَا reflects the concept of successfully escaping peril, highlighting both the vulnerability of the individual and the intervention required for salvation. The connection emphasizes themes of protection, mercy, and hope, as the act of being saved often implies reliance on external help, whether divine or human. This highlights the importance of seeking refuge and trusting in the source of deliverance, while also appreciating the transformative relief that salvation brings.",
  "3969": "نَجَاةٌ and related words stem from the root ن-ج-و, with the root verb نَجَا meaning \"he became safe\" or \"he escaped.\" نَجَاةٌ means \"salvation,\" \"deliverance,\" or \"safety.\" The connection lies in the state of being rescued or spared from harm, highlighting themes of divine mercy and protection. This term reflects spiritual salvation and emphasizes the importance of striving for safety from punishment through faith, repentance, and righteous actions.",
  "3970": "نَجَسٌ and related words stem from the root ن-ج-س, with the root verb نَجُسَ meaning \"he was impure\" or \"he became unclean.\" نَجَسٌ means \"impurity\" or \"filth,\" referring to both physical and spiritual uncleanness. The root extends to themes of defilement and contamination, emphasizing the importance of purification in every aspect of life. This connection highlights the necessity of maintaining both external cleanliness and internal righteousness, fostering purity in body, soul, and conduct.",
  "3971": "نَجِيٌّ and related words stem from the root ن-ج-و, with the root verb نَجَا meaning \"he became safe\" or \"he conversed secretly.\" نَجِيٌّ means \"confidant\" or \"intimate companion,\" referring to someone who engages in trusted and private communication. The word reflects a state of closeness and exclusivity, emphasizing the trust and intimacy required for confidential exchanges. This term highlights the profound nature of such relationships, where private discourse conveys not only secrecy but also a sense of elevation and distinction. The connection lies in the root’s themes of nearness and separation from others, symbolizing a privileged relationship built on trust and exclusivity.",
  "3972": "نَجَّىٰ and related words stem from the root ن-ج-و, with the root verb نَجَا meaning \"he became safe\" or \"he escaped.\" نَجَّىٰ is an intensified form meaning \"he saved\" or \"he delivered,\" indicating an active role in saving or delivering another from harm. The connection lies in providing salvation and protection, reflecting themes of mercy, aid, and divine deliverance.",
  "3973": "نَجْدَيْنِ and related words stem from the root ن-ج-د, with the root verb نَجَدَ encompassing meanings such as \"he rose high,\" \"he exerted effort,\" \"he overcame or surpassed,\" and \"it became apparent or evident.\" نَجْدَيْنِ means \"two elevated roads\" or \"two visible paths.\" The root conveys broader themes of elevation, clarity, prominence, effort, and manifestation. This connection emphasizes the concept of distinct and visible choices, symbolizing moral clarity and the exertion required to navigate life’s challenges. In the Qur'an, it refers to the two clear paths of good and evil, urging human responsibility to discern and choose wisely, striving with effort and purpose toward righteousness.",
  "3974": "نَجْمٌ and related words stem from the root ن-ج-م, with the root verb نَجَمَ meaning \"it appeared,\" \"it rose,\" or \"it emerged.\" نَجْمٌ means \"star,\" referring to celestial bodies that rise and illuminate the night sky. The root also extends to describe plants without stems that emerge from the earth and periodic payments due at intervals. The connection lies in the recurring act of emergence, whether in the sky, the earth, or timing. Stars symbolize guidance, cosmic order, and divine precision, serving as markers for navigation and reflections of Allah’s (ﷻ) intricate design. The rising and appearing emphasized by the root highlight themes of renewal, purpose, and recognition of Allah’s (ﷻ) wisdom in creation.",
  "3975": "نَجْوَىٰ and related words stem from the root ن-ج-و, with the root verb نَجَا meaning \"he became safe\" or \"he conversed secretly.\" نَجْوَىٰ means \"secret conversation\" or \"confidential talk,\" emphasizing private communication. The connection lies in the intimacy and trust inherent in such exchanges, highlighting themes of sincerity and the consequences of secrecy. This term reflects the dual nature of private discussions, whether for good or ill, emphasizing accountability and the intentions behind concealed actions.",
  "3976": "نَحِسَاتٍ and related words stem from the root ن-ح-س, with the root verb نَحِسَ meaning \"he was unlucky\" or \"he was ill-fated.\" نَحِسَاتٍ means \"ill-omened,\" \"unlucky,\" or \"inauspicious,\" often describing days, times, or events perceived as bringing misfortune or calamity. The root conveys themes of adversity, difficulty, and negative outcomes. The connection lies in the characterization of these times as warnings or manifestations of divine displeasure, tied to human actions or collective wrongdoing.",
  "3977": "نَحْبٌ and related words stem from the root ن-ح-ب, with the root verb نَحَبَ meaning \"he vowed,\" \"he promised solemnly,\" or \"he raised his voice in intense weeping.\" نَحْبٌ means \"vow,\" \"solemn promise,\" or \"appointed term,\" and in some contexts refers to \"death\" or \"ultimate fulfillment.\" The root conveys themes of deep emotional intensity, personal sacrifice, and unwavering commitment. The connection lies in the profound nature of a vow, which often involves significant effort, dedication, or even ultimate sacrifice. This term highlights the seriousness of commitments, emphasizing sincerity, perseverance, and fulfilling promises despite adversity or cost.",
  "3978": "نَحْسٌ and related words stem from the root ن-ح-س, with the root verb نَحِسَ meaning \"he was unlucky\" or \"he was ill-fated.\" نَحْسٌ means \"misfortune,\" \"ill luck,\" or \"adversity,\" referring to states of hardship or calamity often linked to divine punishment or warnings. The root reflects the idea of consequences for actions, serving as a reminder of the perils of disbelief or disobedience. The connection lies in the depiction of نَحْسٌ as a manifestation of divine justice, emphasizing the stark outcomes of rejecting truth or engaging in wrongdoing. This highlights the importance of striving for righteousness and seeking Allah’s (ﷻ) mercy to avoid falling into states of adversity or hardship.",
  "3979": "نَحْلٌ and related words stem from the root ن-ح-ل, with the root verb نَحَلَ meaning \"he gave as a gift.\" نَحْلٌ means \"bees,\" highlighting their role as a divine gift to humanity, providing honey and pollination. The connection lies in the sustenance and benefits they offer, symbolizing themes of generosity, industry, and balance in creation. Bees reflect the intricate cooperation and harmony in Allah’s (ﷻ) design, reminding humanity of the blessings and wisdom inherent in His creation.",
  "3980": "نَخِرَةٌ and related words stem from the root ن-خ-ر, with the root verb نَخِرَ meaning \"it decayed\" or \"it became rotten.\" نَخِرَةٌ means \"decayed,\" \"rotten,\" or \"crumbled,\" often describing bones. The connection lies in the state of decomposition, highlighting themes of mortality, the transient nature of life, and the inevitability of death. This serves as a reminder of human fragility and the importance of preparing for the afterlife.",
  "3981": "نَخِيلٌ and related words stem from the root ن-خ-ل, with the root verb نَخَلَ meaning \"he sifted\" or \"he purified by sifting.\" The root conveys notions of separation, refinement, and selecting the best. نَخِيلٌ means \"palm groves,\" representing an assembly of these valuable trees. The connection may lie in the refined nature of the date palm’s fruits, which are carefully harvested, emphasizing their value as a source of nourishment and sustenance. Palm trees are central to life in arid regions, symbolizing abundance, resilience, and divine blessings.",
  "3982": "نَخْزَىٰ and related words stem from the root خ-ز-ي, with the root verb خَزِيَ meaning \"he was ashamed\" or \"he was disgraced.\" نَخْزَىٰ translates as \"we are disgraced\" or \"we become humiliated,\" expressing an experience of shame or dishonor. The root conveys themes of shame, loss of dignity, and humiliation. This word highlights the deep impact of disgrace, where one is stripped of honor and left vulnerable to humiliation, reflecting the consequences of failure or wrongdoing.",
  "3983": "نَخْلٌ and related words stem from the root ن-خ-ل, with the root verb نَخَلَ meaning \"he sifted\" or \"he purified.\" نَخْلٌ means \"date palms\" or \"palm trees.\" The connection lies in the process of sifting and refining, akin to the cultivation and harvesting of palm trees, which provide vital sustenance. These trees symbolize nourishment, life, and divine provision, as their fruit and shade sustain entire communities. The act of sifting also metaphorically reflects selecting the finest, mirroring how the palm tree stands as a refined and essential element of life in harsh climates.",
  "3984": "نَخْلَةٌ and related words stem from the root ن-خ-ل, with the root verb نَخَلَ meaning \"he sifted\" or \"he separated impurities.\" نَخْلَةٌ refers to a \"date palm\" or \"palm tree,\" emphasizing its vital role in the ecosystem. The connection lies in the tree’s provision of fruit, shade, and support for life, reflecting its essential contribution to sustaining communities. The root’s association with refinement and selection highlights the balance of creation, where every aspect serves a purpose, pointing to the generosity and wisdom of Allah (ﷻ).",
  "3985": "نَدَامَةٌ and related words stem from the root ن-د-م, with the root verb نَدِمَ meaning \"he regretted\" or \"he felt remorse.\" نَدَامَةٌ means \"regret\" or \"remorse,\" capturing the intense sorrow experienced upon realizing one’s mistakes. The root emphasizes the emotional depth of regret over past actions or decisions. In some contexts, نَدَامَةٌ highlights regret when it is too late to amend one’s actions, serving as a powerful reminder of the consequences of neglecting responsibility. The term highlights the gravity of accountability and the emotional burden of realizing the truth of one’s deeds.",
  "3986": "نَدِيٌّ and related words stem from the root ن-د-ي, with the root verb نَدَا meaning \"he called,\" \"he proclaimed,\" or \"he invited.\" نَدِيٌّ means \"assembly\" or \"council,\" focusing on the group of people gathered together, often for consultation or discussion. The root conveys concepts of calling and gathering, with نَدِيٌّ highlighting the participants brought together by the call, emphasizing the assembly itself rather than the space.",
  "3987": "نَذَرَ and related words stem from the root ن-ذ-ر, with the root verb نَذَرَ meaning \"he vowed\" or \"he made a solemn promise.\" The connection lies in committing oneself to a pledge or undertaking, reflecting the root's emphasis on vows and dedication. It highlights the seriousness of making promises and the importance of fulfilling one's commitments.",
  "3988": "نَذِلَّ and related words stem from the root ذ-ل-ل, with the root verb ذَلَّ meaning \"he was lowly, humbled, or became submissive.\" نَذِلَّ means \"we become humbled\" or \"we become humiliated.\" This directly connects to the root's concept of experiencing humility or abasement. It reflects a collective acknowledgment of humility, perhaps in supplication or recognition of human limitations before a higher power, emphasizing the importance of collective humility in spiritual or communal contexts.",
  "3989": "نَذِيرٌ and related words stem from the root ن-ذ-ر, with the root verb نَذَرَ meaning \"he warned\" or \"he vowed.\" This root includes the concepts of warning others and making serious commitments. نَذِيرٌ means \"a warner\" or \"a warning.\" It can refer to a person who warns or the warning message itself. The connection lies in the root's focus on cautioning others. نَذِيرٌ embodies the act of delivering important warnings meant to prevent harm or guide behavior, reflecting the root's essence by emphasizing the significance of heeding such cautions.",
  "3990": "نَذْرٌ and related words stem from the root ن-ذ-ر, with the root verb نَذَرَ meaning \"he vowed\" or \"he made a solemn promise.\" The root encompasses concepts of making vows, dedicating oneself, and issuing warnings. نَذْرٌ means \"a vow\" or \"solemn promise.\" It signifies a serious commitment made to perform a specific action or abstain from something, often as an act of devotion. The connection lies in the root's emphasis on solemn commitments and obligations. نَذْرٌ reflects the gravity and sincerity involved in making a vow, embodying the root's essence by highlighting the moral and spiritual weight of such promises.",
  "3991": "نَزَعَ and related words stem from the root ن-ز-ع, and as the root verb, it means \"he pulled out,\" \"he extracted,\" or \"he tore away.\" The root conveys themes of deliberate and forceful removal, whether physical or metaphorical. It also encompasses ideas of separation, withdrawal, or departure, emphasizing the exertion and intention involved. The connection is direct, as نَزَعَ encapsulates the fundamental action of the root, reflecting acts of extraction or displacement. It represents not only physical actions but also the figurative pulling away of intangible things, such as emotions, authority, or states.",
  "3992": "نَزَغَ and related words stem from the root ن-ز-غ, meaning \"he incited,\" \"he instigated,\" or \"he tempted.\" The root involves concepts of provoking, stirring up discord, or causing mischief. نَزَغَ means \"he incited\" or \"he instigated.\" It represents the act of provoking others into conflict or wrongdoing. The connection lies in the root's focus on sowing discord. نَزَغَ embodies the subtle yet harmful actions that lead to strife, reflecting the root's essence by highlighting the destructive impact of incitement and the importance of resisting such provocations.",
  "3993": "نَزَلَ and related words stem from the root ن-ز-ل, and as the root verb, it means \"he or it descended,\" or \"he or it came down.\" It conveys the fundamental action of moving from a higher place to a lower one or stopping at a location during a journey. This core meaning of descending is central to the root's concept, encompassing both physical and metaphorical descent. In the Qur'an, نَزَلَ is often associated with the descent of angels, revelations, or blessings from Allah (ﷻ), highlighting the connection between the divine and the earthly realms.",
  "3994": "نَزَّاعَةٌ and related words stem from the root ن-ز-ع, with the root verb نَزَعَ meaning \"he pulled out\" or \"he extracted.\" نَزَّاعَةٌ is an intensive form indicating repeated or forceful extraction, meaning \"intensely extracting\" or \"relentlessly pulling out.\" The root further conveys ideas of stripping away, uprooting, or violently separating. In the Qur'an, it describes something that forcefully strips or tears away, emphasizing the overwhelming severity of the action. The connection lies in the amplification of the root's core concept, where نَزَّاعَةٌ heightens the idea of extraction to reflect relentless force and intensity, embodying the root's essence by portraying overpowering and unstoppable action.",
  "3995": "نَزَّلَ and related words stem from the root ن-ز-ل, with the root verb نَزَلَ meaning \"he descended.\" نَزَّلَ is an intensified form meaning \"he sent down gradually\" or \"he revealed.\" This verb emphasizes a deliberate and systematic process of descent, building upon the root's concept of descending. In the Qur'anic context, نَزَّلَ describes how Allah (ﷻ) revealed the Qur'an to Prophet Muhammad (ﷺ) over time, facilitating deeper understanding and allowing the guidance to address specific circumstances as they arose.",
  "3996": "نَزْغٌ and related words stem from the root ن-ز-غ, with the root verb نَزَغَ meaning \"he incited\" or \"he instigated.\" This root encompasses concepts of provocation and stirring up mischief. نَزْغٌ means \"instigation,\" \"temptation,\" or \"mischief.\" It refers to the act or influence that leads individuals toward conflict or wrongdoing. The connection lies in the root's emphasis on the sources of discord. نَزْغٌ represents the catalysts that disrupt harmony, embodying the root's essence by highlighting the need for vigilance against such negative influences.",
  "3997": "نَزْلَةٌ and related words stem from the root ن-ز-ل, with the root verb نَزَلَ meaning \"he descended\" or \"he came down.\" نَزْلَةٌ refers to \"a descent\" or \"a single act of descending,\" representing an instance of coming down from a higher to a lower place. This term emphasizes the singularity or specificity of the act, aligning with the root’s broader concept of transition and movement between levels. The term also conveys the gravity or importance of the act of descending, particularly in contexts where what descends carries weighty significance.",
  "3998": "نَسَبٌ and related words stem from the root ن-س-ب, with the root verb نَسَبَ meaning \"he attributed,\" \"he related,\" or \"he assigned.\" نَسَبٌ means \"lineage,\" \"kinship,\" or \"relationship,\" referring to one's ancestry and familial ties. The term encapsulates the inherent connection within blood relationships, as it involves attributing shared characteristics, identity, and heritage to a common origin. نَسَبٌ emphasizes the continuity of these ties, highlighting the deep bond and mutual obligations that define family and lineage, rooted in the act of attributing and assigning belonging.",
  "3999": "نَسِمُ and related words stem from the root و-س-م, with the root verb وَسَمَ meaning \"he branded,\" \"he marked,\" or \"he imprinted.\" نَسِمُ means \"we brand,\" referring to the act of creating a permanent mark. The root emphasizes themes of marking for identification, ownership, or distinction. In the Qur'an, branding symbolizes humiliation and divine punishment, as marking the \"snout\" reflects disgrace and dishonor. This highlights how branding signifies both a literal mark and a reminder of accountability and consequences for arrogance.",
  "4000": "نَسِيءٌ and related words stem from the root ن-س-أ, with the root verb نَسَأَ meaning \"he postponed\" or \"he delayed.\" نَسِيءٌ means \"postponement\" or \"deferral,\" referring to the act of delaying or altering something from its appointed time. The term highlights the deliberate adjustment of established schedules or obligations, often with significant consequences. In the Qur'an, نَسِيءٌ denotes the pre-Islamic practice of deferring the sacred months to manipulate the calendar for personal gain.This reflects the root’s emphasis on deferral, reminding of the importance of adhering to prescribed times and the potential imbalance caused by unnecessary delays.",
  "4001": "نَسِيَ and related words stem from the root ن-س-ي, and as the root verb, it means \"he forgot.\" This foundational meaning captures both unintentional forgetfulness and deliberate acts of neglect or omission. The root broadly extends to themes of memory, abandonment, and disregard, emphasizing the transient and fragile nature of human awareness and attention. The word reflects the vulnerability of memory, whether due to human limitations or external circumstances, serving as a reminder of the ease with which things can slip from consciousness.",
  "4002": "نَسِيًّا and related words stem from the root ن-س-ي, with the root verb نَسِيَ meaning \"he forgot.\" نَسِيًّا means \"forgetful\" or \"prone to forgetfulness.\" The root also conveys themes of neglect and omission, whether deliberate or unintentional. In some contexts, نَسِيًّا may describe something disregarded or forgotten, emphasizing insignificance. However, in its Qur'anic usage, as in وَمَا كَانَ رَبُّكَ نَسِيًّا, it affirms Allah’s (ﷻ) perfect awareness and the impossibility of forgetfulness, highlighting His complete knowledge and vigilance.",
  "4003": "دَرَجَةٌ and related words stem from the root د-ر-ج, with the root verb دَرَجَ meaning \"he proceeded gradually\" or \"he ascended or advanced step by step.\" This root conveys structured advancement. دَرَجَةٌ refers to \"degree,\" \"rank,\" or \"level,\" emphasizing elevation within a system. Just as steady progress happens in stages, this word reflects how ranks or statuses are achieved gradually. The root revolves around progression, movement, and aging, reinforcing that rising in status, knowledge, or capability occurs step by step.",
  "4004": "نَسْتَنْسِخُ and related words stem from the root ن-س-خ, with the root verb نَسَخَ meaning \"he copied,\" \"he transcribed,\" or \"he abrogated.\" اِسْتَنْسَخَ means \"he had something written down\" or \"he caused something to be transcribed,\" and نَسْتَنْسِخُ means \"We cause to be recorded\" or \"We transcribe,\" emphasizing the act of preserving and documenting. This relates to the root's concept of copying, which includes accuracy, continuity, and record-keeping. The term highlights the importance of writing essential matters for preservation and judgment, reflecting the divine act of recording deeds as ultimate accountability.",
  "4005": "نَسْرٌ and related words stem from the root ن-س-ر, which encompasses meanings such as \"tearing,\" \"plucking,\" or \"scattering.\" نَسْرٌ specifically refers to the idol Nasr, worshipped by the people of Prophet Noah ﷺ. According to Islamic tradition, Nasr was originally a righteous man whose memory was honored after his death, but over time, misguided devotion led to idol worship. The root reflects themes of dispersal and separation, symbolizing the scattering of truth and unity when people deviate from pure monotheism. The story of Nasr serves as a reminder of the dangers of misplacing reverence, which should be directed solely to Allah (ﷻ), the true source of guidance and worship.",
  "4006": "نَسْفٌ and related words stem from the root ن-س-ف, with the root verb نَسَفَ meaning \"he winnowed,\" \"he scattered,\" or \"he pulverized.\" نَسْفٌ means \"scattering,\" \"pulverizing,\" or \"dispersing,\" emphasizing the act of breaking something into pieces and dispersing it. The root encompasses both forceful destruction and the resulting dispersal of fragments, often implying a complete and thorough process. نَسْفٌ captures the imagery of intense fragmentation, whether applied to physical objects, such as mountains, or symbolic entities, emphasizing total obliteration followed by widespread dispersal.",
  "4007": "نَسْفَعًا and related words stem from the root س-ف-ع, with the root verb سَفَعَ meaning \"he seized,\" \"he grabbed,\" or \"he branded.\" نَسْفَعًا means \"We will surely seize\" or \"We will certainly drag.\" The connection lies in the forceful act of grabbing or seizing, directly relating to the root's emphasis on grasping firmly. In the Qur'anic context, it serves as a stern warning of severe consequences for defiance, illustrating the power and authority of divine retribution against those who persist in wrongdoing.",
  "4008": "نَسْلٌ and related words stem from the root ن-س-ل, with the root verb نَسَلَ meaning \"he begot,\" \"he reproduced,\" or \"he procreated.\" نَسْلٌ refers to \"offspring,\" \"progeny,\" or \"descendants,\" highlighting the concept of perpetuation and the continuation of life. The root also conveys the idea of swift motion or dispersal, which complements the notion of life spreading rapidly through generations. The connection lies in the shared emphasis on continuity—whether through lineage or dynamic movement. نَسْلٌ captures the essence of generational flow, linking the physical act of reproduction to the broader concept of life's propagation and dispersal.",
  "4009": "نَسْلَخُ and related words stem from the root س-ل-خ, with the root verb سَلَخَ meaning \"he stripped off,\" \"he flayed,\" or \"he removed (skin).\" نَسْلَخُ means \"We strip off,\" \"We remove.\" The connection lies in the act of removing or separating layers, directly reflecting the root's concept. In a Qur'anic context, it refers to Allah (ﷻ) removing the day from the night, symbolizing the natural cycles and divine control over creation, emphasizing themes of transformation and renewal.",
  "4010": "نَسْيًا and related words stem from the root ن-س-ي, with the root verb نَسِيَ meaning \"he forgot\" or \"it slipped from memory.\" نَسْيًا means \"a forgotten thing\" or \"something of no account.\" The root also conveys broader dimensions such as neglect, abandonment, and disregard, emphasizing the state of something being left behind or treated as insignificant. This root captures both deliberate forgetting and unintentional lapses, extending to themes of loss, obscurity, and being overlooked. In its usage, نَسْيًا reflects the profound idea of something reduced to irrelevance, with no impact or remembrance, amplifying the concept of total insignificance and detachment.",
  "4011": "نَشْأَةٌ and related words stem from the root ن-ش-أ, with the root verb نَشَأَ meaning \"he originated,\" \"he grew,\" or \"he began.\" نَشْأَةٌ means \"origin,\" \"creation,\" or \"development.\" This term emphasizes the state or phase of being created or developed, focusing on the progression or emergence of something already initiated. The connection lies in the beginning or initial phase of existence, reflecting the root’s emphasis on growth and origination. It highlights stages of development or renewal, such as creation or resurrection, emphasizing the process of existence itself.",
  "4012": "نَشْرٌ and related words stem from the root ن-ش-ر, with the root verb نَشَرَ meaning \"he spread out,\" \"he unfolded,\" or \"he revived.\" نَشْرٌ means \"spreading,\" \"dissemination,\" or \"revival.\" The root captures the transition from a compact or hidden state to an expansive or open one, symbolizing the act of making something accessible or evident. This term embodies themes of distribution and rejuvenation, where what was confined is made widespread or restored.",
  "4013": "نَشْطٌ and related words stem from the root ن-ش-ط, with the root verb نَشَطَ meaning \"he untied,\" \"he loosened,\" or \"he became active.\" نَشْطٌ means \"untying,\" \"loosening,\" or \"release,\" emphasizing the act of freeing or transitioning from constraint to freedom. The root conveys not only physical untying but also the energetic movement that follows release. This term reflects liberation, purposeful activity, and the transition from a state of restriction to one of dynamic freedom, capturing the root’s dual emphasis on effort and ease.",
  "4014": "نَصَبٌ and related words stem from the root ن-ص-ب, with the root verb نَصَبَ meaning \"he toiled,\" \"he labored,\" or \"he endured hardship.\" نَصَبٌ means \"toil,\" \"fatigue,\" or \"hardship,\" highlighting the physical and emotional strain that results from sustained effort or challenges. The root also conveys the sense of being burdened or wearied by exertion, whether in worldly tasks or enduring trials. نَصَبٌ encapsulates the struggles inherent in life’s endeavors, serving as a reminder of the need for balance and alignment with purpose to ensure that efforts are meaningful and rewarding.",
  "4015": "نَصَحُوا and related words stem from the root ن-ص-ح, with the root verb نَصَحَ meaning \"he advised sincerely\" or \"he was sincere.\" نَصَحُوا means \"they advised sincerely\" or \"they were sincere,\" emphasizing the collective act of offering genuine counsel. The connection lies in shared sincerity and the communal responsibility to act with purity and honesty. This term highlights the importance of collective sincerity in fostering trust and harmony within communities.",
  "4016": "نَصَرَ and related words stem from the root ن-ص-ر, and as the root verb, it means \"he helped\" or \"he gave victory.\" It signifies the fundamental act of providing assistance, emphasizing support that leads to overcoming challenges or achieving success. The root encompasses the ideas of aid, triumph, and strength, highlighting the transformative power of help in securing victory and resolving difficulties. This reflects the importance of collaboration and reliance on Allah (ﷻ) or human support in achieving outcomes.",
  "4017": "نَصُوحٌ and related words stem from the root ن-ص-ح, with the root verb نَصَحَ meaning \"he was sincere,\" \"he was pure,\" or \"he acted with integrity.\" نَصُوحٌ means \"most sincere,\" \"pure,\" or \"faithful,\" referring to the highest level of sincerity and genuineness. The root conveys themes of purity, refinement, and the absence of deceit, emphasizing intentions and actions that are free from flaws or ulterior motives. In the Qur'anic context, \"توبةً نَصُوحًا\" refers to repentance that is completely sincere, involving heartfelt remorse and a firm resolve to avoid sin. This term highlights that purity of intent leads to moral elevation and spiritual renewal, reflecting the transformative power of genuine sincerity.",
  "4018": "نَصِيبٌ and related words stem from the root ن-ص-ب, with the root verb نَصَبَ meaning \"he set up\" or \"he assigned.\" نَصِيبٌ means \"share,\" \"portion,\" or \"lot,\" referring to what has been allocated or established for someone. The connection lies in the act of assigning or designating a portion, directly relating to the root's theme of establishing or dividing. This term highlights the concept of fairness and predestination, often associated with wealth, inheritance, or fate, reflecting the deliberate and equitable apportionment rooted in divine wisdom.",
  "4019": "نَصِيرٌ and related words stem from the root ن-ص-ر, with the root verb نَصَرَ meaning \"he helped.\" نَصِيرٌ means \"strong helper\" or \"steadfast protector,\" referring to one who provides significant assistance or defense. The connection lies in the root's focus on aid and support, particularly in moments of need. نَصِيرٌ embodies the idea of active involvement in ensuring success or safety, reflecting the root’s emphasis on providing unwavering support that brings relief and resolution.",
  "4020": "نَصْرٌ and related words stem from the root ن-ص-ر, with the root verb نَصَرَ meaning \"he helped.\" نَصْرٌ means \"help,\" \"aid,\" or \"victory,\" emphasizing assistance that leads to triumph. The term captures the outcome of effective support, whether in physical, moral, or spiritual contexts. The root’s emphasis on aid aligns with نَصْرٌ as the result of combined effort and support, highlighting the power of help in achieving decisive success and overcoming adversity.",
  "4021": "نَصْرَانِيٌّ and related words stem from the root ن-ص-ر, with the root verb نَصَرَ meaning \"he helped\" or \"he assisted.\" نَصْرَانِيٌّ refers to \"a Christian,\" derived from نَصْرَان, associated with Nazareth, the town linked to Prophet Yeshua (ﷺ). The term emphasizes the geographical and cultural connection of early Christians to Nazareth. The root’s theme of assistance is reflected in the disciples of Prophet Yeshua (ﷺ), known as الحَوَارِيُّونَ, who supported him in spreading his message. نَصْرَانِيٌّ encapsulates the religious and cultural identity of early followers of Prophet Yeshua (ﷺ) and their ties to Nazareth, highlighting mutual support and unity central to the root’s meaning.",
  "4022": "نَضِجَتْ and related words stem from the root ن-ض-ج, with the root verb نَضَجَ meaning \"it became ripe\" or \"it was fully cooked,\" indicating something reaching its state of completion or perfection. نَضِجَتْ means \"it became fully burned,\" emphasizing the thorough and complete transformation of something through heat. The connection lies in the root's focus on maturity and culmination, whether in ripening, cooking, or burning. In the Qur'anic context, it describes the skins being fully burned and then renewed, highlighting the completeness and ongoing nature of the punishment.",
  "4023": "نَضِيدٌ and related words stem from the root ن-ض-د, with the root verb نَضَدَ meaning \"he piled up,\" \"he arranged,\" or \"he set things in order by placing one upon another.\" نَضِيدٌ means \"arranged in layers\" or \"piled up,\" reflecting meticulous organization and abundance. The root emphasizes careful arrangement and deliberate stacking, whether in the context of blessings abundantly bestowed or objects layered and prepared for another purpose. This highlights the precision and intentionality in creating order, whether for reward, sustenance, or consequence, highlighting the balance between abundance and purpose in the arrangement of all things.",
  "4024": "نَضّاخَتان and related words stem from the root ن-ض-خ, with the root verb نَضَخَ meaning \"it gushed forth,\" signifying a forceful and abundant outpouring of liquid. نَضّاخَتان refers to \"two gushing springs,\" emphasizing an abundant and continuous flow. The root conveys the idea of profusion and energy, highlighting the vitality and generosity of the flow. In the Qur'anic description of Paradise, it portrays two springs gushing forth, symbolizing the abundance and perpetual blessings of the afterlife, reflecting the root’s themes of plentiful provision and dynamic outpouring.",
  "4025": "نَضْرَةٌ and related words stem from the root ن-ض-ر, with the root verb نَضَرَ meaning \"he became fresh,\" \"bloomed,\" or \"flourished.\" نَضْرَةٌ refers to \"brightness,\" \"radiance,\" or \"freshness,\" capturing the essence of vitality and luminous beauty. The root conveys themes of renewal, growth, and flourishing, often associated with the healthy vibrancy of life. نَضْرَةٌ symbolizes an outward glow that reflects inner vitality, linking physical brightness to well-being and spiritual contentment. This connection highlights the harmony between external beauty and inner flourishing, emphasizing renewal and vitality as signs of divine favor and perfection in creation.",
  "4026": "نَطِيحَةٌ and related words stem from the root ن-ط-ح, with the root verb نَطَحَ meaning \"he butted\" or \"he gored,\" referring to an animal striking with its horns. نَطِيحَةٌ means \"an animal that has been gored\" or \"killed by butting.\" The connection lies in the direct action of butting causing the death of the animal, rendering it unlawful for consumption according to Islamic dietary laws. This emphasizes the root's concept of forceful impact leading to harm or death, highlighting the importance of proper methods in slaughter and avoiding consumption of such animals.",
  "4027": "نَطْوِي and related words stem from the root ط-و-ي, with the root verb طَوَىٰ meaning \"he folded\" or \"he rolled up.\" نَطْوِي means \"we fold\" or \"we roll up.\" The connection lies in the act of folding or gathering something together, emphasizing the concept of compacting or bringing things into a smaller form. This term suggests the action of organizing, storing, or preparing something for a later time, reflecting the root's focus on transformation and change in form.",
  "4028": "نَظَرٌ and related words stem from the root ن-ظ-ر, with the root verb نَظَرَ meaning \"he looked,\" \"he observed,\" or \"he considered.\" نَظَرٌ means \"the look,\" \"observation,\" or \"consideration.\" It encapsulates the act of seeing or contemplating something carefully. The connection lies in the root's focus on perception and thoughtful reflection, emphasizing the importance of using one's faculties to reflect on the signs of Allah (ﷻ) in the universe.",
  "4029": "نَظَرَ and related words stem from the root ن-ظ-ر, meaning \"he looked,\" \"he observed,\" or \"he considered.\" This root verb conveys the act of perceiving with sight or contemplating with thought, combining both physical and intellectual observation. The root emphasizes thoughtful reflection, deliberate observation, and the pursuit of understanding. It highlights the role of perception and contemplation in gaining knowledge, fostering awareness, and recognizing the signs of Allah (ﷻ) in creation, encouraging mindfulness and insight in all aspects of life.",
  "4030": "نَظِرَةٌ and related words stem from the root ن-ظ-ر, with the root verb نَظَرَ meaning \"he looked,\" \"he observed,\" or \"he considered.\" نَظِرَةٌ means \"a respite,\" \"a delay,\" or \"time given.\" The connection lies in granting time or considering a postponement, reflecting the root's emphasis on observation and contemplation extending to allowing time for reflection or repayment. In the Qur'anic context, it instructs giving time to debtors in difficulty, emphasizing mercy and compassion.",
  "4031": "نَظْرَةٌ and related words stem from the root ن-ظ-ر, with the root verb نَظَرَ meaning \"he looked,\" \"he observed,\" or \"he considered.\" نَظْرَةٌ means \"a glance,\" \"a gaze,\" or \"a look.\" It captures the act of observing or contemplating something, often implying attention or consideration. The connection lies in the root's focus on sight and perception, emphasizing the significance of even a single glance in understanding or moral accountability.",
  "4032": "The particle نَعَمٌ means \"yes\" and serves as an affirmation to express agreement, approval, or confirmation in response to a question, statement, or command. It is widely used in polite affirmations, direct answers, and to emphasize certainty or resolve. In classical Arabic, نَعَمٌ was employed in dialogue to provide clear and respectful responses, ensuring the listener understood the speaker's agreement. Unlike بَلَى, which is used to negate a negative question, نَعَمٌ straightforwardly affirms without negating anything. Its usage reflects the precision and clarity valued in Arabic communication, emphasizing the importance of clear affirmation in dialogue and interpersonal exchanges.",
  "4033": "نَعِيمٌ and related words stem from the root ن-ع-م, with the root verb نَعِمَ meaning \"he was at ease,\" \"he enjoyed comfort,\" or \"he lived pleasantly.\" نَعِيمٌ means \"bliss,\" \"delight,\" or \"luxury,\" referring to a state of profound comfort, happiness, and enjoyment. The root’s emphasis on ease and pleasant living connects to the idea of enduring comfort and satisfaction, associated with blessings or rewards. ",
  "4034": "نَعَّمَ and related words stem from the root ن-ع-م, with the root verb نَعِمَ meaning \"he was at ease,\" \"he enjoyed comfort.\" نَعَّمَ means \"he made someone live in ease\" or \"he granted comforts and luxury.\" Unlike أَنْعَمَ, it emphasizes actively increasing or providing material comfort, luxury, or physical well-being. This term reflects the root’s emphasis on ease and enjoyment but highlights deliberate acts of generosity, often focusing on tangible or physical blessings.",
  "4035": "نَعْجَةٌ and related words stem from the root ن-ع-ج, with the root verb نَعَجَ meaning \"to bleat,\" referring to the cry of a sheep. نَعْجَةٌ specifically denotes \"an ewe\" or \"a female sheep.\" The root conveys associations with softness and gentleness, characteristics attributed to female sheep. In classical Arabic, نَعْجَةٌ symbolizes meekness and docility, often used metaphorically to represent submissiveness or innocence.",
  "4036": "نَعْلَيْنِ and related words stem from the root ن-ع-ل, with the root verb نَعَلَ meaning \"he put on sandals\" or \"he shoed (someone).\" نَعْلَيْنِ is the dual form of نَعْلٌ, meaning \"two sandals.\" The root encompasses meanings related to sandals and footwear, emphasizing protection, utility, and mobility. In classical Arabic, نَعْلٌ symbolized both practicality and readiness, as sandals were essential for travel and daily life. The connection highlights the importance of preparing oneself with the necessary provisions for life’s journey, both physical and spiritual.",
  "4037": "نَعْمَاءُ and related words stem from the root ن-ع-م, with the root verb نَعِمَ meaning \"he was at ease,\" \"he enjoyed comfort.\" نَعْمَاءُ means \"blessing,\" \"favor,\" or \"prosperity.\" It refers to being endowed with abundant good and ease. The connection lies in the root's emphasis on comfort and enjoyment, highlighting the favors bestowed by Allah (ﷻ). In the Qur'anic context, it serves as a reminder to be grateful for blessings and recognize them as tests of thankfulness and obedience.",
  "4038": "نَعْمَةٌ and related words stem from the root ن-ع-م, with the root verb نَعِمَ meaning \"he was at ease\" or \"he enjoyed comfort and luxury.\" نَعْمَةٌ refers to a state of ease, luxury, and contentment brought about by blessings or favorable circumstances. It highlights the enjoyment of comfort and prosperity as a reflection of Allah's (ﷻ) provision. The root conveys themes of ease, delight, and satisfaction, emphasizing the transformative power of blessings in bringing tranquility and fulfillment. This word highlights the importance of recognizing such moments of ease as an opportunity for gratitude and reflection, reminding believers of their reliance on Allah's (ﷻ) sustenance.",
  "4039": "نَفَادٌ and related words stem from the root ن-ف-د, with the root verb نَفَدَ meaning \"it was exhausted,\" \"it came to an end,\" or \"it was depleted.\" نَفَادٌ refers to \"exhaustion,\" \"depletion,\" or \"ending,\" emphasizing the idea of something finite reaching its limit or being entirely used up. The root encompasses broader themes of limitation, transience, and the eventual end of all created things. This conveys a profound reminder of the eternal and inexhaustible nature of Allah's (ﷻ) power, knowledge, and provisions. It highlights the dependence of all creation on Allah (ﷻ) as the sole source of sustenance and the ultimate refuge when all else comes to an end.",
  "4040": "نَفَخَ and related words stem from the root ن-ف-خ, and as the root verb, it means \"he blew\" or \"he breathed into.\" The action conveys the forceful exhaling of air with a specific purpose or effect. The root emphasizes initiating movement, transferring energy, or enacting transformation, whether signifying the giving of life, signaling events, or breaking barriers. It highlights creation, change, and power, as the act of blowing serves as a catalyst for physical and spiritual transformation, marking transitions or the start of momentous occurrences.",
  "4041": "نَفَرَ and related words stem from the root ن-ف-ر, with the root verb نَفَرَ meaning \"he departed,\" \"he set out,\" or \"he fled.\" This verb conveys the action of leaving, often quickly or with a specific purpose. The root also encompasses themes of movement, urgency, and sometimes aversion or turning away. The connection lies in the idea of dynamic action, whether departing from a situation out of necessity, aversion, or intentional mobilization. It reflects the dual nature of purposeful departure—either as a deliberate effort toward a goal or as a response to avoid what is undesirable. The root’s versatility highlights human tendencies to act decisively in moments of both pursuit and avoidance.",
  "4042": "نَفَشَتْ and related words stem from the root ن-ف-ش, with the root verb نَفَشَ meaning \"he fluffed up,\" or \"he (or his livestock) grazed by night without a shepherd\" or \"he strayed.\" نَفَشَتْ means \"she or it strayed\" or \"she or it grazed.\" The connection lies in the uncontrolled wandering of animals, akin to wool spreading when fluffed, directly relating to the root's meaning. It reflects the idea of dispersal and lack of guidance, emphasizing the need for direction and oversight.",
  "4043": "نَفَعَ and related words stem from the root ن-ف-ع, and as the root verb, it means \"he benefited,\" \"he was useful,\" or \"he brought advantage.\" The root conveys themes of utility, advantage, and positive impact. ٱلنَّافِعُ, one of Allah's (ﷻ) perfect names, means \"The Benefactor\" or \"The Bestower of Benefits,\" highlighting Allah’s (ﷻ) exclusive ability to provide goodness and advantage to His creation. The connection lies in the root's emphasis on bringing benefit, as ٱلنَّافِعُ signifies that all forms of benefit, whether physical, spiritual, or material, originate solely from Allah (ﷻ). This name serves as a reminder to seek Allah’s (ﷻ) help and trust in His wisdom in guiding us to what is ultimately good.",
  "4044": "نَفَقٌ and related words stem from the root ن-ف-ق, with the root verb نَفَقَ meaning \"he tunneled\" or \"he made an underground passage.\" نَفَقٌ means \"tunnel\" or \"underground passage.\" The connection lies in the physical creation of a concealed pathway, directly relating to the root's meaning. It symbolizes hidden routes and the ability to move unseen, reflecting secrecy or escape.",
  "4045": "نَفَقَةٌ and related words stem from the root ن-ف-ق, with the root verb نَفَقَ meaning \"it expired\" or \"it was depleted,\" and the derived verb أَنْفَقَ meaning \"he spent.\" نَفَقَةٌ means \"expenditure,\" \"maintenance,\" or \"alimony.\" The connection lies in the act of spending resources for the support of others, causing a decrease in one's wealth, directly relating to the root's meaning. It emphasizes the responsibility and commitment to provide financial support.",
  "4046": "نَفِدَ and related words stem from the root ن-ف-د, with the root verb نَفِدَ meaning \"it was exhausted,\" \"it came to an end,\" or \"it was depleted.\" The root highlights themes of limitation and finality, emphasizing that all resources, options, or efforts ultimately reach their endpoint. This sense of depletion aligns with the finite nature of worldly possessions and human capabilities. In a Qur'anic context, the root reflects the contrast between the transient nature of creation and the boundlessness of Allah's (ﷻ) knowledge and power, reminding humankind of their dependence on Him and the limitations inherent in their existence.",
  "4047": "نَفِيرٌ and related words stem from the root ن-ف-ر, with the root verb نَفَرَ meaning \"he departed,\" \"he set out,\" or \"he fled,\" often with urgency or purpose. نَفِيرٌ means \"an army,\" \"a troop,\" or \"manpower,\" referring to a group gathered and mobilized for a specific cause, often in preparation for battle. The connection lies in the concept of departure or movement, as an assembled group departs collectively toward a goal, reflecting the root's emphasis on motion and action. This term highlights the organized and purposeful nature of collective effort, capturing the idea of individuals uniting for a shared objective, whether in defense, confrontation, or collective action.",
  "4048": "نَفّاثَاتٌ and related words stem from the root ن-ف-ث, with the root verb نَفَثَ meaning \"he blew\" or \"he exhaled,\" often accompanied by a slight spitting action. نَفّاثَاتٌ (plural of نَفّاثَةٌ) means \"blowers,\" referring to those who blow repeatedly, typically with intention or purpose. The root conveys broader themes of emitting or releasing energy, often in subtle yet deliberate ways, such as blowing to transmit something unseen or to exert influence. This plural form highlights collective or repeated actions, emphasizing the power of small yet intentional acts to create tangible effects, whether physical, symbolic, or spiritual.",
  "4049": "نَفْحَةٌ and related words stem from the root ن-ف-ح, with the root verb نَفَحَ meaning \"he blew,\" \"he emitted,\" or \"he sent forth,\" often with the sense of spreading air, fragrance, or an offering. نَفْحَةٌ refers to \"a breath,\" \"a whiff,\" or \"a gentle gust,\" emphasizing something fleeting yet impactful. The root conveys broader themes of subtle movement and influence, where even a small or brief act can carry significant meaning. This reflects the profound power of seemingly minor occurrences to create lasting effects, aligning with the root's focus on precision and deliberate action.",
  "4050": "نَفْخَةٌ and related words stem from the root ن-ف-خ, with the root verb نَفَخَ meaning \"he blew\" or \"he breathed into.\" نَفْخَةٌ refers to \"a blast\" or \"a blowing,\" often signifying a single, forceful act of blowing. The root conveys broader themes of transferring energy or life through a breath or a powerful motion, emphasizing creation, transformation, or signaling significant events. This highlights the potency and purpose behind seemingly simple acts, such as the breath that gives life or the blast that marks a profound change. In this sense, نَفْخَةٌ reflects not only physical action but also the spiritual and cosmic significance tied to the act of blowing, symbolizing power, renewal, or finality.",
  "4051": "نَفْسٌ and related words stem from the root ن-ف-س, with the root verb نَفَسَ meaning \"he breathed\" or \"he exhaled,\" reflecting the essential act of life. نَفْسٌ means \"self,\" \"soul,\" or \"essence,\" encompassing the physical, spiritual, and emotional dimensions of a being. The connection lies in breath as a vital sign of life, symbolizing the soul's presence and the self's awareness, directly tied to the root's focus on vitality and individuality. It highlights the intrinsic relationship between life, breath, and identity, portraying the self or soul as the seat of consciousness, individuality, and existence.",
  "4052": "نَفْعٌ and related words stem from the root ن-ف-ع, with the root verb نَفَعَ meaning \"he benefited\" or \"he was useful.\" نَفْعٌ means \"benefit\" or \"usefulness.\" The connection lies in the concept of advantage or profit that arises from beneficial actions or things, directly relating to the root's meaning. It embodies the essence of positive outcomes and the inherent value found in what is advantageous.",
  "4053": "نَقَضَتْ and related words stem from the root ن-ق-ض, with the root verb نَقَضَ meaning \"he broke\" or \"he nullified.\" نَقَضَتْ means \"she broke\" or \"she nullified.\" The connection lies in the act of breaking an agreement or undoing something established, directly relating to the root's meaning. It reflects betrayal or the reversal of commitments.",
  "4054": "نَقِيبٌ and related words stem from the root ن-ق-ب, with the root verb نَقَبَ meaning \"he pierced\" or \"he penetrated.\" نَقِيبٌ means \"chief,\" \"leader,\" or \"representative.\" The connection lies in the idea of one who delves deeply into matters, penetrating to the core of issues, directly relating to the root's meaning. It signifies a person entrusted with leadership, who thoroughly understands and oversees the affairs of the people.",
  "4055": "نَقِيرٌ and related words stem from the root ن-ق-ر, with the root verb نَقَرَ meaning \"he pierced,\" \"he hollowed out,\" or \"he pecked.\" نَقِيرٌ refers to a \"speck,\" \"tiny dot,\" or \"small groove in a date stone,\" highlighting something extremely small or insignificant. The root conveys themes of creating small openings or marks, reflecting precision and minuteness. Historically, it has been associated with the tiny groove on the back of a date stone and metaphorically used to describe the smallest measure or most negligible detail, emphasizing insignificance or precision.",
  "4056": "نَقَّبُوا and related words stem from the root ن-ق-ب, with the root verb نَقَبَ meaning \"he pierced\" or \"he penetrated,\" and the intensified verb نَقَّبَ meaning \"he explored thoroughly.\" نَقَّبُوا means \"they explored thoroughly\" or \"they investigated deeply.\" The connection lies in penetrating deeply into places or matters, directly relating to the root's meaning. It emphasizes thorough exploration and the pursuit of knowledge or discovery.",
  "4057": "نَقْبٌ and related words stem from the root ن-ق-ب, with the root verb نَقَبَ meaning \"he pierced\" or \"he penetrated.\" نَقْبٌ means \"breach,\" \"opening,\" or \"passage.\" The connection lies in creating an opening by piercing through a barrier, directly relating to the root's meaning. It represents access or entry where there was none before, symbolizing breakthrough or infiltration.",
  "4058": "نَقْتَبِسْ and related words stem from the root ق-ب-س, with the root verb قَبَسَ meaning \"he took fire.\" اقْتَبَسَ means \"he sought to acquire\" or \"he borrowed light.\" نَقْتَبِسْ means \"we may borrow\" or \"we may acquire.\" The connection lies in actively seeking to obtain light or knowledge, embodying the root's concept of borrowing illumination. It emphasizes the human pursuit of guidance and understanding, illustrating dependence on shared enlightenment.",
  "4059": "نَقْضٌ and related words stem from the root ن-ق-ض, with the root verb نَقَضَ meaning \"he broke\" or \"he nullified.\" نَقْضٌ means \"breaking,\" \"breach,\" or \"violation.\" The connection lies in the concept of undoing or invalidating something, directly relating to the root's meaning. It represents the act of violating agreements or disrupting established order.",
  "4060": "نَقْعٌ and related words stem from the root ن-ق-ع, with the root verb نَقَعَ meaning \"he soaked\" or \"he saturated.\" نَقْعٌ means \"dust,\" \"soaking,\" or \"saturation.\" The connection lies in the idea of something being thoroughly permeated or enveloped, directly relating to the root's meaning. In classical Arabic, it can refer to the dust raised by a galloping horse, symbolizing intensity and immersion.",
  "4061": "نَكالٌ and related words stem from the root ن-ك-ل, with the root verb نَكَلَ meaning \"he refrained\" or \"he punished severely.\" نَكالٌ means \"punishment\" or \"penalty.\" The connection is that the punishment serves as a deterrent, causing others to refrain from similar misdeeds, embodying the root's emphasis on refraining due to fear of retribution. It highlights the concept of justice and the consequences of actions.",
  "4062": "نَكَثَ and related words stem from the root ن-ك-ث, and as the root verb, it means \"he broke (a pledge)\" or \"he unraveled.\" The connection lies in the act of undoing or violating an agreement, directly relating to the root's meaning. It reflects betrayal or the failure to uphold one's commitments.",
  "4063": "نَكَحَ and related words stem from the root ن-ك-ح, meaning \"he married.\" The connection lies in the act of entering into a marital contract, directly relating to the root's meaning. It represents the establishment of a lawful and committed relationship between spouses.",
  "4064": "نَكَصَ and related words stem from the root ن-كَ-ص, with the root verb نَكَصَ meaning \"he turned back,\" \"retreated,\" or \"recoiled.\" The word captures the act of withdrawing or reversing direction, often in the face of fear or reluctance. The connection to the root emphasizes the concept of turning away from a path or purpose, highlighting themes of hesitation or abandonment.",
  "4065": "نَكِدٌ and related words stem from the root ن-ك-د, with the root verb نَكَدَ meaning \"it became difficult,\" \"it was scanty,\" or \"he was miserly.\" The root encompasses concepts of hardship, scarcity, and stubbornness. نَكِدٌ means \"difficult,\" \"miserable,\" or \"unfortunate.\" The connection lies in depicting someone or something characterized by hardship or causing difficulty, reflecting the root's emphasis on scarcity and adversity.",
  "4066": "نَكِرَ and related words stem from the root ن-ك-ر, with the root verb itself being نَكِرَ meaning \"he did not know,\" \"he found strange,\" or \"he disowned.\" The root conveys ideas of unfamiliarity and rejection. نَكِرَ as a verb encapsulates the act of perceiving something as unknown or strange, leading to disapproval or denial. This directly reflects the root's emphasis on strangeness and the reaction of rejecting or not recognizing something that is unfamiliar.",
  "4067": "نَكِيرٌ and related words stem from the root ن-ك-ر, with the root verb نَكِرَ meaning \"he did not know,\" \"he found strange,\" or \"he disowned.\" The root conveys concepts of unfamiliarity, denial, and rejection. نَكِيرٌ means \"denial,\" \"rejection,\" or \"punishment\" and can also refer to something astonishing or dreadful due to its unfamiliarity. The connection lies in the outcome of denial and rejection, reflecting the root's emphasis on strangeness leading to disapproval and the potential for severe consequences.",
  "4068": "نَكِّرُوا and related words stem from the root ن-ك-ر, with the root verb نَكَّرَ meaning \"he made unknown,\" \"he disguised,\" or \"he rendered unfamiliar.\" نَكِّرُوا means \"disguise!\" or \"make unknown!\" The root conveys ideas of making something strange or unrecognizable. The connection lies in the act of intentionally making something unfamiliar or strange, directly reflecting the root's emphasis on transforming recognition into unfamiliarity.",
  "4069": "نَمارِقُ does not originate from the standard Arabic root system and is thought to derive from Middle Persian namrag, meaning \"cushions\" or \"pillows,\" particularly those used for reclining. It conveys themes of comfort, luxury, and hospitality. In the Qur'anic context, as seen in وَنَمَارِقُ مَصْفُوفَةٌ, it symbolizes the bounties and tranquility of Paradise, representing divine provision, rest, and honor for the righteous. The term also reflects the cultural importance of hospitality, where offering cushions signifies generosity, care, and respect.",
  "4070": "نَمِيرُ and related words stem from the root م-ي-ر, with the root verb مَارَ meaning \"he sought, obtained, or brought provisions\" or \"he collected supplies for sustenance.\" نَمِيرُ means \"we obtain provisions\" or \"we bring food,\" emphasizing the act of securing essential sustenance. The root also encompasses broader themes of seeking what is necessary to sustain life and providing for one's dependents, highlighting responsibility and care. This connection highlights the effort and diligence required to meet basic needs, reflecting the essential human endeavor to ensure survival and well-being.",
  "4071": "نَمِيمٌ and related words stem from the root ن-م-م, with the root verb نَمَمَ meaning \"he spread rumors\" or \"he slandered.\" نَمِيمٌ means \"slander\" or \"malicious gossip,\" referring to the act of conveying harmful or deceitful information to sow discord. The root conveys themes of spreading, exaggeration, and mischief, emphasizing the destructive nature of such actions in social and moral contexts. نَمِيمٌ highlights the grave consequences of spreading rumors and slander, highlighting the importance of truthfulness, restraint, and maintaining harmony within a community.",
  "4072": "نَمْلٌ and related words stem from the root ن-م-ل, with the root verb نَمَلَ meaning \"he copied,\" \"he wrote quickly,\" or \"he whispered.\" نَمْلٌ means \"ants,\" referring to the small, industrious creatures known for their organized and cooperative behavior. The root conveys themes of activity, movement, and communication, as seen in the ants’ relentless labor and their silent, almost whispered manner of interaction. The connection lies in the ants' efficiency and intricate system of communication, mirroring the root's focus on swift, subtle, and purposeful action. نَمْلٌ serves as a reminder of the importance of diligence, collaboration, and maintaining a balance between individual roles and collective responsibility.",
  "4073": "نَمْلَةٌ and related words stem from the root ن-م-ل, with the root verb نَمَلَ meaning \"he whispered,\" \"he copied,\" or \"he wrote quickly,\" reflecting subtle and purposeful action. نَمْلَةٌ means \"an ant,\" referring to the small, industrious insect known for its tireless labor and cooperation. The connection lies in the ant’s quiet yet coordinated movements and its efficient communication, mirroring the root’s themes of activity and precision. This term highlights the moral lessons of diligence, teamwork, and the importance of purposeful effort, exemplified by the ants' remarkable organization and persistence.",
  "4074": "نَهارٌ and related words stem from the root ن-ه-ر, with the root verb نَهَرَ meaning \"he turned away\" or \"he averted.\" نَهارٌ means \"day\" or \"daylight,\" referring to the time when light prevails and darkness is averted. The connection lies in the root’s concept of separation or turning away, symbolizing the transition from the obscurity of night to the clarity of day. نَهارٌ reflects themes of illumination, activity, and clarity, emphasizing the association of daylight with productivity and the dispelling of darkness, both literal and metaphorical.",
  "4075": "نَهَرٌ and related words stem from the root ن-ه-ر, with the root verb نَهَرَ meaning \"he turned away\" or \"he averted.\" نَهَرٌ means \"a stream\" or \"flowing water.\" The connection lies in the flow and movement of water, symbolizing the natural course or the act of turning, directly relating to the root's concept of movement and direction. This term emphasizes the continuous and purposeful flow, highlighting themes of persistence and the natural order.",
  "4076": "نَهَى and related words stem from the root ن-ه-ى, with the root verb نَهَى meaning \"he forbade\" or \"he prohibited.\" نَهَى means \"he forbade\" or \"he prohibited.\" The connection lies in the act of forbidding, directly relating to the root's concept of prohibition and setting limits. This term emphasizes the moral lesson of obedience and the importance of adhering to divine commands, highlighting the consequences of disobedience.",
  "4077": "نَواصِي and related words stem from the root ن-ص-ي, with the root verb نَصَا meaning \"he led,\" \"he directed,\" or \"he advanced forward.\" نَواصِي (plural of نَاصِيَةٌ) means \"forelocks,\" referring to the front part of the head. The connection lies in the act of leading or directing, as the forelock symbolizes control and submission, often metaphorically representing the will or decision-making. Just as a leader directs or guides, the forelock signifies how individuals can be led or held accountable. This reflects the root's emphasis on direction and advancement, highlighting Allah's (ﷻ) authority over all actions and the inevitability of judgment and accountability for one’s choices.",
  "4078": "النَّوَىٰ and related words stem from the root ن-و-ى, with the root verb نَوَى meaning \"he intended,\" \"he aimed,\" or \"he planned.\" النَّوَىٰ refers to \"seeds\" or \"stone pits of fruits,\" such as date seeds. The connection lies in the root's themes of purpose and potential, as seeds symbolize the foundation of growth and the intention behind creation. Just as intention sets the stage for action, a seed holds the potential for life and development.",
  "4079": "نَوْمٌ and related words stem from the root ن-و-م, with the root verb نَامَ meaning \"he slept.\" نَوْمٌ means \"sleep,\" referring to the state of rest characterized by reduced consciousness and inactivity. This term reflects the root's fundamental concept of rest and rejuvenation, essential for health and well-being. The root also extends to مَنامٌ (the act of sleeping or a dream), highlighting different aspects of sleep. Additionally, metaphorical expressions like نَامَتِ ٱلرِّيحُ (the wind slept) describe the calming or cessation of wind, illustrating the root's broader application in conveying states of tranquility and inactivity.",
  "4080": "نَيْلٌ and related words stem from the root ن-و-ل, with the root verb نَالَ meaning \"he attained\" or \"he acquired.\" نَيْلٌ means \"achievement,\" \"attainment,\" \"an advantage,\" or \"a gain,\" encompassing both the act of acquiring something and the impact of reaching a goal. The term reflects the root's core themes of obtaining, reaching, or accomplishing. It also extends to contexts where the attainment involves overcoming challenges or causing an effect, such as harm or gain in adversarial situations. نَيْلٌ highlights the dual nature of effort and result, illustrating that striving, whether for personal goals or broader pursuits, leads to meaningful outcomes.",
  "4081": "نُبُوَّةٌ and related words stem from the root ن-ب-أ, with the root verb نَبَأَ meaning \"he informed,\" \"he announced,\" or \"he brought news,\" as well as \"he was exalted or elevated,\" indicating a rise in prominence. نُبُوَّةٌ means \"prophethood,\" denoting the state or office of a prophet. The root conveys themes of delivering significant truths, aligning with the prophet's role as a divinely chosen messenger of revelations and guidance. It emphasizes the responsibility, honor, and divine trust inherent in this role. The association with elevation reflects the esteemed status of prophets in guiding and leading their communities, highlighting both their honored position and their duty to convey divine messages.",
  "4082": "نُجَازِي and related words stem from the root ج-ز-ي, with the root verb جَزَى meaning \"he recompensed\" or \"he rewarded.\" نُجَازِي means \"We recompense\" or \"We reward,\" often used in the divine context to highlight Allah’s (ﷻ) perfect justice. It reflects the idea that actions—whether righteous or sinful—are met with precise and appropriate recompense. The root highlights the fairness and inevitability of divine judgment, where every deed is accounted for.",
  "4083": "نُحَاسٌ and related words stem from the root ن-ح-س, with the root verb نَحِسَ meaning \"he was ill-fated\" or \"he was unlucky,\" and نَحَسَ meaning \"it was inauspicious\" or \"it brought misfortune.\" نُحَاسٌ means \"copper,\" \"brass,\" or \"smoke,\" specifically referring to the smoke produced from heated brass. This smoke powerfully represents ill-fate or punishment, symbolizing the harsh and adverse consequences of divine wrath. The connection lies in the intense and harmful nature of molten brass and its byproducts, evoking themes of trial, misfortune, and severity.",
  "4084": "نُدَاوِلُ and related words stem from the root د-و-ل, with the root verb دَالَ meaning \"he went round or revolved\" or \"he alternated or took turns.\" نُدَاوِلُ means \"We cause to alternate\" or \"We alternate,\" referring to making something circulate or shift between people. The root conveys changing circumstances, emphasizing how shifts in fortune, power, or events occur in cycles. This reflects the transient nature of success and hardship, reminding that no state remains fixed and outcomes unfold by Allah's (ﷻ) will and wisdom.",
  "4085": "نُذُورٌ and related words stem from the root ن-ذ-ر, with the root verb نَذَرَ meaning \"he vowed\" or \"he warned.\" The root involves concepts of making vows and issuing warnings. نُذُورٌ (plural of نَذْرٌ) meaning \"vows\" or \"solemn promises.\" It refers to multiple commitments made by individuals to perform certain acts. The connection lies in the root's emphasis on serious commitments. نُذُورٌ highlights the collective weight of multiple vows, reflecting the root's essence by demonstrating the importance and prevalence of solemn promises in moral and spiritual life.",
  "4086": "نُذُرٌ and related words stem from the root ن-ذ-ر, with the root verb نَذَرَ meaning \"he warned\" or \"he vowed.\" This root conveys the act of warning and making solemn commitments. نُذُرٌ (plural of نَذِيرٌ) means \"warnings\" or \"warners.\" It represents multiple warnings given or multiple individuals who warn others. The connection lies in the root's focus on the proliferation of warnings as a means of guidance. نُذُرٌ highlights the importance of repeated cautions to ensure the message is heeded, embodying the root's essence by highlighting the persistent efforts to guide and protect.",
  "4087": "نُزُلٌ and related words stem from the root ن-ز-ل, with the root verb نَزَلَ meaning \"he descended\" or \"he came down.\" نُزُلٌ refers to \"hospitality,\" \"provision for a guest,\" or \"welcome gift,\" describing what is prepared for someone who has arrived or descended at one’s dwelling. This connection reflects the root's concept of descending, as نُزُلٌ signifies readiness to welcome and provide for guests. In the Qur'an, نُزُلٌ often describes the rewards prepared by Allah (ﷻ) for believers in the hereafter, symbolizing divine generosity and care, encompassing both material and spiritual honor as the ultimate welcome.",
  "4088": "نُسُكٌ and related words stem from the root ن-س-ك, with the root verb نَسَكَ meaning \"he devoted himself to worship\" or \"he performed acts of devotion.\" نُسُكٌ refers to \"acts of worship,\" \"devotional practices,\" or \"ritual sacrifice.\" The connection lies in the collective expression of devotion through specific rituals, reflecting the root's emphasis on purity and dedication. This term highlights the various forms of worship that bring a person closer to Allah (ﷻ), emphasizing both outward actions and inward sincerity.",
  "4089": "نُسْخَةٌ and related words stem from the root ن-س-خ, with the root verb نَسَخَ meaning \"he copied,\" \"he transcribed,\" or \"he abrogated.\" نُسْخَةٌ refers to \"a copy,\" \"a transcript,\" or \"an exemplar,\" indicating a faithful reproduction of an original text. The term conveys the significance of preserving and transmitting knowledge accurately. The root also includes the idea of replacement, hinting at the dynamic relationship between original texts and updates. نُسْخَةٌ emphasizes the dual role of texts as preservers of knowledge and instruments of renewal, reflecting Allah's (ﷻ) wisdom in safeguarding essential guidance.",
  "4090": "نُشُورٌ and related words stem from the root ن-ش-ر, with the root verb نَشَرَ meaning \"he revived,\" \"he resurrected,\" or \"he spread.\" نُشُورٌ means \"resurrection\" or \"rising again.\" The root highlights themes of revival and renewal, emphasizing the act of restoring life or vitality to what was lifeless. This term encapsulates the transformative process of renewal, whether applied to physical or metaphorical revival, highlighting the root's association with vitality and reanimation.",
  "4091": "نُشُوزٌ and related words stem from the root ن-ش-ز, with the root verb نَشَزَ meaning \"he rose\" or \"he rebelled.\" نُشُوزٌ means \"rebellion,\" \"discord,\" or \"ill-conduct,\" especially within marital relationships. The root's idea of elevation here signifies an unwarranted or improper rise that disrupts harmony, leading to estrangement or separation. In the Qur'anic context, it refers to behaviors that disturb marital balance, emphasizing the consequences of disharmony and rebellion in relationships.",
  "4092": "نُشِرَتْ and related words stem from the root ن-ش-ر, with the root verb نَشَرَ meaning \"he spread out,\" \"he unfolded,\" or \"he opened.\" نُشِرَتْ is a passive form meaning \"it was spread out\" or \"it was unfolded.\" The root emphasizes the act of revealing, making accessible, or expanding. نُشِرَتْ conveys the idea of transitioning from a closed or concealed state to one that is open and visible, aligning with the root's focus on dissemination and clarity.",
  "4093": "نُصُبٌ and related words stem from the root ن-ص-ب, with the root verb نَصَبَ meaning \"he set up\" or \"he erected.\" نُصُبٌ refers to \"idols,\" \"altars,\" or \"stones erected for worship,\" emphasizing objects set up for reverence or devotion. The connection lies in the physical act of erecting these structures, reflecting the root's focus on establishment. This term highlights idolatrous practices, symbolizing the misplaced veneration of material objects, contrasting with the worship of Allah (ﷻ).",
  "4094": "نُصِبَتْ and related words stem from the root ن-ص-ب, with the root verb نَصَبَ meaning \"he set up,\" \"he erected,\" or \"he toiled.\" نُصِبَتْ is a passive form meaning \"it was set up\" or \"it was erected,\" emphasizing the act of something being established or positioned. The command form اِنْصَبْ means \"exert yourself,\" reflecting a call to focused effort and diligence. The root conveys themes of effort, toil, and the establishment of structures, linking the labor required with the creation of stability and significance. These forms highlight the actions of setting up enduring elements, whether physical structures or symbolic markers, and the purposeful effort involved in their establishment.",
  "4095": "نُصْبٌ and related words stem from the root ن-ص-ب, with the root verb نَصَبَ meaning \"he toiled,\" \"he labored,\" or \"he exerted himself.\" نُصْبٌ refers to \"fatigue,\" \"weariness,\" or \"hardship,\" emphasizing the state of physical or mental strain resulting from continuous effort or toil. The root conveys themes of exertion, endurance, and the struggles encountered during laborious tasks or challenging journeys. نُصْبٌ reflects the burdens that weigh heavily on an individual, highlighting the human experience of striving and the inevitable weariness that accompanies it. It emphasizes the reality of hardship as an intrinsic part of life’s struggles, connecting deeply to the root's focus on effort and perseverance.",
  "4096": "نُصْحٌ and related words stem from the root ن-ص-ح, with the root verb نَصَحَ meaning \"he was sincere.\" نُصْحٌ means \"sincere advice\" or \"sincerity,\" focusing on the purity of intent and the honesty behind counsel. The connection lies in offering genuine guidance that aligns with the root’s emphasis on truthfulness and clarity. This term highlights the intrinsic value of sincerity in interactions, fostering trust and meaningful communication.",
  "4097": "نُطْفَةٌ and related words stem from the root ن-ط-ف, with the root verb نَطَفَ meaning \"it dripped,\" \"it flowed gently,\" or \"it was clean or pure.\" نُطْفَةٌ refers to \"a drop of fluid,\" particularly \"a drop of semen,\" representing the initial stage of human life. The root conveys notions of purity, clarity, and minuteness, emphasizing the subtle and delicate nature of this fluid. نُطْفَةٌ highlights the humble origins of human creation, transforming from an insignificant drop into a fully developed being. This reflects the root's focus on smallness and purity while highlighting the divine power and wisdom in the intricate process of creation, serving as a reminder of human dependency on Allah (ﷻ).",
  "4098": "نُعَاسٌ and related words stem from the root ن-ع-س, with the root verb نَعَسَ meaning \"he slumbered\" or \"he became drowsy.\" نُعَاسٌ refers to \"sleepiness,\" \"drowsiness,\" or \"slumber,\" denoting a light and tranquil state of rest. The root emphasizes calmness and physical relaxation, symbolizing relief and reassurance. In classical Arabic, نُعَاسٌ is associated with peace and renewal during times of stress or uncertainty, reflecting divine mercy in providing rest as a means to restore balance and well-being. This highlights the connection between physical rest and spiritual ease.",
  "4099": "نُفُورٌ and related words stem from the root ن-ف-ر, with the root verb نَفَرَ meaning \"he departed,\" \"he fled,\" or \"he showed aversion.\" نُفُورٌ means \"aversion,\" \"dislike,\" or \"avoidance.\" The connection lies in emotional or physical distancing from something, reflecting strong dislike or avoidance. In the Qur'anic context, it describes disbelievers' aversion to the truth and their turning away from the message, emphasizing the root's theme of fleeing or being repelled, highlighting stubbornness and rejection.",
  "4100": "نُقَدِّسُ and related words stem from the root ق-د-س, with the root verb قَدَّسَ meaning \"he purified,\" \"he sanctified,\" or \"he consecrated.\" نُقَدِّسُ means \"we sanctify,\" \"we purify,\" or \"we glorify as holy,\" emphasizing an active, collective acknowledgment of sanctity. The root conveys themes of reverence, elevation, and purification, reflecting a profound sense of respect and devotion. This term embodies the act of exalting and venerating through recognizing and declaring purity and holiness. It highlights the communal effort to maintain and uphold sacredness, symbolizing deep dedication to divine attributes and the pursuit of purity in thought, word, and action.",
  "4101": "نُقِرَ and related words stem from the root ن-ق-ر, with the root verb نَقَرَ meaning \"he pierced,\" \"he tapped, producing a sound,\" or \"he hollowed out.\" نُقِرَ is a passive form meaning \"it was blown\" or \"it was sounded,\" referring to an act that produces a sharp or piercing sound, such as a trumpet blast. The root emphasizes acts of penetration or impact, often associated with sound production or physical marking. نُقِرَ highlights the moment of auditory impact, symbolizing an event or announcement that demands immediate attention.",
  "4102": "نُقْرِئُ and related words stem from the root ق-ر-أ, with the root verb قَرَأَ meaning \"he read,\" \"he recited,\" or \"he gathered.\" نُقْرِئُ means \"We cause to read,\" \"We make recite,\" or \"We deliver (a message).\" The connection lies in facilitating or enabling the act of reading or recitation, directly reflecting the root's concepts of recitation and gathering. This term emphasizes the role of transmitting knowledge or revelations to others, highlighting the active dissemination of messages.",
  "4103": "نُكُرٌ and related words stem from the root ن-ك-ر, with the root verb نَكِرَ meaning \"he found strange\" or \"he disowned.\"  نُكُرٌ means \"strange,\" or \"dreadful.\" The root embodies concepts of unfamiliarity and disapproval. It denotes that which is unfamiliar and therefore objectionable or alarming. The connection lies in capturing the sense of astonishment or dread toward something unknown or unrecognized, aligning with the root's emphasis on strangeness leading to disapproval or fear.",
  "4104": "نُكِسُوا and related words stem from the root ن-ك-س, with the root verb نَكَسَ meaning \"he inverted,\" \"reversed,\" or \"turned upside down.\" نُكِسُوا is a passive form meaning \"they were reversed\" or \"they were turned back.\" The term conveys a forced reversal or regression, indicating a return to a degraded or inferior state. This reflects the root’s concept of inversion, emphasizing a shift away from progress or enlightenment to a state of denial or degradation. It highlights the idea of being overturned or reduced to a condition of weakness or inferiority, aligning with the root’s focus on a complete reversal of position or state.",
  "4105": "نُكْرٌ and related words stem from the root ن-ك-ر, with the root verb نَكِرَ meaning \"he found strange,\" \"he denied,\" or \"he disowned.\" نُكْرٌ means \"terrible,\" \"strange,\" or \"reprehensible,\" describing actions or things that are objectionable due to their unacceptable or unfamiliar nature. The root conveys themes of unfamiliarity, rejection, and disapproval, emphasizing instinctive aversion to the unrecognized or improper. This term highlights the moral and social response to actions that deviate from accepted norms, reflecting the root’s focus on rejection of the objectionable.",
  "4106": "نُنْشِزُ and related words stem from the root ن-ش-ز, with the root verb نَشَزَ meaning \"he rose,\" \"he elevated,\" or \"he assembled.\" نُنْشِزُ means \"We raise\" or \"We assemble.\" The connection lies in Allah’s (ﷻ) power to elevate or reassemble, as in the Qur'anic description of resurrecting and bringing together bones. This reflects the root’s emphasis on elevation and creation, highlighting divine authority in revival and re-creation.",
  "4107": "نُهَى and related words stem from the root ن-ه-ي, with the root verb نَهَى meaning \"he forbade\" or \"he prevented.\" نُهَى means \"intelligence,\" \"reason,\" or \"understanding.\" The connection lies in the ability to restrain oneself, as true intelligence involves knowing when to stop or avoid certain actions, reflecting the root's emphasis on prohibition. It highlights the role of reason in guiding behavior and making wise decisions.",
  "4108": "نُوحُ stems from the root ن-و-ح, with the root verb نَاحَ meaning \"he wailed,\" \"lamented,\" or \"mourned.\" نُوحُ is the name of Prophet Noah (ﷺ), known for his enduring patience and persistent efforts to guide his people. The connection lies in his profound grief over the disbelief of his community, reflecting the root's concept of deep lamentation. Prophet Noah (ﷺ) tirelessly warned his people for centuries, mourning their refusal to embrace the truth. His story in the Qur'an serves as a lesson in perseverance, emphasizing the importance of steadfastness and compassion in the face of persistent rejection.",
  "4109": "نُورٌ and related words stem from the root ن-و-ر, with the root verb نَوَّرَ meaning \"he or it became radiant\" or \"he or it illuminated.\" نُورٌ means \"light,\" encompassing both physical and spiritual illumination. The root reflects clarity, brightness, and guidance, symbolizing the dispelling of darkness and ignorance. ٱلنُّورُ, one of Allah’s (ﷻ) beautiful names, means \"The Light,\" signifying His (ﷻ) role as the ultimate source of guidance and truth. This name highlights Allah’s (ﷻ) ability to illuminate hearts and minds, replacing doubt with clarity and misguidance with wisdom, reminding us to seek His light in every aspect of life.",
  "4110": "ذَا النُّونِ and related words stem from the root ن-و-ن, with the root verb نَانَ meaning \"he moved\" or \"he wavered.\" النُّون refers to \"the fish,\" and ذَا النُّونِ means \"the one of the fish,\" a title for Prophet Jonah (ﷺ), who was swallowed by a great fish. The root conveys the idea of movement back and forth in a regular rythm, symbolizing the fish's dynamic nature and the Prophet's journey through trials and repentance. ذَا النُّونِ emphasizes the connection between the Prophet’s story and themes of humility, perseverance, and ultimate redemption.",
  "4111": "نِحْلَةٌ and related words stem from the root ن-ح-ل, with the root verb meaning \"he gave as a gift.\" نِحْلَةٌ means \"gift\" or \"present,\" often referring to something given freely, sincerely, and graciously, such as a dowry. The connection lies in the act of giving with generosity and good intentions, reflecting kindness and selflessness. نِحْلَةٌ emphasizes the moral and spiritual value of sincere and gracious giving, highlighting how such acts are both a blessing for the giver and a means of fostering harmony and gratitude.",
  "4112": "نِسَاءٌ and related words stem from the root ن-س-و, with the root verb نَسَا meaning \"he delayed\" or \"he deferred.\" نِسَاءٌ refers to \"women.\" The root’s core meaning of deferral or delay connects to the concept of \"delayed companionship,\" reflecting the creation of Eve (عَلَيْهَا ٱلصَّلَاةُ وَٱلسَّلَامُ) after Adam (ﷺ) as a complementary partner. This connection highlights the deliberate design of human relationships, emphasizing the integral bond and mutual fulfillment between men and women. Derived from this root, نِسَاءٌ carries a linguistic depth that ties the word to the broader narrative of companionship and purpose in creation, rooted in the notion of deferral.",
  "4113": "نِصْفٌ and related words stem from the root ن-ص-ف, with the root verb نَصَفَ meaning \"he divided equally\" or \"he was just.\" نِصْفٌ means \"half,\" referring to one of two equal parts of a whole. The connection lies in equal division, reflecting the root’s emphasis on fairness, balance, and justice. The term conveys precision and impartiality, highlighting the importance of equity in dividing or distributing something. نِصْفٌ symbolizes proportionality and fairness, emphasizing the moral responsibility to ensure justice in both material and non-material dealings.",
  "4114": "نِعْمَ and related words stem from the root ن-ع-م, with the root verb نَعِمَ meaning \"he was at ease\" or \"he enjoyed comfort.\" نِعْمَ is a term of commendation meaning \"how excellent\" or \"what a good (thing/person),\" used to praise something admirable or beneficial. The root’s broader themes of ease, comfort, and pleasantness emphasize qualities that bring goodness and satisfaction. The connection lies in acknowledging and valuing excellence, reflecting the root’s focus on positive attributes that inspire admiration and gratitude.",
  "4115": "نِعْمَةٌ and related words stem from the root ن-ع-م, with the root verb نَعِمَ meaning \"he was at ease\" or \"he enjoyed comfort.\" نِعْمَةٌ refers specifically to a \"blessing,\" \"favor,\" or \"bounty\" that is bestowed upon someone. Unlike نَعْمَةٌ, which emphasizes the state of ease experienced, نِعْمَةٌ focuses on the tangible or intangible blessings granted by Allah (ﷻ). The connection to the root lies in the inherent comfort and happiness these blessings provide, fostering gratitude and dependence on Allah (ﷻ). This word serves as a reminder to recognize the source of all bounties, encouraging humility and sincere acknowledgment of Allah’s (ﷻ) favors.",
  "4116": "نِفَاقٌ and related words stem from the root ن-ف-ق, with the root verb نَفَقَ meaning \"he tunneled,\" and the derived verb نَافَقَ meaning \"he acted hypocritically.\" نِفَاقٌ means \"hypocrisy.\" The connection lies in the concept of hidden intentions and duplicity, akin to moving through tunnels unseen, directly relating to the root's meaning. It represents the state of pretending to hold beliefs or virtues one does not truly possess.",
  "4117": "نِكَاحٌ and related words stem from the root ن-ك-ح, with the root verb نَكَحَ meaning \"he married.\" نِكَاحٌ means \"marriage\" or \"matrimony.\" The connection lies in the institution of marriage itself, directly relating to the root's meaning. It embodies the legal and social bond established between a husband and wife.",
  "4118": "The particle هَـ is a demonstrative prefix meaning \"this,\" used to emphasize or point out specific nouns, indicating proximity or presence. It highlights the noun it precedes, such as in هَذَا (this) or هَذِهِ (this for feminine nouns). هَـ can also function as a vocative particle, drawing attention when addressing someone directly, such as هَا أَنْتَ (here you are). In the Qur'an, it frequently emphasizes specific events, persons, or concepts, making the message more direct and engaging, and enhancing clarity by specifying what or who is being referenced.",
  "4119": "هَاؤُمُ stems from the root ه-ا-ء, meaning \"Here it is!\" or \"Take it!\" It is used to draw attention or invite a group to receive something being offered. This word reflects the root’s concept of presenting or bringing forth, emphasizing the act of offering something with intention and purpose. هَاؤُمُ highlights themes of sharing and engaging others in receiving, making it a direct and purposeful expression of giving or showing.",
  "4120": "هَاتُوا stems from the root ه-ا-ت, with the root verb هَاتَ functioning as a command meaning \"Bring!\" or \"Give!\" in singular form, while هَاتُوا is the plural command meaning \"Bring (you all)!\" or \"Give (you all)!\" This term reflects the root’s focus on the act of presenting or delivering something directly upon request. Unlike typical roots with past-tense origins, هَاتَ is inherently a command form, emphasizing immediacy and purposeful action. هَاتُوا highlights themes of deliberate delivery or offering, addressing a group to fulfill the request, aligning with the root’s practical and action-oriented nature.",
  "4121": "هَاجَرَ stems from the root ه-ج-ر, with the root verb هَجَرَ meaning \"he forsook,\" \"he abandoned,\" or \"he shunned.\" هَاجَرَ means \"he emigrated\" or \"he migrated.\" This verb intensifies the root’s concept by implying mutual or deliberate action, often involving collective effort in leaving behind something significant. It reflects purposeful migration, typically undertaken for meaningful reasons such as seeking safety, betterment, or a higher purpose. This meaning aligns with the root’s broader themes of separation, highlighting the importance of severing ties for the sake of progress or greater goals.",
  "4122": "هَادٍ and related words stem from the root ه-د-ي, with the root verb هَدَىٰ meaning \"he guided\" or \"he led aright.\" هَادٍ means \"guide\" or \"one who guides,\" representing someone or an entity that directs others toward the correct path. While it can refer to a person who leads others with wisdom, it also profoundly connects to Allah (ﷻ) as the ultimate guide providing unfailing direction. This term embodies the root's essence by emphasizing the active role of guiding others toward truth, clarity, and righteousness, reflecting the supreme guidance of Allah (ﷻ).",
  "4123": "هَادُوا and related words stem from the root ه-و-د, with the root verb هَادَ meaning \"he turned back\" or \"he repented.\" هَادُوا means \"they became Jews,\" referring to those who identified as Jews or followed Judaism. The connection lies in the root's emphasis on turning or returning, symbolizing being repeatedly called to return to Allah (ﷻ) through repentance and adherence. This term reflects a collective identity tied to the call to embrace the laws and teachings brought by all the prophets sent by Allah (ﷻ).",
  "4124": "هَادِي and related words stem from the root ه-د-ي, with the root verb هَدَىٰ meaning \"he guided\" or \"he led aright.\" هَادِي means \"guide\" or \"one who guides,\" emphasizing a consistent and enduring quality of guidance. ٱلْهَادِي, one of Allah's (ﷻ) beautiful names, refers to \"The Guide\" or \"The One Who Leads,\" highlighting Allah’s (ﷻ) role in directing His servants to the right path and what is best for them. This name signifies that Allah (ﷻ) is the ultimate source of guidance, reminding us to seek His direction in all aspects of life and trust in His wisdom to lead us toward success and salvation.",
  "4125": "هَارٍ and related words stem from the root ه-و-ر, with the root verb هَارَ meaning \"it collapsed\" or \"it crumbled.\" هَارٍ means \"crumbling\" or \"about to collapse,\" describing a state of instability or imminent failure. The root conveys the idea of precariousness, where something fragile or poorly supported teeters on the brink of falling. This term highlights the peril of relying on weak or insincere foundations, whether in physical constructs or actions. It serves as a cautionary reminder that efforts lacking sincerity or stability are destined to fail, emphasizing the importance of building on solid, pious, and well-intentioned foundations to achieve enduring success.",
  "4126": "هَارُوتُ refers to one of two angels, Harut (ﷺ) and Marut (ﷺ). هَارُوتُ does not have a definitive Arabic root and is considered to be of foreign origin. Despite this, the story of Harut (ﷺ) and Marut (ﷺ) conveys essential lessons about the ethical use of knowledge and the dangers of succumbing to temptation. Sent as a test to the people, these angels symbolize accountability and free will. Their story highlights the importance of humility, obedience to Allah (ﷻ), and the grave consequences of misusing the gifts entrusted by Him.",
  "4127": "هارُونُ is the name of Prophet Aaron (ﷺ), the brother of Prophet Moses (ﷺ). Derived from the Hebrew root אַהֲרֹן, it is commonly interpreted as \"high mountain\" or \"mountain of strength.\" This meaning reflects Aaron's (ﷺ) role as a strong supporter of Moses (ﷺ), embodying strength and resilience in delivering Allah’s (ﷻ) message. His story emphasizes brotherhood, cooperation, and the value of unity in overcoming challenges. In the Qur'an, Prophet Aaron (ﷺ) exemplifies leadership and eloquence, reinforcing the importance of collective effort in achieving shared goals.",
  "4128": "هَالِكٌ and related words stem from the root ه-ل-ك, with the root verb هَلَكَ meaning \"he perished,\" \"he died,\" or \"he was destroyed.\" هَالِكٌ means \"perishing one\" or \"one who is doomed.\" The nuance lies in the internal or ongoing state of perishing, focusing on the process of decline or decay. It reflects themes of mortality and transience, emphasizing the inevitability of death and the fleeting nature of life. This term conveys the internal aspect of decline, contrasting with مُهْلَكِينَ, which emphasizes external destruction.",
  "4129": "هَامَانُ is the name of a figure associated with Pharaoh, known for his arrogance and opposition to Prophet Moses (ﷺ). Some Hebrew scholars connect this name to the root המה (hama), meaning \"noise\" or \"tumult.\" This reflects his chaotic and destructive role as Pharaoh’s chief minister, contributing to oppression and injustice. His story highlights the destructive consequences of the misuse of power, pride, and defiance against Allah's (ﷻ) message and authority, ultimately leading to his downfall.",
  "4130": "هَامِدَةٌ and related words stem from the root ه-م-د, with the root verb هَمَدَ meaning \"it became still,\" \"lifeless,\" or \"extinct.\" هَامِدَةٌ means \"lifeless\" or \"barren.\" The connection lies in describing land that appears dead or motionless, like earth without vegetation. In the Qur'anic context, it illustrates how Allah (ﷻ) revives the dead earth with rain, symbolizing resurrection and renewal, directly relating to the root's emphasis on lifelessness transitioning to vitality.",
  "4131": "هَاوِيَةٌ and related words stem from the root ه-و-ى, with the root verb هَوَىٰ meaning \"he fell\" or \"he descended.\" هَاوِيَةٌ means \"abyss\" or \"pit,\" referring specifically to the deep, endless void of Hell. The connection lies in the act of falling into a profound and catastrophic descent, directly reflecting the root's emphasis on descent. This term vividly describes the ultimate punishment for those who deviate from righteousness, emphasizing the terrifying and irreversible nature of falling into such a place of torment.",
  "4132": "هَباءٌ and related words stem from the root ه-ب-و, with the root verb هَبَأَ meaning \"he scattered\" or \"he dispersed.\" هَباءٌ refers to fine particles, such as dust or minute debris, that are light enough to be suspended in the air. This term embodies the root's concept by illustrating the scattering and dispersion of tiny particles, often visible in a beam of sunlight. It reflects themes of minuteness, transience, and insignificance, highlighting the ephemeral nature of such particles. In a metaphorical sense, هَباءٌ can denote something trivial or of no substantial value.",
  "4133": "هَجْرٌ stems from the root ه-ج-ر, with the root verb هَجَرَ meaning \"he forsook,\" \"he abandoned,\" or \"he shunned.\" هَجْرٌ means \"abandonment\" or \"desertion,\" emphasizing the act or state of leaving something behind. It encapsulates the root’s concept by focusing on the emotional and physical aspects of severance, whether from a place, a person, or an action. This term highlights the deliberate nature of leaving or avoiding something undesirable, reflecting the root’s central idea of purposeful separation and detachment.",
  "4134": "هَادٍ and related words stem from the root ه-د-ي, with the root verb هَدَىٰ meaning \"he guided\" or \"he led aright.\" هَادٍ means \"guide\" or \"one who guides,\" representing someone or an entity that directs others toward the correct path. While it can refer to a person who leads others with knowledge and wisdom, it also carries a profound connection to Allah (ﷻ) as the ultimate guide who provides perfect and unfailing direction. This term embodies the root's essence by emphasizing the active role of guiding others toward truth, clarity, and righteousness. It highlights the interplay between wisdom, leadership, and responsibility while ultimately reflecting the supreme guidance of Allah (ﷻ), who leads His creation to moral and spiritual success.",
  "4135": "هَدِيَّةٌ and related words stem from the root ه-د-ي, with the root verb هَدَىٰ meaning \"he guided\" or \"he led aright.\" هَدِيَّةٌ means \"gift\" or \"present,\" symbolizing something given to benefit the recipient. The connection lies in the shared idea of offering value, as gifts and guidance both aim to provide goodness and upliftment. This term embodies the root’s themes of generosity and benevolence, representing material and spiritual acts of giving that foster connection and goodwill.",
  "4136": "هَدٌّ and related words stem from the root ه-د-د, with the root verb هَدَّ meaning \"he demolished,\" \"he destroyed,\" or \"he pulled down.\" هَدٌّ means \"demolition\" or \"destruction.\" This term directly mirrors the root's concept by representing the act of tearing down or dismantling structures. It underscores the power and force required to bring about such destruction, reflecting the root's emphasis on overwhelming strength leading to ruin.",
  "4137": "هَدْيٌ and related words stem from the root ه-د-ي, with the root verb هَدَىٰ meaning \"he guided\" or \"he led aright.\" هَدْيٌ refers to \"a sacrificial offering\" or \"dedicated gift,\" especially in the context of pilgrimage rituals, symbolizing submission and devotion to Allah (ﷻ). The root encompasses themes of guidance, bestowal, and leading toward righteousness, emphasizing direction and purpose. هَدْيٌ embodies these ideas as an act that represents seeking spiritual alignment and divine favor. This connection highlights how offerings serve both as expressions of faith and as a means to attain guidance and moral clarity.",
  "4138": "هَرَبًا and related words stem from the root ه-ر-ب, with the root verb هَرَبَ meaning \"he fled,\" \"he escaped,\" or \"he ran away.\" هَرَبًا means \"fleeing\" or \"flight,\" capturing the act of running away from danger, pursuit, or undesirable circumstances. The root encompasses themes of urgency, fear, and instinctual self-preservation, emphasizing the necessity of escape to ensure safety or avoid harm. It also reflects a broader sense of separation or avoidance, whether from physical threats or metaphorical challenges. This connection highlights the human tendency to seek safety and distance oneself from perceived harm, aligning with the root's focus on escape as both a physical and psychological response.",
  "4139": "هَزَمُوا and related words stem from the root ه-ز-م, with the root verb هَزَمَ meaning \"he defeated,\" \"he overcame,\" or \"he routed.\" هَزَمُوا means \"they defeated\" or \"they overcame.\" This term embodies the root's concept by indicating that a group has achieved victory over others. It reflects themes of triumph and dominance inherent in the root, highlighting collective success in overcoming opposition",
  "4140": "هَزْلٌ and related words stem from the root ه-ز-ل, with the root verb هَزَلَ meaning \"he jested,\" \"he joked.\" هَزْلٌ means \"jest,\" \"frivolity,\" or \"lightness.\" This term embodies the root's concept by representing lack of seriousness or playful behavior. It reflects themes of levity and triviality inherent in the root, contrasting with earnestness or gravity.",
  "4141": "هَشِيمٌ and related words stem from the root ه-ش-م, with the root verb هَشَمَ meaning \"he crushed,\" \"he broke,\" or \"he shattered.\" هَشِيمٌ means \"dry twigs,\" \"broken pieces,\" or \"stubble,\" referring to plants that are dry and brittle, breaking easily into fragments. This term reflects the root's concept by symbolizing something reduced to fragments, highlighting themes of decay, fragility, and impermanence. It emphasizes the transient nature of material things, aligning with the inherent fragility conveyed by the root.",
  "4142": "هَضِيمٌ and related words stem from the root ه-ض-م, with the root verb هَضَمَ meaning \"he digested\" or \"he diminished.\" هَضِيمٌ means \"slender\" or \"delicate,\" and is often used to describe something like a plant or a slender waist. This term relates to the root's concept by reflecting something that has been diminished or reduced in size, emphasizing refinement or subtlety. It conveys the idea of something that has undergone a process of reduction or softening, aligning with the root’s theme of diminishment or gentleness.",
  "4143": "هَضْمٌ and related words stem from the root ه-ض-م, with the root verb هَضَمَ meaning \"he digested\" or \"he diminished.\" هَضْمٌ means \"diminishment\" or \"reduction,\" particularly in the context of rights or something that is due. It conveys the idea of something being consumed or reduced in its value or substance. While it can refer to the physical process of digestion, in a broader sense it also relates to the figurative concept of deprivation or unfair reduction, particularly in the context of justice or recompense.",
  "4144": "The interrogative particle هَل is used to introduce yes/no questions. It is positioned at the beginning of a sentence to indicate a query. Unlike أَ (another interrogative), هَل implies an expectation of either affirmation or negation, often seeking clarification or confirmation. In the Qur'an, هَل carries rhetorical weight, not just in questioning, but sometimes in challenging the listener to reflect deeply on a concept, as seen in verses about the afterlife or the truth of prophethood. Its placement adds emphasis to the inquiry, urging careful consideration.",
  "4145": "هَلَكَ and related words stem from the root ه-ل-ك, and as the root verb, it means \"he perished,\" \"he died,\" or \"he was destroyed.\" This fundamental verb encapsulates the essence of the root, describing the end of life, destruction, or total ruin. It conveys the inevitability of mortality and the fragility of existence, reflecting themes of transience and impermanence. The root’s broader dimensions highlight the cessation of both physical and metaphorical forms of existence, such as authority, emphasizing the finite nature of worldly life and the ultimate reality of demise.",
  "4146": "هَلُمَّ and related words stem from the root ه-ل-م, which conveys the meaning of \"to approach,\" \"to come forward,\" or \"to bring.\" هَلُمَّ is a command form meaning \"come\" or \"bring forth,\" used to call someone closer or to demand something be presented. The word embodies urgency and immediacy, often employed to prompt action or response.",
  "4147": "هَلُوعٌ and related words stem from the root ه-ل-ع, with the root verb هَلَعَ meaning \"he was anxious,\" \"he was impatient,\" or \"he was greedy.\" هَلُوعٌ means \"anxiously impatient\" or \"greedy.\" This term embodies the root's concept by describing someone excessively anxious about loss, eager for gain, or unable to withstand hardship. It reflects themes of restlessness, insatiable desire, and vulnerability inherent in the root, highlighting negative traits of impatience, covetousness, and instability.",
  "4148": "هَمَزَاتٌ and related words stem from the root ه-م-ز, with the root verb هَمَزَ meaning \"he slandered,\" \"he mocked,\" or \"he backbit.\" هَمَزَاتِ (plural of هَمَزَةٌ) means \"malicious suggestions\" or \"harmful proddings.\" The root emphasizes actions that cause harm through subtle or overt attacks, whether verbal or figurative. هَمَزَاتٌ conveys the idea of repeated or ongoing incitements, often destructive or misleading in nature, reflecting the root’s focus on instigation and harm. This term highlights the insidious nature of such influences, emphasizing the need for vigilance against malicious provocations that can lead to harm or deviation.",
  "4149": "هَمَّازٌ and related words stem from the root ه-م-ز, with the root verb هَمَزَ meaning \"he slandered\" or \"he defamed.\" هَمَّازٌ means \"habitual slanderer\" or \"persistent defamer,\" describing someone who frequently engages in malicious speech or ridicule. The root conveys themes of harm, insult, and attack, emphasizing actions intended to degrade or injure others. هَمَّازٌ captures the active and repeated nature of such behavior, serving as a stark warning against the destructive consequences of constant defamation and slander.",
  "4150": "هَمَّ and related words stem from the root ه-م-م, and as the root verb, it means \"he intended or desired\" or \"he was concerned.\" The root conveys themes of internal thought, preoccupation, and emotional engagement, encompassing both purposeful intentions and emotional struggles such as worry or hesitation. This term reflects the human experience of forming intentions, such as the inclination to act decisively, as well as grappling with concerns that arise from external challenges or inner fears. It can describe noble aspirations, as when someone is driven by righteous goals, but also cautionary moments when unchecked emotions or desires lead to potential error or harm.",
  "4151": "هَمْسٌ and related words stem from the root ه-م-س, with the root verb هَمَسَ meaning \"he spoke inaudibly,\" \"he spoke softly,\" or \"he produced a low sound.\" هَمْسٌ refers to a \"gentle sound,\" \"soft sound,\" emphasizing subtlety, quietness, and restraint. The root conveys themes of delicacy and subdued communication, reflecting the absence of harshness or loudness in the action. هَمْسٌ also captures the essence of faint, barely perceptible sounds, whether in speech, nature, or movement.",
  "4152": "هَنِيئًا and related words stem from the root ه-ن-أ, with the root verb هَنِئَ meaning \"it came without inconvenience or trouble\" or \"the food was pleasant and not succeeded by harm even after digestion.\" هَنِيئًا means \"pleasant\" or \"enjoyment,\" used to describe the ease and delight of consuming food or blessings without any negative consequences. The connection lies in the root's emphasis on ease, comfort, and the absence of difficulty or harm, reflecting a state of effortless, untroubled enjoyment. This term highlights the idea that lawful enjoyments are both freely granted and purely beneficial, serving as blessings from Allah (ﷻ) that bring satisfaction and gratitude without any burden or harm.",
  "4153": "هَوَاءٌ and related words stem from the root ه-و-ى, with the root verb هَوَىٰ meaning \"he fell,\" \"he descended,\" or \"he desired passionately.\" هَوَاءٌ primarily means \"air\" or \"atmosphere,\" as well as \"void\" or \"empty space,\" and \"desire.\" The connection lies in how air fills an empty space, just as desires fill a heedless heart. Like air, desires are unstable and easily shift directions, pulling a person in harmful ways and causing them to stray. This mirrors the root's themes of inclination and falling, emphasizing how unchecked desires can lead one off the correct path, leaving behind emptiness and ruin.",
  "4154": "هَوَىٰ and related words stem from the root ه-و-ى, with the root verb meaning \"he fell,\" \"he descended,\" or \"he desired passionately.\" This term encompasses both the physical act of falling and the emotional inclination or yearning for something with overwhelming passion. In different contexts, هَوَىٰ is used to describe physical descent, such as falling or being hurled, emotional longing or yearning, and moral or spiritual decline, such as falling into ruin. The root emphasizes the duality of movement—both literal and figurative—highlighting the powerful pull of desires and inclinations that, if unchecked, can lead to destruction.",
  "4155": "هَوْنٍ and related words stem from the root ه-و-ن, with the root verb هَانَ meaning \"he was easy\" or \"he was gentle.\" هَوْنٍ means \"gentleness,\" \"humility,\" or \"ease.\" The connection lies in embodying a demeanor of mildness and modesty, directly reflecting the root’s focus on softness and simplicity. This term highlights a noble quality of modesty and grace, particularly in interactions with others.",
  "4156": "هَيِّنٌ and related words stem from the root ه-و-ن, with the root verb هَانَ meaning \"he was easy\" or \"he was insignificant.\" هَيِّنٌ means \"easy\" or \"simple.\" The connection lies in describing matters that are not difficult or burdensome, directly aligning with the root’s emphasis on ease. This term often conveys that certain matters are simple for Allah (ﷻ), reflecting His omnipotence and effortless control over all things.",
  "4157": "هَيْتَ and related words stem from the root ه-ي-ت, with the root verb هَيَّتَ meaning \"he cried out and called.\" هَيْتَ is an expression meaning \"Come!\" or \"Approach!\" used to summon someone with urgency or purpose. Similar calls, like هَيْتَ هَيْتَ or يَاهْ يَاهْ, were commonly used by shepherds or to call companions from afar. While rooted in the concept of vocalization and summoning, هَيْتَ also functions as a fixed exclamatory term, particularly in the Qur'an, signifying a direct invitation or call to action.",
  "4158": "The particle هَيْهَاتَ means \"far\" or \"far removed,\" and it is used to emphasize that something is perceived as distant or unattainable by the person being addressed. In the Qur'an, it highlights the flawed perception of those who wrongly believe that certain realities—such as the Hereafter or accountability—are far off or improbable. This word highlights their mental and emotional disconnection, ignorance, and negligence regarding the seriousness of the matter. It serves as a powerful reminder that such dismissive attitudes only deepen the divide between misguided beliefs and reality, ultimately resulting in profound regret and despair.",
  "4159": "هُدًى and related words stem from the root ه-د-ي, with the root verb هَدَىٰ meaning \"he guided\" or \"he led aright.\" هُدًى means \"guidance,\" encapsulating the root's core theme by representing the direction needed to reach the right path or truth. It emphasizes the transformative power of guidance in achieving enlightenment, moral integrity, and spiritual growth, reflecting the indispensable role of direction in aligning with righteousness.",
  "4160": "هُدِّمَتْ and related words stem from the root ه-د-م, with the root verb هَدَمَ meaning \"he demolished,\" \"he destroyed,\" or \"he pulled down.\" هُدِّمَتْ is a passive form meaning \"it was demolished\" or \"it was destroyed.\" This term embodies the root's concept by indicating that a feminine noun (such as a building or structure) has been brought to ruin. It highlights the outcome of destructive forces acting upon something, emphasizing the loss and devastation inherent in the root.",
  "4161": "هُدْهُدٌ stems from the root ه-د-ه-د, with the root verb هَدْهَدَ meaning \"he produced a repetitive or cooing sound\" or \"he calmed or soothed.\" هُدْهُدٌ refers to the hoopoe, a bird known for its distinctive crest, behaviors, and unique call. The term is onomatopoeic, imitating the repetitive sound of the bird’s vocalizations. The root also encompasses themes of gentle repetition, calming actions, and persistent observation, reflecting the bird's symbolic qualities of vigilance, communication, and purposeful motion.",
  "4162": "هُزُؤٌ and related words stem from the root ه-ز-أ, with the root verb هَزَأَ meaning \"he mocked,\" \"he ridiculed,\" or \"he scoffed.\" هُزُؤٌ means \"mockery\" or \"derision.\" This term embodies the root's concept by representing the act of ridicule itself. It reflects themes of scorn and disrespect, highlighting the negative behavior of belittling others inherent in the root.",
  "4163": "هُزِّي and related words stem from the root ه-ز-ز, with the root verb هَزَّ meaning \"he shook,\" \"he moved,\" or \"he agitated.\" هُزِّي means \"shake!\" or \"move!\" This command embodies the root’s emphasis on initiating movement or stirring something into action. The term reflects themes of dynamic energy, responsiveness, and the ability to bring about change or effect through effort. The root further conveys notions of vigor and activity, highlighting the importance of purposeful action in achieving results or triggering a response.",
  "4164": "هُمَزَةٌ and related words stem from the root ه-م-ز, with the root verb هَمَزَ meaning \"he slandered,\" \"he mocked,\" or \"he backbit.\" هُمَزَةٌ refers to a \"backbiter\" or \"defamer,\" describing someone who secretly harms others through slander or malicious speech. The root’s focus on harm and attack is reflected in the covert nature of backbiting, which damages reputations and relationships. هُمَزَةٌ emphasizes the subtle and often hidden nature of this harm, highlighting the moral and social dangers of gossip and defamation.",
  "4165": "The noun هُنا is used to denote a place and is translated as \"here.\" It indicates a location close to the speaker or within the immediate context of the conversation. In the Qur'an, هُنا not only specifies physical proximity but can also be used to highlight a particular moment or event that is immediately relevant. Its usage can serve to draw attention to a specific point in a narrative, emphasizing the significance of what is happening in the present context, whether it’s an action, command, or divine intervention.",
  "4166": "The noun هُنالِك combines هُنَا (\"here\") with the element لِك, which introduces a sense of distance or separation. This shifts the meaning from \"here\" to something farther away, thus forming هُنالِك, meaning \"there\" or \"at that moment.\" It denotes both physical and metaphorical remoteness, often referring to a distant place or specific time. In the Qur'an, هُنالِك highlights pivotal moments or locations, drawing attention to decisive points in the narrative, and emphasizing the significance of these events or places within the broader context.",
  "4167": "هُودٌ and related words stem from the root ه-و-د, with the root verb هَادَ meaning \"he turned back\" or \"he repented.\" هُودٌ refers to the Jews, the followers of Judaism, and is also the name of Prophet Hud (ﷺ), who was sent to the people of ʿAd. The connection lies in his mission to guide his people back to the worship of Allah (ﷻ), reflecting the root's emphasis on returning to righteousness. His story exemplifies the call to abandon idolatry and embrace monotheism, highlighting the importance of repentance and adherence to Allah’s (ﷻ) guidance.",
  "4168": "هُونٌ and related words stem from the root ه-و-ن, with the root verb هَانَ meaning \"he was despised\" or \"he became insignificant.\" هُونٌ means \"humiliation\" or \"disgrace.\" The connection lies in the state of being degraded or shamed, directly reflecting the root’s focus on lowness and contempt. This term signifies the consequences of dishonor and the impact of societal or personal disgrace.",
  "4169": "هِيمٌ and related words stem from the root ه-ي-م, with the root verb هَامَ meaning \"he wandered aimlessly\" or \"he became passionately in love.\" هِيمٌ refers to \"thirsty camels,\" symbolizing a desperate, wandering search for water. The root conveys themes of uncontrolled movement, restlessness, and overwhelming need, whether driven by physical thirst or emotional desires. This highlights the inherent connection between wandering and an insatiable desire for fulfillment, reflecting the urgency and aimlessness that accompany such states.",
  "4170": "The particle و is primarily used to connect words, phrases, and sentences, meaning \"and.\" It links elements together, suggesting they are part of the same category or context. و can join nouns, verbs, adjectives, and full sentences. In some cases, و may imply contrast, especially when connecting oppositional ideas like \"truth and falsehood.\" When و links two near-synonymous words, it often emphasizes subtle differences between them, highlighting that while similar, the terms are not entirely the same. However, this is context-dependent, as و may sometimes simply reinforce an idea or provide emphasis without implying contrast.",
  "4171": "وَابِلٌ and related words stem from the root و-ب-ل, meaning \"heavy rain\" or \"violent rain.\" The root conveys themes of abundance, forcefulness, and profusion, directly reflecting the heaviness and intensity of torrential rainfall. وَابِلٌ vividly illustrates the overwhelming power of a storm, symbolizing forces that are overpowering, intense, and destructive, highlighting their devastating impact.",
  "4172": "وَاثَقَ and related words stem from the root و-ث-ق, with the root verb وَثَقَ meaning \"he trusted\" or \"he was firm.\" وَاثَقَ means \"he made an agreement with\" or \"he pledged to.\" The connection lies in the mutual act of establishing trust and firmness between parties, directly reflecting the root's emphasis on reliability. This term emphasizes the reciprocal nature of agreements and the importance of mutual trust in forming bonds.",
  "4173": "وَاجِفَةٌ and related words stem from the root و-ج-ف, with the root verb وَجَفَ meaning \"it palpitated\" or \"it beat rapidly.\" وَاجِفَةٌ means \"palpitating,\" \"throbbing,\" or \"trembling.\" The connection lies in the rapid or trembling movement, especially of the heart, directly relating to the root's emphasis on quick motion. This term vividly describes feelings of fear or anxiety that cause one's heart to beat rapidly.",
  "4174": "وَاحِدٌ and related words stem from the root و-ح-د, with the root verb وَحَدَ meaning \"he was alone\" or \"he was unique.\" وَاحِدٌ means \"one,\" \"single,\" or \"unique,\" reflecting the concept of singularity and being unparalleled. The name ٱلْواحِدُ, meaning \"The One\" or \"The Unique,\" signifies Allah’s (ﷻ) absolute oneness in essence, attributes, and actions, with no partners or equals. It emphasizes divine unity, affirming Allah (ﷻ) as the only one worthy of worship and devotion, reminding us to uphold the belief in His oneness and direct all worship and love toward Him alone.",
  "4175": "وَاحِدَةٌ and related words stem from the root و-ح-د, with the root verb وَحَدَ meaning \"he was alone\" or \"he was unique.\" وَاحِدَةٌ is the feminine form of وَاحِدٌ, meaning \"one,\" \"single,\" or \"unique\" (feminine). The connection lies in the singularity and uniqueness applied in a feminine context, directly reflecting the root's emphasis on being one. This term highlights the concept of unity and singularity in feminine nouns.",
  "4176": "وَادٍ and related words stem from the root و-د-ي, with the root verb وَدَى meaning \"it flowed\" or \"he perished.\" وَادٍ means \"valley,\" emphasizing the natural channel through which water flows. The connection to the root lies in the continuous movement and passage of water, symbolizing life's journey and the sustenance it provides. Valleys in the Qur'an often represent trials, passages, or places of refuge, highlighting the significance of guidance and the nurturing aspects of the natural world.",
  "4177": "وَادِيٌ and related words stem from the root و-د-ي, with the root verb وَدَى meaning \"it flowed\" or \"he perished.\" وَادِيٌ is another form of \"valley,\" stressing the location where water gathers and flows. The connection is in the embodiment of movement and the life-sustaining properties of flowing water, directly relating to the root's meaning. In Arabic literature and the Qur'an, the valley often symbolizes life's pathways, challenges, and the environment in which communities dwell and thrive.",
  "4178": "وَارِثٌ and related words stem from the root و-ر-ث, with the root verb وَرِثَ meaning \"he inherited.\" وَارِثٌ means \"heir\" or \"inheritor,\" reflecting the role of receiving and preserving what is entrusted. The name ٱلْوَارِث refers to \"The Inheritor\" or \"The Heir,\" highlighting that Allah (ﷻ) is the ultimate inheritor of all things, as everything returns to Him. This name signifies Allah’s (ﷻ) eternal ownership and reminds us that all possessions and dominion belong to Him. It encourages us to use our time and resources wisely, recognizing that everything we have will ultimately return to Allah (ﷻ).",
  "4179": "وَارِدٌ and related words stem from the root و-ر-د, with the root verb وَرَدَ meaning \"he came\" or \"he arrived.\" وَارِدٌ means \"one who comes,\" \"visitor,\" or \"entrant.\" This term describes someone who arrives at a place, especially with intent or purpose, directly reflecting the root's concept of approaching. In the Qur'an, it can depict those who approach significant thresholds, such as entering paradise or facing judgment, emphasizing the journey and arrival at one's ultimate fate.",
  "4180": "وَازِرَةٌ and related words stem from the root و-ز-ر, with the root verb وَزَرَ meaning \"he carried a burden\" or \"he bore a load.\" وَازِرَةٌ means \"burden-bearer\" or \"one who carries.\" The connection lies in the act of bearing weight or responsibility, directly reflecting the root's concept of carrying burdens. In the Qur'an, the phrase \"وَلَا تَزِرُ وَازِرَةٌ وِزْرَ أُخْرَىٰ\" (\"No bearer of burdens will bear the burden of another\") emphasizes personal accountability and the justice inherent in Allah's (ﷻ) judgment.",
  "4181": "واسِعٌ and related words stem from the root و-س-ع, with the verb وَسِعَ meaning \"he was vast,\" \"ample,\" or \"all-encompassing.\" واسِعٌ means \"vast,\" \"boundless,\" or \"all-encompassing,\" describing something immense in scope or capacity. The name ٱلْوَاسِعُ refers to \"The All-Encompassing\" or \"The Boundless,\" highlighting Allah’s (ﷻ) infinite mercy, knowledge, and power that extend over all creation. The connection to وَسِعَ highlights the limitless and inclusive nature of Allah’s (ﷻ) attributes, reminding us to trust in His boundless mercy and recognize His control over all matters.",
  "4182": "واسِعَةٌ and related words stem from the root و-س-ع, with the root verb وَسِعَ meaning \"he was or became ample, spacious, or extensive.\" واسِعَةٌ is the feminine form of واسِعٌ, meaning \"vast,\" \"spacious,\" or \"expansive.\" It is used to describe feminine nouns that embody vastness or great capacity. The connection to the root reflects the idea of immense space or abundance, emphasizing the ability to encompass much within. It highlights the extensive nature of what is being described, aligning with the root's emphasis on expansiveness.",
  "4183": "واصِبٌ and related words stem from the root و-ص-ب, with the root verb وَصَبَ meaning \"he became perpetual\" or \"he endured pain.\" واصِبٌ means \"continuous,\" \"everlasting,\" or \"unceasing.\" It can also mean \"painful\" or \"enduring hardship.\" The connection to the root reflects something ongoing without interruption, whether it be time, pain, or affliction. In the Qur'an, it is used to describe continuous punishment or unceasing torment, emphasizing the perpetual nature of the experience.",
  "4184": "وَاعَدَ and related words stem from root و-ع-د, with the root verb وَعَدَ meaning \"he promised.\" وَاعَدَ means \"he made a mutual promise\" or \"he agreed upon\" with someone else. The connection emphasizes the reciprocal nature of commitments, highlighting the root's focus on mutual trust and the binding nature of shared promises. This reflects the collaborative aspect of agreements, fostering unity and cooperation.",
  "4185": "واعِظٌ and related words stem from the root و-ع-ظ, with the root verb وَعَظَ meaning \"he admonished\" or \"he advised.\" واعِظٌ means \"admonisher\" or \"preacher.\" It denotes a person who delivers guidance, advice, or moral instruction to others. The connection to the root involves the role of conveying important messages intended to influence behavior and encourage ethical living.",
  "4186": "واعِيَةٌ and related words stem from the root و-ع-ى, with the root verb وَعَى meaning \"he comprehended\" or \"he retained.\" واعِيَةٌ means \"conscious,\" \"aware,\" or \"attentive,\" or \"receptive.\" The connection lies in the state of being fully aware and receptive, reflecting the root's emphasis on comprehension and mindfulness. This highlights the importance of attentiveness and the capacity to internalize and act upon knowledge, which is crucial for personal growth and understanding.",
  "4187": "واقٍ and related words stem from the root و-ق-ي, with the root verb وَقَىٰ meaning \"he guarded\" or \"he preserved.\" واقٍ means \"protector,\" referring to someone who actively provides protection or acts as a shield against harm. The root conveys themes of shielding, preserving, and safeguarding. This term emphasizes the role of guarding oneself or others from physical, moral, or spiritual harm, embodying the root’s core concept of preservation and guarding against adversity.",
  "4188": "واقِعٌ and related words stem from the root و-ق-ع, with the root verb وَقَعَ meaning \"he fell\" or \"it occurred.\" واقِعٌ translates as \"happening\" or, in some contexts, \"to fall upon,\" signifying an event that is certain to occur or befall. The connection lies in the inevitability and certainty of an event \"falling upon\" or happening to those involved. In the Qur'an, it refers to inevitable occurrences such as the Day of Judgment, punishment, or the accounting of one's deeds. This reflects the root's emphasis on the inevitability and realization of destined events.",
  "4189": "والٍ and related words stem from the root و-ل-ي, with the root verb وَلِيَ meaning \"he was near,\" \"he befriended,\" or \"he protected.\" والٍ means \"governor\" or \"protector.\" The connection is direct, representing someone who is close in authority and responsibility, reflecting the root's concepts of guardianship and leadership. It emphasizes the role of overseeing, guiding, and protecting others.",
  "4190": "والِدٌ and related words stem from the root و-ل-د, with the root verb وَلَدَ meaning \"he begot\" or \"he gave birth.\" والِدٌ means \"father\" or \"parent.\" The connection lies in the role of one who contributes to birth, directly relating to the root's concept of procreation. It emphasizes paternal responsibility and the bond between father and child.",
  "4191": "والِدَةٌ and related words stem from the root و-ل-د, with the root verb وَلَدَ meaning \"he begot\" or \"he gave birth.\" والِدَةٌ means \"mother.\" The connection is inherent, representing the female who gives birth, embodying the root's core concept of bearing offspring. It emphasizes motherhood and the nurturing role associated with giving life.",
  "4192": "وَالِدَيَّ and related words stem from the root و-ل-د, with the root verb وَلَدَ meaning \"he begot\" or \"he gave birth.\" وَالِدَيَّ means \"my two parents\" or \"my mother and father.\" The connection refers to both parents, directly relating to the root's concept of begetting and birth. It highlights the shared role of both parents in giving life and nurturing their children.",
  "4193": "واهِيَةٌ and related words stem from the root و-ه-ى, with the root verb وَهَى meaning \"it became weak\" or \"it decayed.\" واهِيَةٌ means \"frail,\" \"fragile,\" or \"delicate.\" The connection lies in the state of weakness or deterioration, reflecting the root's concept of structural frailty. It emphasizes vulnerability and the potential for collapse, highlighting the importance of strength and support.",
  "4194": "وَبَالٌ and related words stem from the root و-ب-ل, meaning \"evil consequence\" or \"dire result.\" The root emphasizes burdensomeness and heaviness in a negative sense, reflecting the oppressive nature of harmful outcomes. وَبَالٌ signifies the weight of sin and its repercussions, highlighting the grave consequences of wrongful actions and the moral and spiritual burdens they impose, serving as a stark reminder of accountability.",
  "4195": "وَبِيلٌ and related words stem from the root و-ب-ل, meaning \"grievous,\" \"severe,\" or \"harsh.\" The root connection lies in the intensity and burdensomeness of affliction or calamity, emphasizing the oppressive and forceful nature of severe hardship. وَبِيلٌ captures the gravity of punishment or trial, evoking imagery of overwhelming and inescapable consequences, highlighting the seriousness of certain situations or divine retribution.",
  "4196": "وَتِينَ and related words stem from the root و-ت-ن, with the root verb وَتَنَ meaning \"he cut\" or \"he severed.\" وَتِينَ refers to \"the life-artery\" or \"the aorta,\" the main artery of the heart. The connection lies in the critical importance of the aorta in sustaining life, and the act of cutting it results in death, directly relating to the root's emphasis on severing. This term underscores the fragility of life and the ultimate power over life and death.",
  "4197": "وَتْرٌ and related words stem from the root و-ت-ر, with the root verb وَتَرَ meaning \"he deprived,\" \"he made solitary,\" or \"he left alone.\" وَتْرٌ means \"odd number\" or \"that which is single or alone.\" The connection lies in the concept of singularity or being without a pair, directly reflecting the root's emphasis on solitude or deprivation. In Islamic tradition, Allah (ﷻ) is referred to as الْوَتْرُ (\"The One\"), emphasizing His uniqueness and oneness.",
  "4198": "وَثَاقٌ and related words stem from the root و-ث-ق, with the root verb وَثَقَ meaning \"he was firm\" or \"he secured.\" وَثَاقٌ means \"bond,\" \"tie,\" or \"fetters.\" The connection lies in the idea of firmly securing or binding something, directly relating to the root's emphasis on firmness and security. This term often refers to physical bonds used to restrain, symbolizing control or captivity.",
  "4199": "وَجَبَتْ and related words stem from the root و-ج-ب, with the root verb وَجَبَ meaning \"he fell,\" or \"he fell on the ground and died,\" or \"it became necessary,\" or \"it became obligatory.\" وَجَبَتْ means \"it fell\" or \"it became due.\" The connection lies in the concept of something occurring inevitably or becoming incumbent, directly relating to the root's meaning. This term signifies the certainty and inevitability of an event or obligation, emphasizing its unavoidable nature.",
  "4200": "وَجَدَ and related words stem from the root و-ج-د, and as the root verb, it means \"he found,\" \"he discovered,\" or \"he attained.\" This reflects the act of finding or perceiving, encompassing both physical discovery and emotional experiences like joy or sorrow. The name ٱلْوَاجِدُ, meaning \"The Finder\" or \"The Perceiver,\" highlights Allah’s (ﷻ) complete knowledge and ability to find all things. It signifies that nothing is hidden from Him and emphasizes divine perception. This serves as a reminder to trust in Allah’s (ﷻ) knowledge and seek His guidance in uncovering truth and understanding.",
  "4201": "وَجِلٌ and related words stem from the root و-ج-ل, with the root verb وَجِلَ meaning \"he feared,\" \"he was anxious,\" or \"he was apprehensive.\" وَجِلٌ means \"fearful,\" \"anxious,\" or \"apprehensive.\" The connection lies in the emotional state of fear or unease, directly reflecting the root's emphasis on apprehension. This term captures the inner feelings of trepidation in the face of uncertainty or danger.",
  "4202": "وَجِلَةٌ and related words stem from the root و-ج-ل, with the root verb وَجِلَ meaning \"he feared\" or \"he was anxious.\" وَجِلَةٌ means \"fearful,\" \"anxious,\" or \"apprehensive.\" The connection lies in experiencing fear or unease, directly relating to the root's emphasis on apprehension. This term expresses the state of being fearful, particularly in a feminine context.",
  "4203": "وَجِلَتْ and related words stem from the root و-ج-ل, with the root verb وَجِلَ meaning \"he feared\" or \"he was anxious.\" وَجِلَتْ means \"she feared\" or \"she became anxious.\" The connection lies in the act of experiencing fear or apprehension, directly reflecting the root's meaning. This term highlights the moment of fear felt by a female subject, emphasizing the emotional response to a situation.",
  "4204": "وَجِيهٌ and related words stem from the root و-ج-ه, with the root verb وَجَهَ meaning \"he faced\" or \"he directed.\" The word وَجْهٌ means \"face\" or \"countenance,\" and وَجِيهٌ means \"distinguished,\" \"honorable,\" or \"of high status.\" The connection lies in the face being a symbol of honor and recognition, directly relating to the root's emphasis on the face. This term signifies someone who is esteemed or holds a prominent position, reflecting respect and dignity.",
  "4205": "وَجَّهَ and related words stem from the root و-ج-ه, with the root verb وَجَهَ meaning \"he directed\" or \"he oriented.\" وَجَّهَ means \"he directed,\" \"he turned,\" or \"he caused to face.\" The connection lies in the action of making something or someone face a certain direction, directly reflecting the root's emphasis on facing or directing. This term highlights the act of guidance or orientation towards a particular focus.",
  "4206": "وَجْهٌ and related words stem from the root و-ج-ه, with the root verb وَجَهَ meaning \"he directed\" or \"he oriented.\" وَجْهٌ means \"face,\" \"aspect,\" or \"front.\" The connection lies in the most prominent and expressive part of a person, directly reflecting the root's emphasis on the face. This term can also signify direction, aspect, or manner, highlighting the multifaceted ways in which the concept of \"face\" is applied, both literally and metaphorically, such as turning one's face towards something symbolizing attention or intention.",
  "4207": "وَحِيدٌ and related words stem from the root و-ح-د, with the root verb وَحَدَ meaning \"he was alone\" or \"he became solitary.\" وَحِيدٌ means \"lonely,\" \"solitary,\" or \"alone,\" often emphasizing a state of isolation or separation. The root encompasses themes of singularity and detachment, reflecting a state where someone stands apart from others, either by circumstance or as a deliberate choice. وَحِيدٌ conveys not just the condition of being alone but also its potential vulnerability, highlighting an existence without companionship or support. This can reflect a sense of being left to one’s own devices, symbolizing independence yet also fragility.",
  "4208": "وَحْدٌ and related words also derive from the root و-ح-د, with وَحَدَ meaning \"he was alone\" or \"he was unique.\" وَحْدٌ means \"singleness,\" \"solitude,\" or \"aloneness,\" with a focus on exclusivity and oneness. Unlike وَحِيدٌ, it lacks emotional undertones and is used to emphasize the idea of independence or uniqueness, often in a definitive and absolute sense. It signifies the concept of singular devotion or acknowledgment, where something or someone is recognized as standing alone, unrivaled, or exclusive in importance. This conveys the notion of unwavering singularity, often linked to the recognition of oneness and ultimate authority.",
  "4209": "وَحْيٌ and related words stem from the root و-ح-ى, with the root verb وَحَى meaning \"he revealed\" or \"he inspired.\" وَحْيٌ means \"revelation,\" \"inspiration,\" or \"divine communication.\" The connection lies in the concept of messages or guidance being imparted subtly or from a divine source, directly relating to the root's emphasis on inspiration. This term is central to the Islamic understanding of how prophets receive guidance from Allah (ﷻ), highlighting the sacredness of the message.",
  "4210": "وَدُودٌ and related words stem from the root و-د-د, with the root verb وَدَّ meaning \"he loved\" or \"he desired.\" وَدُودٌ means \"loving,\" \"affectionate,\" or \"kind.\" The connection lies in the attribute of being full of love and affection, directly reflecting the root's emphasis on love. , As one of the perfect names of Allah (ﷻ), the word الْوَدُودُ signifies His boundless love and kindness towards His creation, highlighting the divine attribute of infinite compassion.",
  "4211": "وَدّ and related words stem from the root و-د-د, with the root verb وَدَّ meaning \"he loved,\" \"he wished,\" or \"he desired.\" وَدّ refers to an idol worshipped by the people of Prophet Noah (ﷺ), representing affection, love, or desire. Originally a righteous man, Wadd was honored after his death, but reverence, influenced by Satan’s whispers, led to idol worship. The root emphasizes themes of attachment and longing, reflecting emotional ties to what people hold dear. The idol Wadd symbolized misplaced devotion, reminding us to reserve ultimate love for Allah (ﷻ), the true source of affection and fulfillment.",
  "4212": "وَدَّ and related words stem from root و-د-د, with the root verb وَدَّ meaning \"he loved,\" \"he wished,\" or \"he desired.\" The connection lies in the act of feeling love or strong desire towards someone or something, directly reflecting the root's emphasis on affection. This term encompasses both emotional love and the wish for something to occur, highlighting the depth of human emotions and aspirations.",
  "4213": "وَدَّعَ and related words stem from the root و-د-ع, with the root verb وَدَعَ meaning \"he left,\" \"he abandoned,\" or \"he let alone.\" وَدَّعَ is an intensified form meaning \"he bade farewell\" or \"he took leave of.\" This intensification signifies a meaningful and deliberate departure, connecting deeply to the root's concept of leaving behind. The term highlights the emotional aspect of parting, transforming a simple act of leaving into a significant farewell. In the Qur'an, it reassures the Prophet (ﷺ) that Allah (ﷻ) has not forsaken him: \"مَا وَدَّعَكَ رَبُّكَ وَمَا قَلَىٰ\" (\"Your Lord has not forsaken you nor has He despised you\"), emphasizing the enduring connection between the divine and the messenger.",
  "4214": "وَدْقٌ and related words stem from the root و-د-ق, with the root verb وَدَقَ meaning \"it rained lightly\" or \"it drizzled.\" وَدْقٌ means \"rain\" or \"drizzle.\" The connection lies in the gentle, continuous nature of light rain, embodying the root's concept of a subtle, permeating action. This term reflects how a steady drizzle nourishes the earth quietly yet effectively. In the Qur'an, such rain symbolizes Allah’s (ﷻ) mercy and the sustenance He provides, illustrating how even the smallest blessings can have profound effects on life.",
  "4215": "The particle وَرَاءَ is a preposition meaning \"behind,\" \"beyond,\" or \"ahead,\" used to indicate position or direction in both physical and abstract contexts. Physically, it refers to something located at the back or beyond a certain point, as in وَرَاءَ الجَبَلِ (behind the mountain). Abstractly, it conveys meanings such as \"behind\" in scope, time, or understanding, as in وَرَاءَ هَذَا القَرَارِ حِكْمَةٌ (behind this decision is wisdom). Its usage in Arabic adds depth and nuance by expressing relationships involving space, time, or abstract notions, highlighting elements that are hidden or less visible. This versatility makes it an essential part of Arabic expression in both descriptive and rhetorical contexts.",
  "4216": "وَرَدَ and related words stem from the root و-ر-د, meaning \"he came,\" \"he arrived,\" or \"he reached.\" This verb encapsulates the action of approaching a destination, often used in contexts like arriving at a watering place. The connection lies in the essential movement towards sustenance or fulfillment, reflecting the root's emphasis on seeking and reaching what is necessary for survival or success.",
  "4217": "وَرَقٌ and related words stem from the root و-ر-ق, with the root verb وَرِقَ meaning \"it became green\" or \"it was verdant.\" وَرَقٌ means \"leaf,\" \"leaves,\" or \"paper.\" The connection lies in the life and growth symbolized by leaves, reflecting the root's concept of greenness and vitality. Additionally, leaves as pages represent knowledge and record-keeping. In some contexts, وَرَقٌ can also refer to silver, highlighting value and exchange, connecting growth with wealth.",
  "4218": "وَرَقَةٌ and related words stem from the root و-ر-ق, with the root verb وَرِقَ meaning \"it became green.\" وَرَقَةٌ means \"leaf\" or \"sheet of paper.\" The connection is direct, focusing on an individual leaf, symbolizing a unit of growth or a single page of knowledge. This term emphasizes the importance of each element in the larger system, whether in nature or in written works.",
  "4219": "وَرِثَ and related words stem from the root و-ر-ث, meaning \"he inherited\" or \"he received as inheritance.\" This verb encapsulates the act of receiving property, knowledge, or status from predecessors, reflecting the root's emphasis on succession. The connection lies in the continuity of lineage, traditions, and responsibilities passed down through generations. In Islamic teachings, inheritance laws derived from this root ensure justice and familial harmony, emphasizing the importance of rightful succession.",
  "4220": "وَرِقٌ and related words stem from the root و-ر-ق, with the root verb وَرِقَ meaning \"it became white\" or \"it shone.\" وَرِقٌ means \"silver\" or \"silver coins.\" The connection lies in the lustrous, shining quality of silver, embodying the root's concept of brightness and value. In the Qur'an, it appears in the story of the People of the Cave (أصحاب الكهف), referring to silver coins, which signifies material wealth and the passage of time.",
  "4221": "وَرِيدٌ and related words stem from the root و-ر-د, with the root verb وَرَدَ meaning \"he came\" or \"he arrived.\" وَرِيدٌ refers to \"the jugular vein.\" The connection lies in the vein being a critical pathway through which blood \"arrives\" at vital organs, embodying the root's concept of essential flow and approach. In the Qur'an, Allah (ﷻ) says, \"وَنَحْنُ أَقْرَبُ إِلَيْهِ مِنْ حَبْلِ الْوَرِيدِ\" (\"And We are nearer to him than his jugular vein\"), highlighting His intimate closeness to us, more so than our own lifeblood.",
  "4222": "وَرْدَةٌ and related words stem from the root و-ر-د, with the root verb وَرَدَ meaning \"he came\" or \"he arrived.\" وَرْدَةٌ means \"rose.\" The connection lies in the rose being the blossoming arrival in a garden, symbolizing beauty and new beginnings. This reflects the root's concept of appearing or coming forth. In the Qur'an, the term is used to describe vivid imagery, as in the sky becoming \"like a rose\" during the end times, emphasizing dramatic transformation.",
  "4223": "وَزَرٌ and related words stem from the root و-ز-ر, with the root verb وَزَرَ meaning \"he carried a burden\" or \"he sought refuge.\" وَزَرٌ means \"refuge,\" \"shelter,\" or \"burden.\" The connection lies in both seeking a place to escape burdens and the burdens themselves, reflecting the dual aspects of the root. In the Qur'an, it can signify a stronghold or a metaphorical burden of sin, highlighting the human need for protection and the weight of moral responsibility.",
  "4224": "وَزَنَ and related words stem from the root و-ز-ن, meaning \"he weighed.\" This verb encapsulates the act of measuring weight or evaluating balance, directly reflecting the root's focus on assessment. The connection lies in determining value or fairness through measurement, whether of physical objects or metaphorically of deeds and intentions, emphasizing the importance of justice and careful consideration.",
  "4225": "وَزِيرٌ and related words stem from the root و-ز-ر, with the root verb وَزَرَ meaning \"he carried a burden.\" وَزِيرٌ means \"minister\" or \"assistant,\" one who helps carry responsibilities. The connection lies in sharing the burdens of leadership or governance, directly reflecting the root's concept of carrying weight. This term underscores the importance of collaboration and support in effectively managing affairs and upholding justice.",
  "4226": "وَزْنٌ and related words stem from the root و-ز-ن, with the root verb وَزَنَ meaning \"he weighed.\" وَزْنٌ means \"weight\" or \"measure.\" The connection lies in the concept of weight as a standard for evaluation, embodying the root's emphasis on balance and fairness. This term highlights the importance of accurate measurement in both physical and moral contexts, reinforcing the value of equity and proportionality.",
  "4227": "وَسَطٌ and related words stem from the root و-س-ط, with the root verb وَسَطَ meaning \"he was in the middle.\" وَسَطٌ means \"middle\" or \"center.\" The connection is direct, emphasizing centrality and balance, embodying the root's concept of being equidistant from extremes. This term highlights the ideal of moderation and the importance of maintaining equilibrium in various aspects of life.",
  "4228": "وَسَطٌ and related words stem from the root و-س-ط, with the root verb وَسَطَ meaning \"he was in the middle.\" وَسَطٌ means \"middle\" or \"center.\" The connection is direct, emphasizing centrality and balance, embodying the root's concept of being equidistant from extremes. This term highlights the ideal of moderation and the importance of maintaining equilibrium in various aspects of life.",
  "4229": "وَسَقَ and related words stem from the root و-س-ق, and as the root verb, it means \"he gathered,\" \"he collected,\" or \"he bound together.\" وَسَقَ means \"he gathered together\" or \"he amassed.\" This connects to the root's emphasis on assembling or bringing together elements into a collective whole. In the Qur'an, it is used to describe the night as it envelops or gathers everything in darkness, highlighting the encompassing nature of nightfall.",
  "4230": "وَسِعَ and related words stem from the root و-س-ع, and as the root verb, it means \"he was or became ample, spacious, or extensive.\" وَسِعَ means \"he encompassed,\" \"he was sufficient for,\" or \"he contained.\" This reflects the capacity to hold or include something within oneself, emphasizing sufficiency and comprehensiveness. The connection to the root underscores expansiveness and the ability to encompass or be sufficient for something, highlighting the notion of boundless capacity.",
  "4231": "وَسِيلَةٌ and related words stem from the root و-س-ل, with the root verb وَسَلَ meaning \"he reached,\" \"he attained,\" or \"he drew near.\" وَسِيلَةٌ means \"means,\" \"medium,\" or \"way of approach.\" It refers to something that brings one closer to a goal or desired outcome. The connection to the root lies in the idea of attaining closeness through a medium or intermediary. In Islamic context, seeking a وَسِيلَةٌ to Allah (ﷻ) involves using righteous deeds as a means to draw nearer to Him.",
  "4232": "وَسْوَاسٌ and related words stem from the root و-س-و-س, with the root verb وَسْوَسَ meaning \"to whisper.\" وَسْوَاسٌ means \"whispering,\" \"temptation,\" or \"evil suggestion.\" It refers to the secretive and persistent promptings that incite doubt or wrongdoing, often associated with the whisperings of Satan. The repetitive sounds in the root mimic the act of whispering, emphasizing the subtle and continuous nature of these temptations that infiltrate the heart and mind.",
  "4233": "وَسْوَسَ and related words stem from the root و-س-و-س, and as the root verb, it means \"he whispered\" or \"he insinuated evil thoughts.\" It reflects the act of subtly instilling ideas or temptations into someone's mind. The connection to the root lies in the repetitive and insidious nature of whispering, highlighting how such suggestions can persistently influence a person's thoughts and actions without overt force.",
  "4234": "وَصِيدٌ and related words stem from the root و-ص-د, with the root verb وَصَدَ meaning \"he enclosed\" or \"he confined.\" وَصِيدٌ means \"entrance,\" \"threshold,\" or \"enclosure.\" It refers to an open space or area adjacent to something enclosed, like the entrance of a cave. The connection to the root lies in the idea of a confined space that serves as a barrier or transitional area. In the story of the People of the Cave, وَصِيدٌ refers to the area where their dog stretched out at the cave's entrance.",
  "4235": "وَصِيلَةٌ and related words stem from the root و-ص-ل, with the root verb وَصَلَ meaning \"he connected\" or \"he joined.\" وَصِيلَةٌ refers to a specific pre-Islamic Arab practice where a she-camel was set free after giving birth to a consecutive pair of female offspring without a male between them. The connection to the root lies in the concept of connection or continuation, as the animal was seen as connected in lineage without interruption. This term reflects cultural practices where lineage and succession were significant.",
  "4236": "وَصِيَّةٌ and related words stem from the root و-ص-ي, with the root verb وَصَّى meaning \"he enjoined\" or \"he advised earnestly.\" وَصِيَّةٌ means \"will,\" \"testament,\" or \"bequest.\" It refers to a directive given by a person regarding their property or wishes to be carried out after death. The connection to the root involves the act of entrusting important instructions to others, emphasizing the seriousness and binding nature of such declarations.",
  "4237": "وَصَّلْنَا and related words stem from the root و-ص-ل, with the root verb وَصَلَ meaning \"he connected\" or \"he joined.\" وَصَّلْنَا means \"We repeatedly conveyed\" or \"We delivered,\" reflecting the act of transmitting or joining something to its destination. The root encompasses themes of connection, continuity, and maintaining bonds, whether physical, relational, or conceptual. It highlights the importance of unity and the seamless flow of actions or messages. In the context of وَصَّلْنَا, it emphasizes deliberate and purposeful conveying, ensuring that what is transmitted fulfills its intended purpose with care and precision.",
  "4238": "وَصَّى and related words stem from the root و-ص-ي, with the root verb وَصَّى meaning \"he enjoined\" or \"he advised earnestly.\" وَصَّى means \"he enjoined emphatically\" or \"he urged repeatedly.\" The intensified form reflects a strong emphasis on the action of giving important advice or commands. The connection to the root highlights the seriousness and importance of the instructions given, often in a moral or religious context.",
  "4239": "وَصْفٌ and related words stem from the root و-ص-ف, with the root verb وَصَفَ meaning \"he described,\" \"he characterized,\" or \"he assigned qualities to.\" وَصْفٌ means \"description,\" \"attribute,\" or \"characterization,\" reflecting the act of portraying the qualities of something or someone. The root emphasizes articulation, precision, and truthful representation, ensuring qualities are conveyed accurately. This highlights the role of descriptions in shaping understanding and perception, aligning with the root's broader themes of assigning and specifying.",
  "4240": "وَضَعَ and related words stem from the root و-ض-ع, and as the root verb, it means \"he placed\" or \"he set down.\" It conveys the action of putting something in a particular position or lowering it. The connection to the root is straightforward, emphasizing the fundamental act of placement or positioning. It can also mean \"he gave birth,\" reflecting the act of bringing forth or producing.",
  "4241": "وَطَرٌ and related words stem from the root و-ط-ر, with the root verb وَطَرَ meaning \"he desired\" or \"he needed.\" وَطَرٌ means \"desire,\" \"need,\" or \"objective.\" It refers to an aim or goal that one seeks to fulfill. The connection to the root emphasizes longing or an unmet need that drives action. In the Qur'an, it highlights the fulfillment of one's desires or the completion of certain obligations.",
  "4242": "وَطْءٌ and related words stem from the root و-ط-أ, with the root verb وَطِئَ meaning \"he trod upon\" or \"he stepped.\" وَطْءٌ means \"impact\" or \"intensity,\" highlighting the weight or effect of an action, akin to the force exerted by treading. The term reflects the underlying themes of effort, pressure, and the profound effects one’s actions can have, both physically and metaphorically.",
  "4243": "وَعَدَ and related words stem from the root و-ع-د, and as the root verb, it means \"he promised\" or \"he gave his word.\" This root verb encapsulates the fundamental act of making a commitment or assurance about a future action. The connection lies in establishing trust and reliability, which are essential for strong relationships and societal cohesion. In the Qur'an, Allah (ﷻ) often uses this term to affirm His promises to humanity, highlighting His faithfulness and the certainty of His word.",
  "4244": "وَعَظَ and related words stem from the root و-ع-ظ, with the root verb وَعَظَ meaning \"he admonished,\" \"he advised,\" or \"he counseled.\" The root conveys themes of imparting wisdom, offering moral guidance, and delivering heartfelt reminders. وَعَظَ emphasizes the act of giving advice or warnings that touch the heart, aiming to inspire positive change and reflection. The connection lies in addressing both intellect and emotion, reflecting the root's focus on impactful communication that motivates individuals to avoid wrongdoing and strive for righteousness.",
  "4245": "وَعِيدٌ and related words stem from the root و-ع-د, with the root verb وَعَدَ meaning \"he promised.\" وَعِيدٌ means \"threat\" or \"warning.\" The connection lies in a promise of negative consequences, reflecting the root's dual capacity for promises of good or ill. This emphasizes the seriousness of warnings and the moral responsibility to heed them, highlighting the potential repercussions of one's actions.",
  "4246": "وَعْدٌ and related words stem from the root و-ع-د, with the root verb وَعَدَ meaning \"he promised.\" وَعْدٌ means \"promise.\" The connection is the commitment to fulfill what one has pledged, reflecting the root's emphasis on trust and reliability. This highlights the moral obligation to keep one's word, which is fundamental to personal integrity and societal trust.",
  "4247": "وَفَّىٰ and related words stem from the root و-ف-ى, with the root verb وَفَىٰ meaning \"he fulfilled\" or \"he completed.\" وَفَّىٰ intensifies the meaning to \"he fulfilled completely\" or \"he paid in full,\" emphasizing the thoroughness and perfection in fulfilling obligations. The connection lies in the meticulous execution of duties, reflecting the root's emphasis on total fulfillment. This highlights the importance of not only meeting commitments but doing so fully and with wholehearted effort, reinforcing personal integrity and trust.",
  "4248": "وَفْدٌ and related words stem from the root و-ف-د, with the root verb وَفَدَ meaning \"he came as a delegate\" or \"he arrived.\" وَفْدٌ means \"delegation,\" \"envoy,\" or \"group of visitors.\" The connection lies in the idea of approaching with purpose and honor, often in a formal or collective manner. This reflects the root's emphasis on arrival with significance, as seen in the Qur'an when the righteous are described as being brought to Allah (ﷻ) in an esteemed and dignified manner, akin to a noble delegation.",
  "4249": "وَقَارٌ and related words stem from the root و-ق-ر, with the root verb وَقَرَ meaning \"he was dignified, steady, and reliable.\" وَقَارٌ refers to a state of dignity, respectability, firmness, and consistency, characterized by calmness and freedom from agitation. The connection lies in the root's emphasis on weight and steadiness, symbolizing a person or entity of substantial presence and composure. When applied to Allah (ﷻ), the word وَقَارٌ means majestic greatness, reflecting His ultimate perfection and grandeur, emphasizing awe and reverence for His unparalleled attributes.",
  "4250": "وَقَبَ and related words stem from the root و-ق-ب, with the root verb وَقَبَ meaning \"it entered.\" This root conveys the idea of something moving inward or spreading into a space, often associated with darkness or shadows as they enter and envelop their surroundings. The connection lies in the imagery of penetration, where an entity, such as darkness or night, invades and fills a space completely. This reflects the root's emphasis on movement, transition, and the act of permeation, symbolizing inevitable or encompassing entry.",
  "4251": "وَقَعَ and related words stem from the root verb و-ق-ع, and as the root verb, it means \"he fell,\" \"it happened,\" or \"it occurred.\" This verb encapsulates the core concept of an action or event coming to pass or \"falling\" into reality. The root conveys themes of falling, happening, or occurring, emphasizing the inevitability and realization of events as they manifest or are fulfilled. It highlights the tangible and impactful nature of actions or occurrences as they \"descend upon\" a situation or individual.",
  "4252": "وَقَىٰ and related words stem from the root و-ق-ي, and as the root verb, it means \"he guarded,\" or \"he preserved.\" This verb encapsulates the fundamental concept of shielding someone or something from harm. It highlights the act of proactive protection, whether physical, moral, or spiritual. The root’s emphasis on preservation extends to related concepts like piety and self-guarding, where God-consciousness serves as a spiritual shield against sin and misguidance, aligning human actions with divine guidance.",
  "4253": "وَقُودٌ and related words stem from the root و-ق-د, with the root verb وَقَدَ meaning \"it kindled,\" \"it ignited,\" or \"it flamed.\" وَقُودٌ means \"fuel\" or \"firewood,\" referring to any material that sustains a fire and keeps it burning. The root conveys themes of ignition, sustenance, and continuous energy. The connection lies in the role of fuel as the essential element that feeds combustion, reflecting the root’s emphasis on the process of kindling and sustaining flames. This term highlights the dynamic nature of fire as dependent on an external source, symbolizing how external factors often drive or sustain powerful forces.",
  "4254": "وَقْتٌ and related words stem from the root و-ق-ت, with the root verb وَقَتَ meaning \"he fixed a time.\" وَقْتٌ means \"time\" or \"period.\" The connection lies in the measurement and recognition of time, reflecting the root's emphasis on temporal allocation. ",
  "4255": "وَقْرٌ and related words stem from the root و-ق-ر, with the root verb وَقَرَ meaning \"he became dull of hearing\" or \"he was deaf.\" وَقْرٌ translates as \"deafness,\" emphasizing a sense of heaviness or obstruction in hearing. The connection to the root lies in the concept of weight, where deafness metaphorically reflects the inability to perceive sound, as if burdened by an auditory heaviness. This deafness acts as a barrier, rendering those who deliberately reject the truth unable to understand or receive guidance.",
  "4256": "وَقْعَةٌ and related words stem from the root و-ق-ع, with the root verb وَقَعَ meaning \"he fell\" or \"it occurred.\" وَقْعَةٌ means \"an event\" or \"an occurrence,\" often referring to a significant or impactful happening. The connection lies in the forceful or sudden nature of an event that \"falls upon\" those involved, such as the commencement of a battle or a dramatic incident. It reflects the root's emphasis on occurrences with substantial effects, marking moments that profoundly alter circumstances.",
  "4257": "وَكَزَ and related words stem from the root و-ك-ز, with the root verb وَكَزَ meaning \"he struck,\" often referring to striking or beating with a fist. The root conveys themes of suddenness, physical force, and direct impact. The connection lies in the abrupt and intense nature of the action, reflecting decisive or forceful intervention. This root emphasizes sharp and impactful actions, symbolizing strength, swiftness, and the ability to produce immediate results, whether through physical or metaphorical force.",
  "4258": "وَكِيلٌ and related words stem from the root و-كـ-ل, with the verb وَكَـلَ meaning \"he entrusted\" or \"he relied upon.\" وَكِيلٌ means \"guardian,\" \"trustee,\" or \"agent,\" emphasizing someone entrusted with responsibilities and reflecting the root’s concepts of trust, reliance, and delegation. ٱلْوَكِيلُ, one of Allah’s (ﷻ) beautiful names, means \"The Trustee,\" signifying Allah’s (ﷻ) role as the ultimate guardian and protector, fully relied upon to manage all affairs. The connection to وَكَـلَ highlights divine reliability, care, and the perfection of Allah’s (ﷻ) management, reminding us to entrust our lives to His wisdom and protection, knowing that His guidance is infallible.",
  "4259": "وِلَايَةٌ and related words stem from the root و-ل-ي, with the root verb وَلِيَ meaning \"he was near,\" \"he befriended,\" or \"he protected.\" وِلَايَةٌ means \"guardianship,\" \"authority,\" or \"sovereignty.\" The connection embodies the state of having authority or guardianship over others, reflecting the root's emphasis on closeness and protection. It signifies responsibility, leadership, and the power associated with governance.",
  "4260": "وَلَدٌ and related words stem from the root و-ل-د, with the root verb وَلَدَ meaning \"he begot\" or \"he gave birth.\" وَلَدٌ means \"child\" or \"son.\" The connection is straightforward, representing the offspring resulting from birth, reflecting the root's fundamental concept of procreation. It emphasizes lineage, inheritance, and familial bonds.",
  "4261": "وَلَدَ and related words stem from the root و-ل-د, and as the root verb, it means \"he begot\" or \"he gave birth.\" The root conveys broader concepts of creation, lineage, procreation, and continuity. The connection is direct, emphasizing the act of bringing forth offspring as the core meaning. It reflects the generative process central to the continuation of family lines, symbolizing origins, relationships, and the perpetuation of life through successive generations.",
  "4262": "وَلِيجَةٌ and related words stem from the root و-ل-ج, with the root verb وَلَجَ meaning \"he entered.\" وَلِيجَةٌ means \"an intimate associate\" or \"confidant,\" referring to someone who has \"entered\" one's private circle or affairs. The root conveys themes of entry, transition, and integration, reflecting the deep trust required to allow someone into personal or private matters. وَلِيجَةٌ signifies a relationship of closeness and reliance, highlighting the bond between individuals who share inner secrets or play integral roles in each other's lives.",
  "4263": "وَلِيدٌ and related words stem from the root و-ل-د, with the root verb وَلَدَ meaning \"he begot\" or \"he gave birth.\" وَلِيدٌ means \"infant,\" \"young one,\" or \"child,\" reflecting the state of being recently born or young. The root conveys broader concepts of creation, lineage, and origin, emphasizing the process of bringing forth new life. The connection lies in the root’s focus on the act and result of birth, highlighting themes of vulnerability, dependence, and the pure beginnings of life, symbolizing potential and continuity within a lineage.",
  "4264": "وَلِيٌّ and related words stem from the root و-ل-ي, with the root verb وَلِيَ meaning \"he was near,\" \"he befriended,\" or \"he protected.\" وَلِيٌّ means \"friend,\" \"guardian,\" or \"ally,\" reflecting the root's concepts of nearness, protection, and loyalty. The connection lies in the close and supportive relationship, emphasizing bonds of trust, guardianship, and mutual support. ٱلْوَلِيُّ, one of Allah’s (ﷻ) beautiful names, means \"The Guardian,\" signifying His closeness to His servants and His role in providing unwavering protection, guidance, and care, embodying the ultimate expression of the root's meanings.",
  "4265": "وَلَّىٰ and related words stem from the root و-ل-ي, with the root verb وَلِيَ meaning \"he was near,\" \"he befriended,\" or \"he protected.\" وَلَّىٰ means \"he turned away\" or \"he appointed,\" reflecting actions that involve shifting focus, position, or responsibility. The root conveys broader concepts of nearness, closeness, guardianship, and authority. The connection lies in the idea of changing proximity or relationship, whether by turning away or transferring authority, emphasizing the root’s focus on relationships and movement in closeness or responsibility.",
  "4266": "وَهَبَ and related words stem from the root و-ه-ب, and as the root verb, it means \"he gave, bestowed, or granted as a gift.\" The root conveys broader concepts of selflessness, generosity, and unconditional giving, emphasizing acts done without expectation of return. وَهَبَ reflects the essence of freely bestowing favors or gifts, embodying benevolence and magnanimity. The connection lies in the root’s focus on gracious giving, highlighting the idea of granting with abundance.",
  "4267": "وَهَنَ and related words stem from the root و-ه-ن, and as the root verb, it means \"he weakened\" or \"he became feeble.\" The root conveys broader concepts of fragility, vulnerability, and diminished strength, whether physical, emotional, or moral. The connection is direct, reflecting the state of losing strength or vigor and emphasizing a decline in power, resilience, or resolve.",
  "4268": "الْوَهَّابُ and related words stem from the root و-ه-ب, with the root verb وَهَبَ meaning \"he granted,\" \"he bestowed,\" or \"he gave as a gift.\" الْوَهَّابُ is an intensive form meaning \"The Bestower\" or \"The Giver of Gifts,\" emphasizing abundant and continuous giving. As one of Allah’s (ﷻ) beautiful names, it reflects His boundless generosity in providing blessings without limit or expectation of return. The root conveys the idea of selfless and gracious giving, and الْوَهَّابُ highlights Allah’s (ﷻ) unparalleled ability to infinitely grant both material and spiritual gifts.",
  "4269": "وَهَّاجٌ and related words stem from the root و-ه-ج, with the root verb وَهَجَ meaning \"it blazed\" or \"it radiated heat.\" وَهَّاجٌ is an intensive form meaning \"blazing\" or \"intensely hot.\" The connection lies in the root's concept of intense heat or brightness. It emphasizes a powerful radiance or fiery nature, often used to describe the sun or intense flames, highlighting overwhelming brilliance or energy.",
  "4270": "وَهْنٌ and related words stem from the root و-ه-ن, with the root verb وَهَنَ meaning \"he weakened\" or \"he became feeble.\" وَهْنٌ means \"weakness\" or \"feebleness,\" describing a state of diminished strength or vitality. The root conveys broader concepts of fragility, vulnerability, and loss of power, whether physical, emotional, or moral. The connection lies in emphasizing human vulnerability and the challenges associated with weakness and difficulty.",
  "4271": "The particle وَيْ is used to express strong emotions such as surprise, sorrow, regret, or distress, translated as \"Woe!\" or \"Oh!\" or \"Ah!\" It functions as an exclamatory expression, either used alone or combined with other words to intensify the emotional impact. In classical Arabic, it draws attention to a grievous situation, serving as a self-admonition or a warning to others. In the Qur'an, وَيْ conveys astonishment or realization, acting as a rhetorical device that emphasizes the severity of consequences, urging reflection and caution.",
  "4272": "وَيْلٌ and related words stem from the root و-ي-ل, meaning \"woe,\" \"grief,\" \"misery,\" or \"destruction,\" and is used as a severe warning or expression of condemnation. The root conveys not only deep sorrow but also a state of ruin or utter loss, typically resulting from wrongdoing or transgression. In the Qur'an, وَيْلٌ serves as a powerful admonition directed at individuals or groups, warning of the devastating outcomes of disbelief or sinful actions. Its usage emphasizes the seriousness of such behaviors and the severe repercussions that await those who persist in them, making it a stark reminder of moral accountability.",
  "4273": "وُجْدٌ and related words stem from the root و-ج-د, with the root verb وَجَدَ meaning \"he found\" or \"he possessed.\" وُجْدٌ means \"wealth,\" \"means,\" or \"ability.\" The connection lies in the state of possessing resources or means, as one who has found or obtained them, directly relating to the root's emphasis on finding or possessing. This term highlights the capacity or means one has, especially in the context of fulfilling obligations.",
  "4274": "وُحُوشٌ and related words stem from the root و-ح-ش, with the root verb وَحَشَ meaning \"he became unsociable\" or \"it was wild.\" وُحُوشٌ is the plural of وَحْشٌ, meaning \"wild beasts\" or \"wild animals.\" The connection lies in the untamed, wild nature of these creatures, directly reflecting the root's emphasis on wildness and lack of domestication. This term highlights the untamed aspects of nature, often symbolizing fear or the unknown.",
  "4275": "وُدٌّ and related words stem from root و-د-د, with the root verb وَدَّ meaning \"he loved\" or \"he desired.\" وُدٌّ means \"love,\" \"affection,\" or \"friendship.\" The connection lies in the mutual feelings of love and goodwill, directly reflecting the root's emphasis on affection. This term often implies reciprocal love or friendship between individuals, highlighting the importance of mutual respect and warmth in relationships.",
  "4276": "وُسْطَى and related words stem from the root و-س-ط, with the root verb وَسَطَ meaning \"he was in the middle.\" وُسْطَى means \"middle,\" \"central,\" or \"most excellent.\" The connection lies in being in the most balanced or ideal position, reflecting the root's emphasis on moderation and excellence. In the Qur'an, it refers to \"الصَّلَاةِ الْوُسْطَى\" (\"the middle prayer\"), signifying its importance and urging believers to maintain diligence in their worship.",
  "4277": "وُسْعٌ and related words stem from the root و-س-ع, with the root verb وَسِعَ meaning \"he was or became ample, spacious, or extensive.\" وُسْعٌ means \"capacity,\" \"ability,\" or \"what is within one's power.\" It refers to the extent of one's capability or what one can bear. The connection lies in measuring one's personal \"spaciousness\" of ability, emphasizing that each is accountable only for what they can manage. In the Qur'an, it denotes that Allah (ﷻ) does not burden a soul beyond its capacity, reflecting divine justice and mercy.",
  "4278": "وُقِفُوا and related words stem from the root و-ق-ف, with the root verb وَقَفَ meaning \"he stood,\" or \"he stopped.\" وُقِفُوا is a passive form meaning \"they were stopped\" or \"they were made to stand.\" The root conveys themes of halting or being restrained, often implying accountability or confrontation. This reflects the root's emphasis on cessation, symbolizing moments of reckoning where one's actions lead to being halted or restricted.",
  "4279": "وُكِّلَ and related words stem from the root و-كـ-ل, with the root verb وَكَـلَ meaning \"he entrusted\" or \"he relied upon.\" وُكِّلَ is a passive form meaning \"he was entrusted\" or \"he was assigned.\" The root conveys themes of delegation, dependence, and appointing a guardian or representative. The connection reflects being given responsibility or being relied upon, aligning with the root's emphasis on trust and delegation. It highlights the transfer of duties to someone deemed capable and trustworthy.",
  "4280": "وُورِيَ and related words stem from the root و-ر-ي, with the root verb وَارَى meaning \"he concealed\" or \"he hid.\" وُورِيَ means \"it was concealed\" or \"it was hidden.\" The connection lies in the state of something being covered or obscured, reflecting the root's emphasis on concealment. This term highlights that certain realities or truths may be hidden from human sight, emphasizing humility and the recognition of divine wisdom.",
  "4281": "وِجْهَةٌ and related words stem from the root و-ج-ه, with the root verb وَجَهَ meaning \"he faced\" or \"he directed.\" وِجْهَةٌ means \"direction,\" \"orientation,\" or \"goal.\" The connection lies in the concept of facing towards a particular place or objective, directly relating to the root's emphasis on facing. This term embodies the idea of having a focus or destination, whether physical or metaphorical, highlighting purpose and intent.",
  "4282": "وِرْدٌ and related words stem from the root و-ر-د, with the root verb وَرَدَ meaning \"he came\" or \"he arrived.\" وِرْدٌ means \"watering place,\" \"place of return,\" or \"daily portion.\" The connection lies in the habitual act of returning to a source of sustenance, embodying the root's emphasis on approach and necessity. In spiritual practice, it can refer to daily recitations or devotions that one consistently returns to for spiritual nourishment.",
  "4283": "وِزْرٌ and related words stem from the root و-ز-ر, with the root verb وَزَرَ meaning \"he carried a burden.\" وِزْرٌ means \"burden,\" often used metaphorically to denote \"sin\" or \"guilt.\" The connection lies in the idea of sins being heavy loads that weigh upon an individual, embodying the root's emphasis on carrying. In the Qur'an, it serves as a reminder of personal responsibility and the consequences that accompany one's actions.",
  "4284": "وِعَاءٌ and related words stem from the root و-ع-ى, with the root verb وَعَى meaning \"he comprehended\" or \"he retained.\" وِعَاءٌ means \"container\" or \"vessel.\" The connection lies in the function of holding and preserving contents, analogous to the mind retaining knowledge. This reflects the root's emphasis on containment and preservation, highlighting the importance of safeguarding valuable information or resources, much like a vessel protects its contents.",
  "4285": "وِفَاقٌ and related words stem from the root و-ف-ق, with the root verb وَفَقَ meaning \"he agreed\" or \"he was suitable.\" وِفَاقٌ means \"in agreement\" or \"in harmony,\" or \"fitting,\" or \"in alignment.\" The connection lies in the state of concord and mutual understanding, reflecting the root's emphasis on compatibility and alignment.",
  "4286": "وِقْرٌ and related words stem from the root و-ق-ر, with the root verb وَقَرَ meaning \"he sat with weight.\" وِقْرٌ translates as \"load\" or \"burden.\" The connection lies in the concept of physical or metaphorical weight that is carried, emphasizing the root's focus on heaviness and substantiality. This term applies to contexts such as clouds bearing water or individuals carrying responsibilities, reflecting the inevitability and impact of bearing significant weight, whether literal or figurative.",
  "4287": "The vocative particle يَا is used to call upon or address someone directly, translated as \"O\" or \"Oh\" in English. It serves to capture attention and is frequently placed before names or titles to signal direct address. In Arabic, يَا is essential for directly engaging individuals or groups, emphasizing the importance or urgency of the communication. In the Qur'an, يَا is used to introduce significant addresses, often preceding calls to prophets, believers, or humanity at large, highlighting the critical nature of the message that follows, and urging immediate reflection or action.",
  "4288": "يابِسٌ and related words stem from the root ي-ب-س, with the root verb يَبِسَ meaning \"it became dry\" or \"it withered.\" يابِسٌ means \"dry\" or \"withered,\" describing something devoid of moisture or vitality. The connection reflects the root's concept of loss of fluidity or freshness, often symbolizing barrenness, lifelessness, or rigidity.",
  "4289": "يَابِسَاتٍ and related words stem from the root ي-ب-س, with the root verb يَبِسَ meaning \"it became dry\" or \"it withered.\" يَابِسَاتٍ means \"dry land\" or \"parched ground,\" emphasizing land as opposed to water. The connection lies in the root's focus on dryness, highlighting a lack of moisture, solidity, and a contrast with fluidity or abundance.",
  "4290": "يَاقُوتٌ and related words stem from the root ي-ق-ت, referring to precious gemstones such as rubies or sapphires, celebrated for their brilliance and purity. While no verb derives from this root, يَاقُوتٌ embodies qualities like beauty, durability, and clarity. In the Qur'an, it describes the radiant beauty of the companions in paradise, comparing them to \"rubies and coral,\" symbolizing their purity and perfection. This metaphor highlights both physical beauty and moral excellence. In classical Arabic literature, يَاقُوتٌ similarly signifies incomparable excellence, reflecting inner value and spiritual brilliance.",
  "4291": "يَأْتَلِ and related words stem from the root أ-ل-و, with the root verb أَلَا meaning \"he fell short\" or \"he neglected to act,\" and آلَىٰ meaning \"he swore an oath.\" يَأْتَلِ means \"he fell short of what was requisite\" or \"he refuses,\" particularly in neglecting a duty, much like how duties arise from oaths. The broader root emphasizes the binding nature of oaths and the decision to refuse or neglect certain responsibilities. The connection highlights that neglecting a duty, whether through an oath or failing to act as required by Allah's (ﷻ) commands, is a significant moral issue.",
  "4292": "يَأْتَمِرُونَ and related words stem from the root أ-م-ر, with the root verb أَمَرَ meaning \"he commanded\" or \"he ordered.\" يَأْتَمِرُونَ translates to \"they consult.\" This word reflects the reciprocal action of giving commands within a group, leading to collective consultation or conspiracy. Depending on the context, it can refer to people consulting together either for beneficial purposes or to plot harm, highlighting the power and impact of collective decision-making. In both cases, the aim is to reach a command or decision to act upon, emphasizing the process of coordinating intentions and actions.",
  "4293": "يَأْجُوجُ stems from the root أ-ج-ج, with the root verb أَجَّ meaning \"it blazed\" or \"burned fiercely.\" يَأْجُوجُ refers to Gog, from the pair Gog and Magog, a people mentioned in the Qur'an associated with chaos and destruction. The root's imagery of intense fire mirrors the overwhelming and fierce nature attributed to Gog, symbolizing their destructive force. In Islamic studies of the 'end times', Gog and Magog are a significant sign of the approaching Day of Judgment, testing humanity’s faith and endurance through severe trials, reflecting the tumultuous challenges they bring.",
  "4294": "يَأْلَمُونَ and related words stem from the root أ-ل-م, with the root verb أَلِمَ meaning \"he felt pain\" or \"he suffered.\" يَأْلَمُونَ means \"they feel pain\" or \"they suffer.\" The root encompasses both physical and emotional suffering, highlighting the depth and continuity of the pain experienced. The connection reflects the ongoing or repeated nature of the suffering, capturing not just the initial sensation but the endurance of distress over time. This ties back to the root's broader meaning of prolonged and intense discomfort, emphasizing the gravity of their pain.",
  "4295": "يَأْلُونَكُمْ and related words stem from the root أ-ل-و, with the root verb أَلَا meaning \"he fell short,\" and آلى meaning \"he swore an oath.\" يَأْلُونَكُمْ means \"they fall short in relation to you.\" The root emphasizes falling short or withholding, suggesting an incomplete effort or restraint. In context, it highlights how actions can be limited or restrained, often due to the binding nature of oaths or commitments. The root connection reflects the idea of incomplete dedication or failure to meet expectations, especially in matters of trust or loyalty.",
  "4296": "يَأْنِ and related words stem from the root أ-ن-ي, with the root verb أَنَىٰ meaning \"it matured,\" \"it became due,\" or \"it reached its time.\" يَأْنِ means \"he comes,\" \"it becomes due,\" or \"it is time.\" The connection lies in the action of approaching the appointed time or maturity, reflecting the root's emphasis on timing and readiness. This term highlights the concept of events unfolding at their proper time, emphasizing patience and the natural order of processes reaching fruition. In the Qur'an, it is used as a reminder that certain moments or realizations are due and should not be delayed.",
  "4297": "يَئُودُ and related words stem from the root أ-و-د, with the root verb أَوِدَ meaning \"it was of itself crooked, curved, or bent.\" يَئُودُ translates as \"it burdened by weight\" or \"it distressed.\" The connection lies in the root’s implication of strain or resistance, as bending or curving under pressure reflects something struggling to maintain its form. In the Qur'an, يَئُودُ conveys the idea that something would be burdened or distressed under a weight too great to bear, emphasizing Allah's (ﷻ) power and effortless ability to sustain all creation without strain.",
  "4298": "يَئُوسٌ and related words stem from the root ي-أ-س, with the root verb يَئِسَ meaning \"he despaired\" or \"he lost hope.\" يَئُوسٌ is an intensive form meaning \"despairing\" or \"extremely hopeless.\" The connection lies in the deep state of despair, reflecting the root's emphasis on hopelessness. It describes someone who is persistently without hope, highlighting a profound lack of optimism or expectation for good.",
  "4299": "يَئِسَ and related words stem from the root ي-أ-س, with the root verb يَئِسَ meaning \"he despaired\" or \"he lost hope.\" The root conveys broader concepts of despair, abandonment, and disconnection from expectations, emphasizing the emotional state of giving up on anticipated outcomes. The connection is direct, embodying the act of losing hope and succumbing to negativity. It reflects a state of emotional surrender, highlighting the root's focus on the absence of optimism and the severing of positive expectations.",
  "4300": "يَبَسٌ and related words stem from the root ي-ب-س, with the root verb يَبِسَ meaning \"it became dry\" or \"it withered.\" يَبَسٌ means \"dryness\" or \"aridity,\" representing a state lacking moisture. The connection embodies the root's emphasis on conditions of drought or deprivation, symbolizing hardship, rigidity, or lack of nourishment.",
  "4301": "يَبُورُ and related words stem from the root ب-و-ر, with the root verb بَارَ meaning \"he perished.\" يَبُورُ means \"he perishes\" or \"it becomes useless,\" conveying the ongoing process of something deteriorating, stagnating, or falling into disuse. The word is often used for actions, markets, or conditions that lose effectiveness, emphasizing a gradual decline into uselessness or failure, where vitality or purpose fades over time.",
  "4302": "يَبِيتُونَ and related words stem from the root ب-ي-ت, with the root verb بَاتَ meaning \"he spent the night,\" or \"he stayed overnight,\" and can also imply actions that occurs \"at night.\" يَبِيتُونَ means \"they spend the night\" or \"they remain overnight,\" referring not only to the physical act of staying but also to the actions or states that occupy a person throughout the night. The root implies purposeful engagement in the night hours, whether in worship, prayer, contemplation, or even planning, highlighting focus and commitment through the quiet and stillness of the night.",
  "4303": "يَبْحَثُ and related words stem from the root ب-ح-ث, with the root verb بَحَثَ meaning \"he searched\" or \"he investigated.\" يَبْحَثُ translates as \"he searches\" or \"he digs,\" referring to an active pursuit of knowledge, discovery, or uncovering something hidden. The connection lies in the act of probing or seeking deeply, whether physically or intellectually, reflecting the root’s essence of inquiry, exploration, and a desire to find or reveal what is concealed.",
  "4304": "يَبْخَسْ and related words stem from the root ب-خ-س, with the root verb بَخَسَ meaning \"he diminished\" or \"he gave short measure.\" يَبْخَسْ translates as \"to diminish\" or \"to reduce,\" specifically referring to depriving someone of their due or rightful portion. The connection lies in the concept of unjust reduction or undervaluing, embodying the root’s essence of withholding what is deserved. This term highlights the injustice of shortchanging, undervaluing, or failing to provide the full measure owed.",
  "4305": "يَتَبَدَّلُ and related words stem from the root ب-د-ل, with the root verb بَدَلَ meaning \"he exchanged\" or \"he replaced.\" The intensified form بَدَّلَ means \"he changed\" or \"he altered,\" suggesting a deliberate transformation, while تَبَدَّلَ means \"he changed himself\" or \"he exchanged\" in a reflexive sense. يَتَبَدَّلُ translates as \"he changes\" or \"he substitutes (for himself),\" emphasizing a personal or self-directed transformation, often involving a shift in one’s own state or condition. The root thus reflects not only external exchange but also the idea of internal change or self-renewal.",
  "4306": "يَتَبَوَّأُ and related words stem from the root ب-و-أ, with the root verb بَاءَ meaning \"he returned\" or \"he withdrew.\" يَتَبَوَّأُ means \"he takes his place\" or \"he settles,\" emphasizing the act of establishing oneself securely in a location, whether physical or symbolic. This root can also imply “returning with something,” often a responsibility or burden. Just as بَاءَ reflects the idea of returning or bearing a responsibility, يَتَبَوَّأُ conveys the sense of purposefully settling oneself, finding stability, relief, and a place of belonging.",
  "4307": "يَتَجَرَّعُ and related words stem from the root ج-ر-ع, with the root verb جَرِعَ meaning \"he swallowed.\" يَتَجَرَّعُ means \"he swallowed in consecutive portions, one time after another,\" conveying reluctance or compulsion. The root reflects the struggle or hesitation involved in swallowing, emphasizing unpleasantness or difficulty. This word captures the experience of consuming something reluctantly or with effort, symbolizing endurance, resistance, or being forced to accept an undesirable situation.",
  "4308": "يَتَجَنَّبُ and related words stem from the root ج-ن-ب, with the root verb جَنَبَ meaning \"he placed at a distance, sent away, or turned aside.\" or \"he moved something to the side.\" يَتَجَنَّبُ means \"he avoids\" or \"he shuns,\" emphasizing a continuous and deliberate act of turning away. The root conveys the idea of creating physical or metaphorical distance, highlighting themes of separation, caution, and self-discipline in avoiding harmful influences or actions.",
  "4309": "يَتَحَاجُّونَ and related words stem from the root ح-ج-ج, with the root verb حَجَّ meaning \"he performed pilgrimage\" or \"he overcame another in an argument, plea, proof, or testimony.\" يَتَحَاجُّونَ means \"they dispute with each other,\" referring to mutual argumentation or debate. The root conveys contention, proof, and challenge, where opposing views are tested against each other. Just as pilgrimage marks a decisive commitment, disputes seek to establish what prevails. Argumentation exposes truth or falsehood, determining accountability and consequences in matters of belief and judgment.",
  "4310": "يَتَحَاكَمُوا and related words stem from the root ح-ك-م, with the root verb حَكَمَ meaning \"he judged\" or \"he governed.\" From this comes حَكَّمَ, meaning \"he appointed as a judge\" or \"he caused someone to judge,\" followed by تَحَاكَمَ, meaning \"he sought judgment\" or \"he engaged in litigation.\" يَتَحَاكَمُوا then means \"they seek judgment\" or \"they litigate,\" reflecting the act of turning to an authority for resolution. This term connects to the root’s broader meanings of judgment, governance, and restraint, emphasizing how rulings establish order by preventing wrongdoing and ensuring justice.",
  "4311": "يَتَخَافَتُونَ and related words stem from the root خ-ف-ت, with the root verb خَفَتَ meaning \"he became silent, quiet, or still,\" or \"he became low in sound or voice.\" تَخَافَتَ means \"he spoke in a low voice with others.\" يَتَخَافَتُونَ means \"they speak to each other in a low voice.\" The root conveys concepts related to silence, quietness, and the reduction of sound. It describes the state of becoming silent or lowering one's voice, as well as actions taken to induce silence or quietness in oneself or others. The connection emphasizes the act of reducing one's volume when speaking, symbolizing secrecy, humility, or attentiveness."
};
